<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Would-Be Virtuosos Vie for Honor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Amateur pianists -- among them a glass  
installer, a hair stylist, a retired school teacher and an 
anesthesiologist -- took the stage for a chance at playing in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Though none of the 32 performers is on a path to a musical  
career, the first International Piano Competition for Outstanding 
Amateurs gave them a chance to perform before a crowd of discerning 
classical music listeners and a dozen or so international jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition for 90 performers from nine countries runs  
through Sunday at Texas Christian University. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Scrimale bowed to the crowd of about 200 and smiled after  
he'd played the last chord. Scrimale said he was shocked that he 
wasn't more scared to be in the spotlight. Until now, the 
43-year-old assistant with a consulting company in Dallas had 
played only for small groups of friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a group of friends in the audience, and that helped,''  
he said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition is sponsored by the Van Cliburn Foundation, the  
same organization that runs the prestigious Van Cliburn 
International Piano Competition every four years. 
</P>
<P>
	The amateur event is open only to those 30 or older who are not  
professional pianists or piano teachers. The main event usually 
includes pianists younger than 30 who are on the path of a musical 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	The top prize at the amateur event is $2,000, regular seats at  
the main Van Cliburn competition and a chance to play with an 
orchestra in Paris sometime before 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges are generally music professors and piano performers.  
</P>
<P>
	Performers were given 10 minutes each to perform whatever they  
wanted for the preliminaries. Fewer than 18 performers will make it 
into the semifinals and finals, which will allow performers more 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Underlying it all is the chance that the event may introduce  
music buffs and piano gurus to an undiscovered talent -- someone 
like Jon Nakamatsu, the German teacher at a San Jose, Calif., high 
school who won the 1997 gold medal at the main Van Cliburn event. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may find the greatest amateur pianist in the world here,''  
said Sevan Melikyan, a spokesman for the Van Cliburn foundation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
