<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Draft Customer Service Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's major airlines today decided  
against announcing a voluntary move that had been aimed at holding 
off more serious mandatory customer-rights directives from 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Greenwald, head of United Airlines, and chairman of a  
trade group representing the country's biggest carriers, said the 
airlines had been ready to announce the plan but decided against it 
at the last moment for reasons he refused to explain. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised an announcement in the near future.  
</P>
<P>
	``The commitment of the airlines to improve customer service is  
real. After all, airline passengers are the heart of our 
business,'' Greenwald told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	One part of the 12-point plan, a draft of which was obtained  
Wednesday by The Associated Press, would have committed airlines to 
meeting customers' essential needs during long, on-aircraft delays. 
That would include making ``every reasonable effort to provide 
food, water, restroom facilities and access to medical treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That commitment stemmed from New Year's travel delays in  
Detroit, when passengers stuck on snowbound planes were held for 
hours in view of the airport terminal, in some cases without access 
to food, water or functioning toilets. Complaints about such 
treatment prompted several bills in the House and Senate this year. 
</P>
<P>
	One such bill would require airlines to pay passengers  
compensation when they are stranded for more than two hours. 
Another would give passengers 48 hours to cancel nonrefundable 
tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest Airlines, the focus for many of the New Year's  
complaints, also was criticized last week by the Transportation 
Department for its handling of the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The heads of the nation's major airlines had been expected to  
announce the plan during a news conference with lawmakers on 
Capitol Hill, but that was postponed Wednesday when last-minute 
glitches arose. Reportedly one carrier balked at some of the 
proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	David Fuscus, spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the  
trade group representing the airlines, said: ``Clearly there has 
been an outcry on this issue. Certainly Congress has been at the 
forefront of it. And we've been talking with members about it and 
ways to do a better job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides better treatment of stranded passengers, the airline  
plan would have publicly committed the airlines to several things 
that have been proposed by Congress and the Clinton administration, 
or which already are the law or are the current policies of some 
carriers. According to the draft, they included: 
</P>
<P>
	--Providing the lowest fare available on telephone reservation  
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	--Notifying customers of known delays, cancellations and  
diversions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Return of checked baggage within 24 hours.  
</P>
<P>
	--Increasing the baggage liability limit from the current $1,250  
per bag. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowing reservations to be held or canceled.  
</P>
<P>
	--Providing prompt ticket refunds.  
</P>
<P>
	--Disclosing airline procedures for accommodating disabled  
passengers or minors traveling alone. 
</P>
<P>
	--Establishing and disclosing policies for all passengers who are  
kept off a flight despite a confirmed reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	--Disclosing in advance aircraft seating plans, rules on  
frequent-flier redemptions and ticket cancellation policies. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ensuring flight partners provide comparable customer service.  
</P>
<P>
	--Assuring that all written complaints are answered within 60  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	The service commitment said the plans would be completed by Dec.  
15 and fully implemented by June 15, 2000. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
