<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 67.76 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened sharply lower today as a strong  
economic report from Japan increased fears that continued growth in 
the U.S. economy may prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 67.76 at 10,622.53, extending a loss of 219 points over the 
previous two sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 8.25 at 1,310.39, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was off 20.99 at 2,498.36. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government said the nation's gross domestic product  
grew 1.9 percent in the first three months of the year -- a larger 
increase than expected, and the first since the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That set off fears that Japanese demand for U.S. goods will  
swell, boosting the domestic economy even further and setting off 
inflationary pressure around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of inflation has prompted the Fed to say it might  
raise interest rates if it determines that higher rates would cool 
off runaway economic growth. Traders are closely watching economic 
reports and signals that could offer a clue to the Fed's next move. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, bank stocks like Chase Manhattan, down 1 1/4 to 72 9/16,  
were mostly lower. Higher interest rates can hurt bank profits as 
lending volume shrinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer fell sharply for a second straight day, losing 4 15/16 to  
100. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration Wednesday restricted the 
use of its antibiotic Trovan. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 91.9 million shares, 
ahead of Wednesday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.80 at 624.48, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.56 at 769.43. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.89 percent as  
investors anticipated the GDP report, which was released after the 
close of trading. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was 
down 0.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1 percent, and 
France's CAC-40 was down 1.1 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
