<DOCNO> APW19990610.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Tinseltown' Subway Line Opens Sat. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Metro Rail Red Line -- the over-budget,  
headache-plagued second installment of the city's subway soap opera 
-- opens this weekend at the corner of Hollywood and Vine. 
</P>
<P>
	The subway station is pure Hollywood -- the ceiling is covered  
with empty film reels, fake palm trees rise to the roof and two 
silent-movie projectors are enshrined as historical artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
	Six months behind schedule, the 4.6-mile subway leg opens  
Saturday. It will create a 19-minute ``Downtown to Tinseltown'' 
line that runs from Union Station to Hollywood and Vine, 
Hollywood's most famous crossroads and now one of the city's 
seedier intersections. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the segment and a smaller addition: $1.74 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	It may be the most-ridiculed transportation project in Southern  
California since Howard Hughes rolled out the Spruce Goose. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-year project was marked by $288 million in cost  
overruns, a federal lawsuit, a fired contractor and angry merchants 
who lost money because three blocks of Hollywood Boulevard were 
closed after a giant sinkhole opened. 
</P>
<P>
	The boulevard itself slipped, cracking sidewalks and forcing the  
removal of several stars from the Hollywood Walk of Fame. Some shop 
owners left. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there is hope the new route will help revitalize  
Hollywood Boulevard, where sidewalks have been repaired, the stars 
are back in place and a stage production of ``The Wizard of Oz'' is 
running at the Pantages Theater, across the street from the new 
station. 
</P>
<P>
	But will Angelenos get out of their cars?  
</P>
<P>
	``People in L.A. are spoiled,'' said David Balmas, 23. ``If my  
car breaks down, that's the only reason I'd use it. In this city, I 
don't think people want to use the subway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Metropolitan Transit Authority predicts the new line will  
more than double weekday boardings (a round-trip is two boardings) 
to about 80,000 by December. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridership on the subway's first leg -- 6.5 miles running west  
from Union Station to the intersection of Wilshire Boulevard and 
Western Avenue -- is estimated at 38,725 weekday boardings. 
</P>
<P>
	A third and final stretch will run from Vine Street to North  
Hollywood. Completion is expected by next year, bringing the total 
mileage of the subway system in America's second-largest city to a 
mere 17.4 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	In comparison, New York City's 722-mile subway system had more  
than a billion fares in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Salvador Mendez, who runs a taco stand steps from the new  
Hollywood station and managed to hang on despite the construction 
problems, said he doesn't expect many new customers from 
underground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody says it's good that it is coming, but I don't  
know,'' Mendez said. ``I don't know if people will ride it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Trinidad Says Vegas Not Neutral Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Felix Trinidad wants more influence  
in the selection of judges for the welterweight unification fight 
against Oscar De La Hoya in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad and his managers also said they want to set aside 3,000  
of the 12,000 tickets for the Sept. 18 championship fight so fellow 
Puerto Ricans can help eliminate any hometown advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my people there,'' the International Boxing Federation  
champion said during a news conference Thursday. ``Every country 
wants to be able to support its champion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad's handlers say they are concerned because Bob Arum, De  
La Hoya's promoter, is based in Las Vegas and De La Hoya is from 
nearby southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight at the Mandalay Bay Hotel must be ``absolutely fair,''  
said Trinidad's manager and father, Felix Trinidad Sr., because it 
will be the biggest match since a disputed March 13 bout between 
Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Boxing fans disgusted by accusations of misconduct by judges in  
the Holyfield-Lewis fight won't pay the $49 pay-per-view fee if 
there are doubts about the fairness, Trinidad Sr. said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Nevada Athletic Commission chairman Elias Ghanem  
has invited both fighters to review lists of possible judges and 
referees and offer suggestions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want you to know that the fight will be fair and that  
Trinidad will have input into selection of the officials,'' he said 
during a conference call Thursday. ``The fight will go on without 
mistakes and without any problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya last fought in Las Vegas on May 22, stopping Oba Carr  
in the 11th round. The city will likely be the site for a 
Holyfield-Lewis rematch in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission will probably choose one judge from the World  
Boxing Council and one from the International Boxing Federation, 
with a third judge from Nevada, Ghanem said. De La Hoya holds the 
WBC belt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can assure the judges that they won't have to do much work,  
since I'm going to win by a knockout,'' Trinidad said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has agreed to fight for a $10.5 million purse -- of which $2  
million will go to promoter Don King -- in addition to $4 for every 
pay-per-view customer over 800,000. De La Hoya will get at least 
$15 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad, who easily stopped Colombian Hugo Pineda before a  
hometown crowd in San Juan on May 29, wants a substantial 
delegation of fans to counter his image as the lesser-known 
fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want Puerto Ricans to witness De La Hoya's death,''  
Trinidad Sr. joked during the news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Arum, however, controls sales of most of the tickets through his  
Top Rank Boxing. A Top Rank spokesman could not immediately be 
reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rico's Secretary of Sports and Recreation, Eric Labrador,  
said he will write letters to Arum and Nevada boxing officials 
urging that some tickets be set aside when sales begin Wednesday. 
Ticket prices will range from $300 to $1,500, according to Top 
Rank. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad is undefeated in 35 fights with 30 knockouts and has  
long sought a fight with De La Hoya, considered the world's top 
welterweight with a 31-0 record and 22 knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighters begin a tour of American cities next week to  
publicize the bout. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:51:01 </DATE_TIME>
