<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Energy Rejects Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group's board of directors  
voted unanimously Thursday to reject a hostile $5.7 billion buyout 
offer from NiSource Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	But a NiSource spokeswoman said the Indiana-based natural gas  
supplier wouldn't immediately abandon its bid, saying the company 
would assess all of its options before making a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're disappointed but not surprised, because this is an  
example of entrenched management refusing to hear their 
shareholders,'' said NiSource spokeswoman Maria Hibbs. ``Columbia 
has sophisticated shareholders who understand the value of their 
investment and they told us clearly they wanted management to meet 
with NiSource.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy's decision underscored the company's position  
that it isn't for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to NiSource chairman and chief executive Gary Neale,  
Columbia Energy chairman, president and CEO Oliver G. Richard III 
said his board concluded that NiSource's offer wasn't in the best 
interests of Columbia Energy and its shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the factors that influenced Columbia Energy was an opinion  
from investment bankers Salomon Smith Barney ``that the proposed 
consideration is inadequate,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your proposal threatens to deprive Columbia shareholders of  
the substantial value that Columbia's existing strategic plan will 
create,'' Richard wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard said Columbia Energy's board was committed to preventing  
another company from taking advantage of a ``current anomaly'' in 
which the Virginia company's stock value doesn't reflect its true 
earnings potential. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy's shares closed Thursday up 18 3/4 cents to $62 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Merrillville, Ind.-based NiSource made an unsolicited  
bid of $68 cash for each share in Columbia Energy. The proposed 
buyout would have made NiSource, the parent company of Northern 
Indiana Public Service Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in Massachusetts, 
one of the nation's biggest natural gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy, based in Herndon, Va., had 1998 revenue of  
nearly $6.6 billion. It is involved in natural gas exploration, 
production, transmission, storage and distribution as well as 
propane sales and electric power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Columbia Energy attempted to buy Pittsburgh-based  
Consolidated Natural Gas. But CNG last month rejected the offer to 
proceed with an already-planned merger with Richmond-based Dominion 
Resources Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Neale had said he hoped shareholder pressure within Columbia  
Energy would force its board to negotiate. At least three 
class-action shareholder lawsuits were filed to get talks going, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Share of NiSource closed down 6 1/4 cents Thursday on the NYSE at  
$27.62 1/2. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks gained on Friday, spurred by the  
announcement a day before that Japan's economy posted robust growth 
in the first quarter of the year. The U.S. dollar was lower against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 237.75  
points, or 1.39 percent, to 17,340.36 at the end of the morning 
session. On Thursday, the average closed up 480.12 points, or 2.89 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 19.78 points, or 1.45 percent, to 1,387.39 
points. The TOPIX was up 25.10 points, or 1.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong stock performance followed the Economic Planning  
Agency's announcement Thursday that the nation's economy grew 1.9 
percent, or 7.9 percent on an annualized basis, in the first 
quarter of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers marked Japan's first expansion after five quarters  
of contraction. The country is struggling with its deepest 
recession since the end of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was lower against the yen  
as traders scrutinized the previous day's surprise market 
intervention by Japan's central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 118.68 yen at late morning, down 0.44 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo and its late New York level of 118.84 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Currency traders said they were assessing what the yen-selling  
action by the Bank of Japan on Thursday afternoon will mean for the 
market's mid-term direction. The intervention followed the 
announcement of new GDP figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials recently have expressed dissatisfaction with  
dollar-yen volatility. The greenback was worth more than 122 yen at 
the beginning of this month, but then dropped as low as 117.63 yen 
after the release of the economic data Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a market estimate, the Bank of Japan spent about $1  
billion in the intervention Thursday, the Nihon Keizai newspaper 
said. The central bank last intervened on Jan. 12 in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies Friday, the euro was traded at 124.62 yen,  
down from 125.11 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond rose to  
1.6800 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.5900 percent, driving 
its price down to 97.60 yen from 98.36 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
