<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 13:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heineken Buys Stake in Brewery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Dutch beer company Heineken NV has agreed to pay  
$919 million in cash for Diageo PLC's majority stake in Spain's 
biggest brewery. 
</P>
<P>
	The British food and drinks conglomerate said Thursday that it  
will earn a profit of $105 million on the sale of its 88 percent 
share in Cruzcampo SA. 
</P>
<P>
	Cruzcampo accounts for a quarter of all beer sold in Spain, the  
third-largest beer market in the European Union. Heineken already 
owns a majority stake in that country's No. 3 brewer, El Aguila. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale requires approval by the European Commission, but  
Diageo spokeswoman Kathryn Partridge said the companies expected to 
satisfy regulatory requirements within eight weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Diageo had received several unsolicited expressions of interest  
in Cruzcampo, said Colin Storm, chief executive of Guinness, 
Diageo's brewing division. 
</P>
<P>
	By selling Cruzcampo, Diageo further streamlines its product  
range to focus on better-selling brands like Guinness Stout and the 
Johnnie Walker and J&AMP;B Scotch whisky labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Diageo also owns the Pillsbury, Haagen-Dazs and Burger King  
brands. It was formed by the merger of Grand Metropolitan and 
Guinness in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Amsterdam-based Heineken is the world's second-largest brewer  
after Anheuser-Busch Inc. of the United States. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 08:13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  14 Pct. of Indonesia Votes Counted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police bolstered security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count fed anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging was again plaguing the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Election officials denied any improprieties, saying they have  
been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in Monday's 
parliamentary election, billed as the country's most democratic 
vote in 44 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Unofficial results released to journalists showed that just 14  
percent of the votes had been tabulated by this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Local authorities had been given the right to redo the voting in  
some provinces where there had been complaints about 
irregularities, said Rudini, head of the General Elections 
Commission. Rudini, like many Indonesians, uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle, headed by  
opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri, maintained its lead with 
35 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling Golkar Party, which languished in pre-election  
opinion polls, moved into second place with just under 21 percent. 
The National Awakening Party of Abdurrahman Wahid, head of 
Indonesia's largest Islamic group, was third with 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, 48 parties fielded candidates.  
</P>
<P>
	International observers, including former President Carter, said  
lingering delays could erase public trust in Indonesia's fledgling 
democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Television stations ran public-service advertisements to explain  
the count and the reasons for the delays. 
</P>
<P>
	To prevent unrest, police shifted security forces to potential  
rallying points in the capital, including the General Elections 
Commission headquarters and the Hotel Aryaduta, where the votes are 
being tabulated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope parties could restrain themselves from going to the  
streets to celebrate victory or to protest results,'' said Jakarta 
police spokesman Lt. Col. Zairuni Lubis. 
</P>
<P>
	Hank Valentino of the Washington-based International Foundation  
for Election Systems, which has been helping in the election, said 
today he believed from the start it would take at least a week to 
tabulate the results. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because fishy things happened in the past doesn't mean  
they're happening now,'' Valentino said. ``It's different this 
time. In the past, they knew the results before the election 
started. Now they're taking the time to do it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rudini said he could not predict when a final result would be  
available. 
</P>
<P>
	He blamed the delays on slow and meticulous work by workers  
processing ballots in tens of thousands of villages. The delays 
were inevitable, he said, because the election was set up in three 
months, compared with three years in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people in Indonesia are impatient because this is the  
first time that we implemented a general election like this -- more 
democratic, more open and more fair,'' said Rudini, who uses only 
one name like many Indonesians. 
</P>
<P>
	The election for 462 seats in Parliament was the first step  
toward selecting a president. The new legislators will join 38 
representatives of the powerful military and 200 government 
appointees to choose a head of state in five months. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesians last voted in a free election in 1955. Monday's  
ballot was held a year after student protests and deadly riots 
forced authoritarian President Suharto to quit after 32 years in 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	During Suharto's era, elections were tightly controlled and his  
Golkar Party always won landslide victories, largely through 
vote-rigging and buying. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0022 </DOCNO>
