<DOCNO> APW19990610.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 02:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outrage Over Sex Abuse Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The American Psychological Association will  
weigh the potential consequences of publishing research after 
criticism of a study that concluded the long-term effects of child 
sexual abuse are not as serious as many believe. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, which concluded that scientists should classify sex  
between adults and children depending on the ``willingness'' and 
age of the child, was published last July in the APA's 
Psychological Bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
	It has become the target of groups such as the Christian  
Coalition and the Family Research Council, which said it plans to 
disrupt the APA's annual meeting in August in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the study could be used to legitimize pedophilia.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've never, ever had a reaction like this,'' said Raymond  
Fowler, chief executive officer of the Washington-based 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The APA, which has been publishing journals for 106 years, said  
it will now consider the ``social policy implications'' of research 
it publishes. It represents 159,000 clinicians, researchers and 
educators. 
</P>
<P>
	The study -- a review of 59 other studies involving college  
students who had been sexually abused before the age of 18 -- 
concluded that lasting negative effects from the abuse were 
uncommon for men and present in only a minority of women. 
</P>
<P>
	Child sexual abuse ``does not cause intense harm on a pervasive  
basis regardless of gender in the college population,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-author Robert Bauserman, an AIDS prevention researcher in  
Maryland, said the article was written for scientists and he never 
expected it to be discussed in the popular media. Another author, 
Temple University psychology professor Bruce Rind, said researchers 
were trying to strike a balance between the total neglect of child 
abuse before 1970 and what they saw as exaggeration of the problem 
after 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Fowler said the APA should have given more thought to how the  
study would be received. It could have been presented with an 
introduction outlining the APA's stance against child abuse or 
paired with an article with a different viewpoint. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
