<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FastShip Develops Speedy Freighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Plans for a fleet of jet-powered, oceangoing  
cargo ships moved a step closer to fruition with an agreement 
Thursday for the construction of the first four vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	FastShip Inc. hopes to begin service between Philadelphia and  
Cherbourg, France, in 2003, with ships that cross the ocean at up 
to 38 knots, or almost 44 mph, more than twice as fast as 
conventional freighters. 
</P>
<P>
	FastShip announced a preliminary agreement with National Steel  
and Shipbuilding Co., and talks are under way on the construction 
of up to five additional high-speed vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, FastShip, which has yet to transport any goods since its  
formation in 1994, will have to raise about $1 billion to foot the 
bill. It earlier hired J.P. Morgan Securities Inc. of New York to 
help raise the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will compete closely to air freights,'' said Roland K.  
Bullard II, the president of Philadelphia-based FastShip. ``We 
represent a whole new mode and choice for the consumer. We all know 
the premium is on speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bullard said the ship should be able to turn today's standard  
14-21 day trans-Atlantic crossing for cargo into a seven-day trip. 
</P>
<P>
	FastShip will target as customers makers of ``high-end,  
time-sensitive'' products such as computer chips, auto parts and 
perishable farm products at transportation costs as much as 75 
percent less than rates for air freight, spokesman Thomas Beck 
said. The company's rates have not been set yet, but are expected 
to be closer to conventional sea cargo rates than to air rates. 
</P>
<P>
	That could lower prices on goods such as computers, for example.  
Microchips would get to their destination faster for assembly into 
computers in a highly competitive industry, allowing companies to 
produce them faster, Beck said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime we introduce more competition, it would be welcome.  
There will be more opportunities to serve shippers in a faster 
manner,'' said Robert Voltmann, of the Transportation 
Intermediaries Association in Alexandria, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a continuance of a trend more in international trade,''  
he added. ``The faster you move a product, the more you can reduce 
inventory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ships will be able to power through the Atlantic's rough  
seas using five modified jet aircraft engines powering water jets 
instead of the conventional propellers, Bullard said. A patented 
hull shape also helps speed up the journey. 
</P>
<P>
	During the roughest conditions, conventional ships must slow  
down to about 14 to 20 knots to safely cross between North America 
and Europe. FastShip's fleet will be smaller than the average 
conventional cargo ship, but will be able to do twice as many runs, 
the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are moving in a different direction from the megaship,''  
Beck said. ``We are not competing on costs, we will compete on 
service. We will be fast, frequent and reliable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bullard called Philadelphia the ideal North American hub for his  
service because 60 percent of the U.S. gross national product is 
generated within 350 miles of the city's port -- less than a day's 
journey by truck or rail. 
</P>
<P>
	The FastShip technology was developed partly using a $7 million  
investment by the Delaware River Port Authority. The authority has 
also promised to finance a new waterfront terminal for FastShip, 
which could cost up to $74.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to forging a long-term relationship ... that  
combines our shipbuilding expertise with FastShip's technology and 
patents,'' NASSCO president Richard H. Voltman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
