<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McGovern, Neuharth Cross Home State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OACOMA, S.D. (AP) -- Former Sen. George McGovern felt right at  
home when he stopped for lunch at a cafe during a drive across 
South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've done that a thousand times,'' the 1972 presidential  
candidate said of the small town meeting-and-greeting. 
</P>
<P>
	McGovern's nostalgic visit to Main Street came during a two-day  
trip with longtime writer and news executive Al Neuharth, the 
former chairman of Gannett Co. Inc., who also grew up in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsman and the newsmaker reminisced about old times and old  
friends as they rode in a bus outfitted with easy chairs, 
telephones and televisions. After leaving Rapid City, they visited 
the Badlands, a wild horse ranch and the Missouri River. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip was part of NewsCapade, a traveling version of the  
Newseum in Arlington, Va., that is designed to give people a better 
understanding of the news media. The exhibit will visit all 50 
states in the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Neuharth, who has known McGovern for more than 40 years, invited  
the former Democratic senator to ride with him on the South Dakota 
leg of the tour. The state remains a touchstone for both men. 
</P>
<P>
	Neuharth said he drives through South Dakota twice a year, in  
the spring and fall, to get a sense of what people are doing and 
thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	McGovern, who is now U.S. representative to the United Nations  
Food and Agriculture Organization in Rome, said he visits the state 
at least four times a year. He expects to return more often because 
Dakota Wesleyan University in Mitchell, where McGovern once taught, 
is planning to build a library in his honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been almost 20 years since I've toured the state, and  
this was an opportunity to do it with somebody else driving,'' 
McGovern said. ``It's nice to be able to come back and look at it 
under more relaxed circumstances.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
