<HEADLINE> BP Amoco To Sell Canada Oil Lands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- BP Amoco PLC is putting its conventional  
and heavy oil properties in Canada up for sale so the company can 
focus on its Canadian gas and petrochemicals businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The global oil company said Thursday the properties represent  
about 60,000 barrels of oil equivalent a day, nearly a third of its 
total Canadian production. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision will affect the jobs of about 250 employees in the  
field and at the Calgary head office of its Canadian subsidiary, BP 
Amoco Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to be the lowest cost producer in Canada in our  
natural gas, natural gas liquids and chemicals operations,'' said 
Joseph Bryant, regional president of BP Amoco in Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco has been moving to cut costs and streamline operations  
since British Petroleum bought Chicago-based Amoco Corp. last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Amoco Canada recently cut 275 jobs, mostly at its Calgary head  
office, because of low world oil prices. The cuts left Amoco Canada 
with about 1,800 employees in the production of conventional and 
heavy oil, natural gas and petrochemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	BP Amoco said it expects to receive bids and complete  
transactions for its Canadian oil properties throughout the third 
and fourth quarters this year. While it will try to sell the 
properties individually, the company said it will consider bigger 
offers for all the properties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
