<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sydney Olympic Panel Denies Firings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The head of Sydney's Olympic Games  
organizing committee denied media reports Friday that some Olympic 
staff had been fired due to cost-cutting measures. 
</P>
<P>
	A Sydney radio report Friday said morale within SOCOG was at an  
``all-time low'' with the torch relay committee, community 
relations group and the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
program reported to be hardest hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reports that there are sackings in SOCOG are incorrect,''  
chief executive Sandy Hollway said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the organization absorbs the budget cuts recently approved  
by the SOCOG board it is inevitable that there will need to be a 
reassignment of resources from some parts of the organization to 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only 22 staff (out of a total of nearly 1,000) will need to be  
reassigned to other programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hollway said he had given reassurances that SOCOG staff who were  
reassigned should not fear for their jobs, and instead the 
organization intends to double its staff between now and September 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``SOCOG is scheduled to take on another 1,000 people between now  
and the Games,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The staff who are being reassigned are people SOCOG wants to  
keep. We can't afford to lose good people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
