<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Raid Japanese Bank HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Investigators raided the headquarters of a failed  
Japanese bank today, seeking evidence that its former management 
concealed bad loans and paid illegal dividends. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors, metropolitan police and securities and exchange  
officials searched the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd.'s Tokyo 
head office, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will fully comply with the searches,'' LTCB said in a  
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators also raided the home of former LTCB President  
Katsunobu Onogi, 63, the Kyodo News agency and national broadcaster 
NHK reported. 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB, once one of Japan's most prominent banks, was nationalized  
last year after being declared insolvent. Prosecutors have 
reportedly summoned former top executives for questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors and police refused to comment on the investigation.  
NHK showed footage of agents wearing business suits filing into the 
bank's headquarters and Onogi's Tokyo home today. 
</P>
<P>
	Onogi and the two other executives are suspected of telling  
employees to falsify the bank's securities reports to coverup the 
actual amount of its bad loans, reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports said Onogi ``forced'' other bank directors to  
consent to paying dividends totaling $58.7 million for fiscal 1997, 
even though the bank had in fact suffered large losses. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay the dividends, the executives allegedly approved a scheme  
to make losses appear less than they actually were, media reports 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB became the first Japanese bank nationalized since the end  
of World War II after authorities determined it had liabilities 
exceeding assets by about $2.81 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The current management has filed a criminal complaint with  
police and prosecutors accusing former executives of engaging in 
illegal business practices. 
</P>
<P>
	LTCB was founded in 1952. Onogi, who assumed the presidency in  
April 1995, resigned last September to take responsibility for the 
bank's failing business. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
