<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Recovers, Japan Stocks Jump / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar recovered much of its early losses  
against the yen today on rumors that Japan's central bank 
intervened to stem the dollar's slide. Japanese stocks jumped on 
optimism that the nation's economic recovery was picking up. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.12 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.26  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level 
of 118.93 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average surged 480.12  
points, or 2.89 percent, closing the day's trading at 17,102.62 
points. On Wednesday, the average closed up 59.58 points, or 0.04 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei was its highest closing level today since May 6, when  
the index finished at 17,300.61. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Tokyo stock market closed, the Economic Planning  
Agency reported that the economy grew 1.9 percent in the 
January-March quarter over the last quarter of 1998, marking the 
first expansion after five quarters of contraction. 
</P>
<P>
	GDP is the measure of all goods and services produced in a  
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar dropped as low as 117.63 yen at  
one point as the strong economic indicator prompted yen-buying. 
</P>
<P>
	But the greenback later recouped much of its early losses after  
rumors that the Bank of Japan was purchasing the U.S. currency to 
stem the yen's rally, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan does not customarily comment on its market  
intervention activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 117.63 yen and 119.50 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.11 yen, up from  
124.88 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices surged noticeably in the afternoon as  
investors waited for the release of the growth figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth was largely due to increased public works spending  
and other stimulus steps by the government, which has earmarked 
more than half a trillion dollars in this year's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said, however, that market gains on the latest news may  
be relatively short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outlook is still unclear for July through September and  
then through December. Private sector demand has yet to show a 
definitive recovery,'' said Masaaki Higashida, deputy general 
manager of the investment information and services department at 
Nomura Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 25.10 points, or 1.87 percent, to 1,367.61 
points. The TOPIX was up 3.37 points, or 0.03 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was fairly heavy with an estimated 712 million shares  
changing hands on the exchange's first section, compared with 
Wednesday's turnover of 490 million shares. Advancing issues 
outnumbered retreaters 992 to 233, with 86 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond rose to  
1.6250 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.5750 percent, driving 
its price down to 98.06 yen from 98.48 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
