<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 09:00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Macarchuk Named Stony Brook Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nick Macarchuk, the coach at Fordham for 12  
years, was hired today to lead Stony Brook into its first season of 
major college basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	The school announced at a news conference that Macarchuk had  
signed a five-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Stony Brook failed to renew the contract of Bernard Tomlin, who  
has coached the Seawolves the last 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Macarchuk had a year remaining on his contract with Fordham.  
</P>
<P>
	Davidson coach Bob McKillop, a friend of Stony Brook athletic  
director Richard Laskowski, was pursued for the job, but decided 
last month to stay with the North Carolina school, where he's 
coached for 10 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Macarchuk was 161-192 at Fordham, but hasn't had a winning  
record since the Rams were 18-13 and played in the NCAA tournament 
in 1992. His last Fordham team was 12-15, the seventh straight 
losing record for the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordham moved to the Atlantic 10 Conference in 1995 and has had  
little success, losing 80 of 108 games in four seasons. But 
Macarchuk made progress last season, with the 12 victories matching 
the combined total of the previous two years. He was honored as 
A-10 coach of the year for the turnaround. 
</P>
<P>
	Macarchuk was 149-128 in 10 seasons at Canisius before taking  
over at Fordham in 1987-88. His first team was 18-15 and played in 
the NIT. His best teams were 20-13 in 1990 and 25-8 in 1991, and 
both played in the NIT. The 1992 team played in the NCAA tournament 
by virtue of winning the Patriot League postseason tournament. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
