<DOCNO> APW19990610.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 02:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Cops Probe Radio Jamming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A white police sergeant has been cleared of  
suspicion he deliberately jammed the radio transmissions of a black 
lieutenant who was directing officers during the first lady's visit 
last week, according to a published report. 
</P>
<P>
	Police sources told The Boston Globe that an internal  
investigation showed that Sgt. Michael R. Donovan used his radio 
just once, for about two seconds, during the hour Friday that Lt. 
Valimore Williams said his radio was jammed. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was using a different channel to direct officers on  
duty and that channel may have been jammed unintentionally by other 
officers, the Globe reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	No problems were reported during Hillary Rodham Clinton's visit.  
</P>
<P>
	Radio transmissions can be jammed, intentionally or  
unintentionally, when several officers are sharing the same 
frequency. Williams himself said Friday's incident ``could be a 
coincidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation marks the second time this year that Boston  
police investigators have cleared a white police officer of charges 
of harassment against Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams found a noose made of police tape on his motorcycle in  
April and has filed a $1.2 million discrimination complaint against 
the Boston Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Donovan was the supervisor of the officer who admitted making  
the noose. An internal investigation concluded the noose was part 
of a prank by both white and black subordinate officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Donovan was not in his office Wednesday and could not be reached  
for comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees-Marlins 'Showdown' Looms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- This weekend's series between the New York Yankees  
and Florida Marlins could provide a clue about what will happen in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, the winner of the series has gone on to win the World  
Series each of the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	That's how Florida's publicity staff is advertising the  
three-game showdown beginning Friday. The hype is tongue-in-cheek 
because the Marlins have the National League's worst record, but 
they're feeling frisky after winning seven of the past eight games 
to climb within 14 victories of .500. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to be intimidated just because we're playing  
the New York Yankees,'' rookie outfielder Bruce Aven said. ``To us, 
it's just another team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since May 6, the surging Marlins have actually played better  
than the Yankees. Florida is 17-15 since then, while the defending 
World Series champs are 15-15. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida spotted the Baltimore Orioles $60 million in payroll  
this week, then won two of three games. The Marlins have baseball's 
best interleague record at 25-12, including 5-1 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookies Aven, Preston Wilson, Alex Gonzalez, Mike Lowell and  
Kevin Millar have all hit well during the Marlins' recent surge, as 
have newcomer Tim Hyers and two young pitchers, Ryan Dempster and 
closer Matt Mantei. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got great talent,'' said former Marlin Jeff Conine,  
now with the Orioles. ``They've got a bunch of young players that 
are very talented. They're on a plan right now. They're building 
for the long term and they've got a good foundation to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins' potential has stirred little excitement so far in  
Miami, where fans remain miffed about the dismantling of the 1997 
World Series champions. Florida's average attendance of 17,269 
ranks ahead of only Montreal in the NL. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend's series will draw the biggest crowds since opening  
day, perhaps reaching 40,000 Friday and Saturday, but many fans 
will be New York transplants cheering for the Yankees. The Marlins 
are accustomed to similar treatment when the Atlanta Braves and New 
York Mets come to town. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans came out opening day, and since then they come out to  
see who we play against,'' Wilson said. ``Whatever. People are 
fickle. People come to see a winner. If the city doesn't recognize 
this team as a potential winner, they're not going to support it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
