<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Mayor Announces Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Mayor Richard Arrington is being accused  
of trying to handpick his successor by stepping down early and 
allowing the candidate he supports to take the job until the 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrington, the city's top elected official for 20 years,  
announced Tuesday he will resign July 19. City Council President 
William Bell, whom Arrington supports in the Oct. 12 election, will 
become interim mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Councilman Bernard Kincaid, another mayoral hopeful, complained:  
``It's similar to a remote-control vehicle, with Arrington holding 
the controls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arrington, Birmingham's first black mayor, is completing his  
fifth term. Had he quit before July 15, a special election would 
have been called. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
