<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Sun-Times Promotes Winnecke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Sun-Times has named Joycelyn Winnecke  
as managing editor. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced in Thursday's editions by Nigel  
Wade, editor in chief. 
</P>
<P>
	Winnecke, 37, came to the Sun-Times five years ago as deputy  
metro editor and most recently was executive news editor. She began 
her newspaper career writing obituaries in her hometown for The 
Evansville (Ind.) Courier and Press. She later was a reporter for 
the Washington bureau of Scripps Howard and city editor of The 
Indianapolis Star. 
</P>
<P>
	The position of Sun-Times managing editor had been vacant for  
three years. Larry Green, executive editor, became vice president 
of advertising and marketing on May 26. The position of executive 
editor eventually will be filled, Winnecke said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sun-Times is owned by Hollinger International, whose  
newspapers include the Daily Telegraph in London, The Ottawa 
Citizen in Canada and the Jerusalem Post in Israel. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
