<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Woman's Sunburn Death Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- An elderly Alzheimer's patient was left on a  
nursing home patio in the broiling Arizona sun long enough to 
suffer a sunburn that killed her. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Miles, 86, a patient at the SunRise Thunderbird Care and  
Rehabilitation Center, died Sunday from burns she suffered May 18 
to her feet, legs, arms and neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors had amputated her legs in trying to save her.  
Investigators are trying to determine whether workers at the 
nursing home are culpable in the death. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers told state investigators that Miles was on the patio for  
an hour at most. Doctors said it would take at least several hours 
of sun exposure to get the third-degree burns she suffered, 
according to police. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Health Services is investigating how long  
Miles actually was in the sun and whether she was taking any drugs 
that would have made her more sensitive to light. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursing home's parent company, New Mexico-based Sun  
Healthcare Group, expressed sympathy for Miles' family and pledged 
to cooperate with the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``A part of what we have to do is deal with incidents like  
this,'' company spokeswoman Karen Gilliland told The Arizona 
Republic on Wednesday. ``It's important not to jump to conclusions 
when you hear about things. It's always more complicated than it 
seems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate incident, the Arizona Department of Health  
Services is looking into beatings suffered by two men at the 
nursing home during the past month. And a probe into the November 
death of another patient who had severe bedsores could not find 
enough evidence to reach a conclusion, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The department investigated at least 16 other complaints of  
abuse or substandard care at the facility in the past 18 months, 
records show. Investigators ruled that one complaint was unfounded, 
referred one case of verbal abuse of patients to prosecutors and 
could not find enough evidence to rule on the other 14 complaints. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
