<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> News Corp. Suspends Talks on Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- News Ltd., the Australian arm of media baron  
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., has suspended talks about selling its 
50 percent stake in the Australian airline And sett. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore Airlines said today it was disappointed by the  
decision, saying it ``had looked forward to part-ownership in the 
Australian airline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	News Ltd. had agreed in March to sell its interest in Ansett to  
Singapore Airlines for $315 million, but Air New Zealand had a 
preemptive right to buy the stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Air New Zealand owns the remaining 50 percent of Ansett, and its  
chairman Selwyn Cushing has expressed a preference for buying the 
rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore Airlines said it met with Air New Zealand several  
times to discuss the waiver of this right. 
</P>
<P>
	News Corp. said it was disappointed that Singapore Airlines and  
Air New Zealand had not resolved issues concerning Ansett. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ansett transaction has become more complex since New  
Zealand's Brierley Investments Ltd. said last week it would 
increase its stake in Air New Zealand to as much as 60 percent from 
47 percent. Cushing also is chairman of Brierley. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have speculated that Brierly is preparing to back Air  
New Zealand's move to take 100 percent control of Ansett, with a 
view to later selling part of the enlarged company to Singapore 
Airlines. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
