<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marichal Considering Resigning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Baseball Hall of Famer  
Juan Marichal, the Dominican Republic's sports minister, says he 
has considered resigning over corruption accusations but will stay 
out of a sense of duty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that Juan Marichal was not the candidate to  
occupy this position and there are some who want me to immediately 
leave this post to which I was named,'' Marichal was quoted as 
saying in Listin Diario newspaper Thursday, implying he never 
wanted the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, The Nation newspaper quoted the Dominican  
Solicitor General's office as saying the Baseball Hall of Fame in 
Cooperstown, N.Y., has asked investigators for more information 
about the case. Officials at the Hall of Fame, which inducted 
Marichal in 1983, were not immediately available to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Marichal refused to appear before a prosecutor to  
respond to allegations of fraud involving millions of dollars, 
saying he was not properly summoned. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is investigating accusations that administrators  
skimmed millions through the purchase of sports equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal has resisted an order to appear before the head of the  
Corruption Prevention Department on May 26 to respond to 
allegations of fraud and corruption. Prosecutor Mariano German 
Mejia said Marichal could face charges if he does not comply. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody is above the law, and all we want is for Marichal to  
answer the allegations. He is a sensible man and I am sure that he 
will appear,'' German said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal, 64, played 16 seasons in the majors, most with the San  
Francisco Giants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
