<DOCNO> APW19990610.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 07:50:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PAC Money Rises for Credit Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As credit unions urged Congress to allow them  
to expand membership, they boosted their campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Their political action committee, the Credit Union Legislative  
Action Council, contributed $1 million to congressional candidates 
for the last election, according to a Federal Election Commission 
report released Wednesday. That's $397,645 more than the PAC spent 
during the 1996 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit unions also spent more than $2 million on lobbying in  
1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress was prodded to act after the Supreme Court ruled that  
corporate credit unions could not accept outside members. Lawmakers 
passed legislation last summer overturning the court decision and 
rejecting an argument that credit unions that wanted to expand 
their membership should be subject to the same taxes and 
regulations as banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The legislation gave us an opportunity to promote political  
action among credit union members,'' said Richard Gose, the Credit 
Union National Association's vice president for political action. 
``Contributions do nothing more than help a group have access and 
be more visible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC said overall PAC contributions to candidates rose  
slightly, from $217.8 million in 1995-96 to $219.9 million in 
1997-98. More than three-fourths of the money went to incumbents, 
up from two-thirds in 1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	The most generous PAC was the Realtors, which gave $2.5 million  
in 1997-98. The Realtors supported legislation making it easier for 
private property owners to sue for the loss of their land due to 
government regulations, opposed efforts to eliminate the home 
mortgage interest tax deduction and backed a bill to protect real 
estate data on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our membership is very engaged in public policy,'' said Lee  
Verstandig, the Realtors' senior vice president for government 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest increase in contributions to candidates was recorded  
by Bell Atlantic Corp., which is seeking government approval to 
merge with GTE and to offer long-distance phone service. Bell 
Atlantic more than doubled its political action committee 
contributions between 1996 and 1998, from $278,464 to $783,495. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Susan Butta said the increase in PAC giving  
reflected the 1997 merger of Bell Atlantic and Nynex, which 
combined their PACs. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislation was introduced in the last Congress to make it  
easier for Bell Atlantic and the other local telephone companies to 
enter the long-distance market. In addition, the Senate Commerce 
Committee held hearings on the 1996 telecommunications deregulation 
law. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
