<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Announces Halt to Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO today announced a suspension of  
its airstrikes against Yugoslavia after verifying the withdrawal of 
Serb forces was underway. ``A few moments ago I instructed Gen. 
Wesley Clark to suspend NATO's air operations,'' said NATO 
Secretary General Javier Solana. The withdrawal of Yugoslav 
security forces from Kosovo is taking place in accordance with the 
peace implementation deal worked out between NATO and Serb forces 
last night, Solana added. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Forces Begin Leaving Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes,  
Yugoslav convoys began withdrawing from Kosovo today as part of a 
peace deal signed by Serbian and Western generals to end the 
Balkans conflict. Soldiers in the convoy smiled and flashed the 
three-fingered Serb sign denoting unity. NATO warplanes flew 
overhead monitoring the noon (7 a.m. EDT) pullout, which began 
several hours later than the allies had expected. Once NATO gives 
the order, British and French troops will be the first to enter 
Kosovo as part of the peacekeeping force. ``It looks as if we're in 
the end game,'' British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Jump by 14,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits shot up last week to the highest level since 
early January. The Labor Department reported today that 323,000 
Americans filed new claims for jobless benefits last week, up by 
14,000 from the previous week. The increase was unexpected. 
Analysts had expected the number of claims for unemployment 
benefits to inch down slightly. Even with the increase in jobless 
claims, the number of Americans putting in for unemployment 
benefits is still low. 

</P>
<P>
	Hillary Clinton Seeks N.Y. Home  
</P>
<P>
	BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- The morning after she faced protesters  
with ``carpetbagger go home'' signs, could-be Senate candidate 
Hillary Rodham Clinton said today she hasn't yet secured a New York 
residence. ``I think a Democrat will win this Senate race and I'm 
looking forward to going out and listening to New Yorkers and just 
having a good time,'' Mrs. Clinton told NBC. She took a jab at 
Republicans, saying the way they've handled gun control legislation 
shows the Democratic Party ``is much more in touch with the 
mainstream -- not only of America, but particularly of New York.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Antimissile Missile Hits Target  
</P>
<P>
	WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) -- An expensive experimental  
antimissile missile did today what it had been unable to do on six 
previous attempts -- hit a flying target. A white puff of smoke in 
the southern New Mexico sky marked where the Army's Theater 
High-Altitude Area Defense, or THAAD, missile struck a target 
missile. Before today, the $3.9 billion system had missed its 
target on six consecutive attempts. 

</P>
<P>
	14 Pct. of Indonesia Votes Counted  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police bolstered security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count fed anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging was again plaguing the 
country. Election officials deny any improprieties, saying they 
have been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in Monday's 
parliamentary election. Unofficial results released to journalists 
showed that just 14 percent of the votes had been tabulated by this 
afternoon. The Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle, headed by 
opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri, maintains its lead with 35 
percent of the vote. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Stresses Loyalty To Church  
</P>
<P>
	SIEDLCE, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II stressed loyalty to the  
church today and warned young people against falling victim to 
``travesties of religion, or to manipulations of the truth.'' At a 
Mass attended by thousands of Roman Catholics and Eastern rite 
Catholics from Belarus, Ukraine and Russia, the pontiff called for 
people to follow the example of 13 martyrs slain in Pratulin in 
1874 for resisting conversion to Orthodox Christianity. ```How 
sweet it is to die for the faith.' These were their last words,'' 
John Paul said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 46; Nasdaq Falls 20  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened lower with the Dow  
Jones industrial average down 46 points in today's early going. 
Losers on the New York Stock Exchange hold a 9-4 lead over gainers. 
The Nasdaq Composite Index is down 20 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Bob Knight Investigated in Assault  
</P>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight is  
being investigated for assaulting a fellow patron at a restaurant, 
Monroe County Prosecutor Carl Salzmann said today. No charges have 
been filed, but Knight may face a misdemeanor charge of battery, 
which carries a maximum penalty of six months in jail and a $5,000 
fine. Salzmann said the 38-year-old man who claims he was assaulted 
also could be charged with provocation. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
