<DOCNO> APW19990610.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ala. Judges Nation's Highest Paid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A new law will make many of Alabama's  
judges the highest paid in the nation, with state Supreme Court pay 
surpassing that of the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The law will add pay hikes over three years, boosting trial  
judges with 20 years of experience to $139,966. A veteran Supreme 
Court chief justice will get $191,284, far ahead of the chief 
justice of the U.S. Supreme Court at $175,400. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Don Siegelman let the pay raises become law Wednesday  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I looked at this as a measure that affected the safety of our  
citizens. It is important to attract and retain judges and 
prosecutors with experience and ability,'' he said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The raises passed the Legislature with bipartisan support.  
Republican Lt. Gov. Steve Windom, who has been trying to change 
Alabama's reputation for huge punitive damage verdicts, said higher 
salaries are need to get high-quality attorneys to run for 
judgeships. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at us nationally, the biggest eyesore we've had  
has been our judicial system,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law ends the practice of paying judges a flat amount and  
goes to a system based on years of service. It also phases out 
extra salaries that some county governments gave to judges. 
</P>
<P>
	A spring survey of judicial salaries by the National Center for  
State Courts in Williamsburg, Va., shows the pay raises will make 
Alabama's Supreme Court the highest paid in the country. Circuit 
judges with 20 years of experience will be the highest paid trial 
court judges in the country, while circuit judges with no 
experience will be the seventh highest-paid. 
</P>
<P>
	To pay for the increases, the Legislature raised court fees,  
including adding $30 to speeding tickets and other traffic 
offenses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
