<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Prices Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian shares finished mostly higher Thursday,  
with the big Tokyo market surging ahead despite concerns that U.S. 
interest rates might be on the way up. Prices in Seoul jumped more 
than 6 percent to a nearly two-year high. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong blue chips bucked the trend, retreating modestly late  
in the session, despite an earlier rally on news that mainland 
China had trimmed interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, shares soared 2.9 percent to their highest level in a  
month on optimism that Japan's economy might finally be recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 480.12 points to  
17,102.62. It was the Nikkei's highest finish since May 6, when it 
closed at 17,300.61. On Wednesday, the Nikkei had been virtually 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the U.S. dollar bounced back from recent  
losses against the Japanese yen, amid rumors that the Japanese 
central bank was intervening to prop up the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.12 yen in the late afternoon, down 0.26  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo but above its late New York level 
of 118.93 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong blue chip stocks finished lower, as late selling in  
the futures market wiped out big early gains that followed lower 
interest rates in mainland China. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index fell 35.21 points, or 0.3 percent, to  
12,839.21 on Asia's second-biggest exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	An early rally, led by companies with close links to China, had  
pushed the Hang Seng up by almost 2 percent, following a lackluster 
session on Wednesday in which the index had finished with a tiny 
gain. 
</P>
<P>
	But foreign investors began selling Hong Kong stock futures late  
in the day, amid concerns that the United States might raise 
interest rates, forcing Hong Kong to follow suit. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, Korean blue chips soared 6.5 percent, with the Kospi  
index up 52.6 points at 856.06, its highest close in almost two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korean shares overcame early losses as the rise by the  
Japanese yen spread enthusiasm through the Seoul market. 
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, shares rallied as foreign institutional investors  
poured cash into the market. The blue chip Straits Times Index rose 
23.46 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,030.00. 
</P>
<P>
	The peaceful elections in neighboring Indonesia has fueled  
recent positive sentiment on the Singapore exchange, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA -- Indonesian shares fell amid concern about the slow  
vote count from Monday's elections. The JSX Composite Index fell 
14.401 points, or 2.1 percent, to 664.569 -- well above its early 
lows. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI -- An optimistic outlook for Taiwanese bank shares pushed  
the Weighted Price Index up by 39.05 points, or 0.49 percent, to 
7,996.76. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia's Composite Index rose 10.19 points, or  
1.3 percent, to 767.69 as investors bet on a local and regional 
economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY -- Shares were mostly lower, with traders waiting for  
fresh cues from Wall Street. The All Ordinaries Index dropped 6.9 
points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,987.6. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON -- Shares rose on strong corporate earnings. The  
NZSE-40 rose 14.03 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,128.45. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA -- Blue chips were slightly higher amid an uncertain  
outlook on U.S. interest rates. The Philippine Stock Exchange index 
of 30 selected companies closed up 6.45 points, or 0.3 percent, at 
2,377.07. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK -- Thai shares ended little changed after an early rally  
ran out of steam. The SET index rose 0.94 point, or 0.2 percent, to 
511.44. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
