<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 01:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Says No Large Tax Cut Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The robust American economy is in no need of a  
major tax cut like the 10-year, $778 billion package being 
developed by congressional Republicans, Treasury Secretary Robert 
Rubin told Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Meeting behind closed doors in the Capitol on Wednesday with  
seven key Democrats, Rubin said a better use for projected surplus 
money left over once Social Security and Medicare are safeguarded 
would be to pay down the nation's debts, according to participants. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's fair to say they would like nothing to happen,''  
said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, top Democrat on the 
Senate Finance Committee. ``The economy is in full employment, with 
low interest rates. This economy doesn't need any stimulus. ... 
That's their view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moynihan and other participants said no final decision was  
reached on whether Democrats will offer an alternative to the 
still-evolving Republican tax relief package. Republican leaders in 
the House and Senate plan to release separate draft proposals in 
July and have asked for Democratic input. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin and the man nominated by President Clinton to succeed him,  
Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, left the Capitol 
meeting without speaking to reporters. The president's fiscal 2000 
budget calls for targeted tax cuts worth $75.3 billion over five 
years, but they are paid for with increases many in the GOP oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said most Democrats believe the  
Republican tax cut would eat up money needed for critical programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our biggest problem with the Republican tax bill is that it's  
so large that it's forcing deep cuts. ... They're going to have to 
cut veterans programs, housing, education, all sorts of things,'' 
Kerrey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, however, believe the existence of the surplus is a  
golden opportunity to reduce taxes without slashing spending and 
say tax cuts are second in priority only to guaranteeing Social 
Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is a bipartisan package of tax cuts,'' Senate Finance  
Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., told panel members in a 
letter this week. ``I hope to build the package on tax relief 
proposals supported on both sides of the aisle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if such support is possible, Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.,  
said, ``That's unclear at this point. It's way too early to tell.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 06:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable Nielsen Rankings / Cable Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rankings for the top 15 programs on basic cable networks as  
compiled by Nielsen Media Research for the week of May 31-June 6. 
Each ratings point represents 994,000 households. Day and start 
time (EDT) are included in parentheses. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``WWF Wrestling'' (Monday, 10 p.m.), USA, 5.1, 5.04 million  
homes. 
</P>
<P>
	2. ``NBA Playoffs: New York vs. Indiana'' (Tuesday, 8:28 p.m.),  
TNT, 4.6, 4.58 million homes. 
</P>
<P>
	3. ``WWF Wrestling'' (Monday, 9 p.m.), USA, 4.4, 4.36 million  
homes. 
</P>
<P>
