<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 09:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philip Morris Defends Store Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Philip Morris Inc. never meant for its  
``Retail Leaders'' program to coerce retailers to sell its Marlboro 
products over rival brands, a company executive testified today at 
a hearing on rival cigarette makers' request that the program 
should be halted. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wouldn't do that,'' James Mortensen, a co-creator of the  
program for Philip Morris, told the court as he defended the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Philip Morris competitors -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.,  
Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp. -- are 
asking U.S. District Judge Frank Bullock to issue a preliminary 
injunction stopping ``Retail Leaders'' until a jury trial can be 
held on their lawsuit challenging the program. 
</P>
<P>
	They claim the program violates state and federal antitrust  
laws; Philip Morris denies wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing was expected to conclude later today. It was unclear  
whether Bullock would issue an oral ruling at the hearing's 
conclusion, or rule in writing later. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses warned Wednesday that Philip Morris could gain a 60  
percent to 70 percent share of U.S. cigarette sales if allowed to 
continue the program, which rewards stores that prominently display 
its brands with generous discounts. Philip Morris products now 
account for nearly 54 percent of all U.S. retail cigarette sales. 
</P>
<P>
	First implemented by Philip Morris last fall, the marketing  
program entitles retailers to rebates of $5.50 or more per 
cigarette carton and additional payments for devoting their most 
prominent counter space to Philip Morris products. 
</P>
<P>
	A provision in the ``Retail Leaders'' contract says if Philip  
Morris furnishes a cigarette display for a retailer, it can demand 
that only Philip Morris products be advertised. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortensen testified Wednesday that each participating retailer  
can decide where a product or advertisement is displayed under the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of the day, the decision is up to the retailer,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But under cross-examination late Wednesday, Mortensen  
acknowledged the program prohibited retailers from accepting any 
offer to improve the positioning of a rival product. 
</P>
<P>
	If a retailer accepted such an offer, said Mortensen, he no  
longer would be considered a ``Retail Leaders'' participant. 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Spell, Lorillard's executive vice president of sales and  
marketing, said Wednesday the ``Retail Leaders'' has had a 
disastrous affect on his company, with 4,000 of its 88,000 accounts 
lost in the last 60 to 90 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in management with this company for 20 years, and  
never during my tenure have I seen this kind of decrease,'' Spell 
said, adding that Lorillard could lose 75 percent of its contract 
agreements because of Philip Morris' program. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Barger, chief operating officer of Morgan Oil &AMP; Propane of  
Waynesville, N.C., testified that he decided against participating 
in the program, even though his 22-store chain would have received 
up to $500,000 in financial incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the incentives, known as ``buy-downs,'' would have made  
it possible for his Convenience King stores to sell Philip Morris 
cigarettes at a lower price, but that he would have had to 
virtually stop selling rival brands. He couldn't do it, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to offer as many tobacco products as we can,'' Barger  
said, adding that vendors of beer, soft drinks and snack food never 
set conditions on displaying and selling rival products like Philip 
Morris did. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
