<DOCNO> APW19990610.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 00:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bettman: NHL in State of Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The NHL lost Wayne Gretzky and Mario Lemieux to  
retirement, and now it might lose the Pittsburgh Penguins, too. 
Owners are bleeding money, TV ratings are down. 
</P>
<P>
	The state of the NHL? Call it a state of flux, of transition, of  
worry. Yet, one of cautious optimism, too. 
</P>
<P>
	As football, baseball and basketball thrive with exciting home  
run races and unpredictable playoffs and survive labor disputes and 
Michael Jordan's retirement, the NHL is nervously trying to 
maintain its niche among the big four sports. 
</P>
<P>
	It isn't easy, not with one team in bankruptcy and another team  
short of money, and nearly every franchise -- even the marquee names 
-- losing enormous bundles of cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Network TV revenues will jump appreciably next season under a  
new contract with ABC and ESPN, but NHL teams still will earn only 
6 percent of what a single NFL franchise makes from TV. That's 
understandable; hockey's most-watched games attract an audience 
less than one-tenth the size of the viewership for the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest-rated NHL game was the 1996 All-Star game, getting a  
4.1 rating. That's about half of what the World Wrestling 
Federation draws on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a great game,'' commissioner Gary Bettman said. ``We  
just have to get more people to watch it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And even as it expands to Atlanta, Columbus and Minnesota to  
bring its league to 30 franchises by the 2000-01 season, the NHL is 
preoccupied with keeping afloat the Penguins and the New York 
Islanders, teams that have won a combined six Stanley Cups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins are operating under federal bankruptcy protection,  
the first major U.S. pro sports team to do so since the Penguins 
themselves a quarter-century ago. The franchise's fate likely will 
be decided June 24, when a group led by Hall of Famer Lemieux could 
have its takeover plan approved by creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Islanders, looking for new ownership and a new arena, have  
cut their payroll so drastically that their one remaining star, 
Zigmund Palffy, is on the trading block. 
</P>
<P>
	So many problems. So much work for hockey to do. So few  
recognizable stars to promote, especially now that Gretzky and 
Lemieux have joined Jordan in retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Think selling Michael Peca as a household name is easy?  
</P>
<P>
	``But Rocket Richard retired and the game went on, and Gordie  
Howe retired and the game went on,'' Bettman said. ``The game will 
go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bettman's game plan for a prosperous NHL:  
</P>
<P>
	--Continue to increase revenues, which have jumped by $500  
million in five years, by moving into even more new 
money-generating arenas and stimulating interest in hockey 
internationally. 
</P>
<P>
	--Slow skyrocketing salaries with judicious personnel decisions  
and, ultimately, through a new collective bargaining agreement, 
even though the current deal doesn't end until 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	``Revenues in the last five years have increased at a phenomenal  
rate but, having said that, players' salaries for the last two 
years have grown faster than our growth in revenues,'' Bettman said 
Wednesday. ``In the final analysis, that is not going to continue 
forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Promote, promote, promote to build a younger and broader fan  
base. Not with glowing hockey pucks or Zamboni races, but by 
enticing fans to watch the game in person, where it much better 
appreciated than on television. 
</P>
<P>
	Correcting hockey's myriad problems won't be easy, especially  
since the game remains indigenous to the sparsely populated plains 
and provinces of Canada, not to the Sun Belt cities where the sport 
has migrated. 
</P>
<P>
	And, as usual, it comes down to money. Always, money.  
</P>
<P>
	Because its national TV ratings and, subsequently, its national  
TV revenues are so much lower than football, baseball or 
basketball, hockey spends a disproportionate amount of its revenues 
on salaries -- approximately 72 percent, or 9 percentage points more 
than any other sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek's $8 million salary, for  
example, rivals that of Mark McGwire. But McGwire's St. Louis 
Cardinals play twice as many games before twice as many fans and 
make five times as much in national TV income as Hasek's Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	And what is the more magical number: Hasek's .939 playoff save  
percentage or McGwire's 70 home runs? 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we are paying 133 percent of our gate receipts to  
the players,'' Boston Bruins general manager Harry Sinden said at a 
recent Board of Governors meeting. ``Take every single ticket that 
is sold across the league, and we've got to find 33 percent more 
just to pay them. Just them! We've got problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a Penguins bankruptcy hearing last week, NHL general counsel  
William Daly estimated that 20 of the NHL's 27 teams are losing 
money. The figure is questionable because it does not count arena 
revenues that some teams control, but the general consensus around 
the league is that at least half the franchises aren't profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the Montreal Canadiens, who are to hockey what the Yankees  
are to baseball, caused a ripple of disbelief in Canada by 
revealing they lost $3.8 million at the same time they moved into a 
new arena this season. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tampa Bay, Art Williams became so disenchanted with the sport  
so quickly that he agreed to sell the Lightning midway through his 
first season of ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Losing money is one thing but, as Kings president Tim Leiweke  
said, ``If the league keeps going in this direction, it's going to 
be losing franchises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It may come as soon as this month if Lemieux's buyout plan in  
Pittsburgh is disapproved, though that does not appear likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret that we have teams losing money,'' Bettman  
said. ``Even if it were one team, it would be too many. The worst 
case is it is a four- or five-year phenomenon. The best case is it 
will start correcting itself sooner. It isn't going to be a 
long-term problem because it is going to get fixed.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 08:00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PAC Money Rises for Credit Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's credit unions boosted their  
giving to members of Congress as they urged lawmakers to pass a 
bill allowing more people to join credit unions -- despite a Supreme 
Court decision restricting their membership. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Election Commission reported Wednesday that the  
credit unions' political action committee contributed $1 million to 
congressional candidates for the last election, $397,645 more than 
the PAC spent during the 1996 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit unions also spent more than $2 million on lobbying in  
1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to influence the policy agenda through their  
campaign contributions and their lobbying spending,'' said Paul 
Hendrie, a spokesman for the Center for Responsive Politics, a 
nonpartisan research group. ``You see the spending rise among 
interest groups who have issues before Congress at a given time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress was prodded to act after the Supreme Court ruled that  
corporate credit unions could not accept outside members. Lawmakers 
passed legislation last summer about five months after the court 
decision, thus rejecting an argument that credit unions who wanted 
to expand their membership should be subject to the same taxes and 
regulations as banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The legislation gave us an opportunity to promote political  
action among credit union members,'' said Richard Gose, the Credit 
Union National Association's vice president for political action. 
``Contributions do nothing more than help a group have access and 
be more visible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC said overall PAC contributions to candidates rose  
slightly, from $217.8 million in 1995-96 to $219.9 million in 
1997-98. More than three-fourths of the money went to incumbents, 
up from two-thirds in 1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	The most generous PAC was the Realtors, which gave $2.5 million  
in 1997-98. The Realtors supported legislation making it easier for 
private property owners to sue for the loss of their land due to 
government regulations, opposed efforts to eliminate the home 
mortgage interest tax deduction, and backed a bill to protect real 
estate data on the Internet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 19:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Resistance Members To Be Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five former members of CIA-backed Iraqi  
resistance groups jailed for 2 1/2 years will be released while they 
seek asylum in another country, the Immigration and Naturalization 
Service said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The men belonged to two groups supported by the CIA as part of a  
U.S. effort to overthrow or weaken Saddam Hussein after the 1991 
Gulf War. When Saddam's troops swept through northern Iraq, 
thousands of opposition fighters and their families were evacuated 
by the U.S. military. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the men were detained by the United States. An  
immigration judge denied them asylum in March 1998 and ordered them 
deported, saying they were security risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement signed Thursday, five of the men will accept  
the deportation order and withdraw any appeals, said Russ Bergeron, 
spokesman for the INS in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	A sixth Iraqi rejected the agreement and will remain in custody.  
</P>
<P>
	The agreement was expected to be filed at immigration court  
early Friday, said Niels Frenzen, the attorney for the six men. 
</P>
<P>
	If the agreement is approved, the men will be able to join their  
families in Nebraska but will be under house arrest until granted 
asylum elsewhere. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0075 </DOCNO>
