<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 69.02 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell Thursday as good economic news for  
Japan stimulated Wall Street's fears that the unfettered growth of 
the U.S. economy will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it looks like interest rates are going up, stocks are going  
down,'' said John Cleland, chief investment strategist at Security 
Benefit Group in Topeka, Kan. ``It's that simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 69.02 to close at  
10,621.27. The blue-chip index, down as much as 164 points earlier 
in the session, began marching back in the last hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 fell 15.82 to 1,302.82, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
dominated by technology stocks, fell 34.73 to 2,484.62. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks came under pressure after the Japanese government said  
the nation's gross domestic product grew 1.9 percent in the first 
three months of the year -- a larger increase than expected, and the 
first since the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the strong report could help sway the Fed toward  
raising interest rates in an effort to halt inflation. Last fall, 
amid a financial crisis that crippled several Asian nations, the 
Fed cut rates three times, hoping to protect the global economy 
from falling into a downward spiral. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of renewed growth in Japan could convince policy-makers  
that it is no longer necessary to hold rates lower, market watchers 
said. Stocks and bond markets have been skittish since May 18, when 
the Fed indicated it might raise interest rates if it determines 
that higher rates would cool off a surging economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices, which are highly sensitive to inflation, fell  
Thursday, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.06 
percent. Analysts consider bond yields above 6 percent to be 
detrimental to stocks, as investors may turn to the lucrative, 
stable return of bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're on an inflation offensive,'' said Ned Riley, chief  
investment officer at BankBoston. ``That has undermined bonds and 
really set the tone for the equities market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of higher rates hurt bank and financial stocks the  
most. Higher interest rates cut into bank profits as lending volume 
shrinks. American Express fell 2 to 123 1/8 and PNC Bank led consumer 
banks lower, falling 1 3/4 to 56 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer stocks also declined. Those shares, which are often  
expensive, are also vulnerable to higher interest rates as 
investors become less willing to pay a high price for a stock 
relative to its earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology companies are also battling customers' uncertainty  
over the Year 2000 computer bug, analysts said. Gateway fell 3 3/16 
to 58 13/16, and network provider Cisco Systems lost 3 5/16 to 110 
7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer tumbled 5 3/8 to 99 9/16, leading the entire drug sector  
lower. Pfizer sustained its second sharp drop since the U.S. Food 
and Drug Administration Wednesday restricted the use of Pfizer's 
antibiotic Trovan. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders remained focused on the Friday morning release of the  
producer price index. That report was expected to offer the latest 
hint of whether inflationary pressures have crept into the U.S. 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to establish that the U.S. economy is not boiling to  
the point of explosion,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, traders listened in on Fed Chairman Alan  
Greenspan's afternoon commencement address at Harvard University. 
Greenspan did not address monetary policy, but kept his remarks 
confined to personal musings on trust and integrity. 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues outnumbered  
advancers by a 2-to-1 margin. NYSE composite volume totaled 853.38 
million shares, compared with 794.35 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 6.43 to 622.85, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.74 to 768.25. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.92 to 442.27.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.89 percent as  
investors anticipated the GDP report, which was released after the 
close of trading. Germany's DAX index fell 0.9 percent, Britain's 
FT-SE 100 fell 0.7 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.9 percent 
lower. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
