<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Lower; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar fell against other major currencies in  
European trading Thursday. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0506, up from $1.0444 Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Wednesday: 118.73 Japanese  
yen, down from 118.84; 1.5212 Swiss francs, down from 1.5223; 
1.4630 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4741. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6040, up from $1.6014.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar was worth 118.75  
Japanese yen, while the euro was worth $1.0469 and the British 
pound was worth $1.6015. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8616 German marks, down from 1.8727; 
6.2436 French francs, down from 6.2807; 2.0976 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1100; 1,843.01 Italian lire, down from 1,853.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $260.50 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$259.40 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $259.75, up from $259.65.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $3.70 in Hong Kong to close at $258.35.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.11 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$4.93. 
  	   	
</P>
