<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heavy rains pummeled parts of the Midwest and Southeast on  
Thursday, while most of the country enjoyed fair and dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms were widespread over the central part  
of the country because of a cold front that stretched from the 
northern Mississippi Valley into the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	In Oklahoma, as much as 10 inches of rain fell in a 24-hour  
period, turning normally placid city creeks into raging torrents, 
flooding wheat fields and sending rivers and streams out of their 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms also dampened the Southeast and Gulf Coast, and  
some light showers threatened Pennsylvania, Maryland and Delaware. 
But fair to partly cloudy skies were found in much of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	Although a few showers were found in Wyoming and northern Utah,  
the rest of the West enjoyed fair and dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	New England had mostly cool and dry weather, as a cold front  
stretched from Pennsylvania into North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	The mid-afternoon high in the Lower 48 states was 90, in Biloxi,  
Miss. The low was 23, in Stanley, Idaho. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
