<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate's Taped Speech Draws Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- The Evergreen State College's choice of  
convicted cop killer Mumia Abu-Jamal as a commencement speaker has 
drawn protests from police, a leading congressman, the governor and 
the victim's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, about 800 graduating students at the state-supported  
liberal arts college are scheduled to hear a 13-minute taped 
address from the former Black Panther sentenced to death for the 
slaying of a Philadelphia police officer in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Students invited Abu-Jamal to be among the commencement speakers  
because he has used his free speech rights ``to galvanize an 
international conversation about the death penalty, the 
disproportionate number of blacks on death row, and the 
relationship between poverty and the criminal justice system,'' 
Evergreen President Jane Jervis said in a statement Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, took the House floor on  
Thursday for a moment of silence to protest the invitation, his 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no justifiable reason for an institution of higher  
learning to have a convicted murderer speak to its students,'' 
DeLay said earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay said his ``heart goes out'' to Maureen Faulkner, widow of  
Officer Daniel Faulkner. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Faulkner said she plans to attend the commencement with a  
picture of her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania Attorney General Mike Fisher, in a letter mailed to  
Jervis on Thursday, asked her to consider canceling Abu-Jamal's 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an affront to the memory of Officer Faulkner, his family  
and all victims of violent crime for your institution to glorify 
this cop killer,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Gov. Gary Locke canceled plans to be among the  
speakers out of respect for police officers. Off-duty officers from 
the Seattle area are expected at the commencement to protest. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal is awaiting execution. The prison journalist claims he  
was railroaded and has become a symbol for anti-death penalty 
groups. His supporters include actor Ed Asner and the Rev. Jesse 
Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	He has appealed his case to the U.S. Supreme Court.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
