<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Boxer Wins $8.5M in Libel Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Sports Illustrated magazine was ordered  
to pay at least $8.5 million to ex-heavyweight boxer Randall 
``Tex'' Cobb, who sued for libel after the publication reported he 
helped fix a fight and shared cocaine with the loser. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal court jury awarded the compensatory damages Wednesday  
to Cobb and will decide on punitive damages during a hearing 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, 46, declined to comment on the case, saying ``I'm sorry,''  
when reached Thursday morning at his hotel room. Cobb's attorney, 
George Bochetto, said his client feels redeemed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' Bochetto said. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine's Nashville attorney, Eddie Wayland, did not  
immediately return a call Thursday but told The Tennessean, ``The 
case is still pending. I don't think that a comment would be 
appropriate at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb sued for $50 million in actual damages and $100 million for  
punitive damages a year after an article headlined ``The Fix Was 
In'' appeared in the magazine Oct. 4 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The story began with an anecdote about the Sept. 15, 1992, bout  
between Cobb and Sonny Barch, a journeyman fighter and former 
Memphis State University football player. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine reported that before the bout in Fort Lauderdale,  
Fla., Cobb asked Barch how he planned to throw the fight because 
Cobb had an injured shoulder and wanted it to end as quickly as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Barch said he told Cobb, ``I'm going to have to  
hit you to make it look good. But I won't hit your shoulder.'' 
Barch told Sports Illustrated that Cobb responded, ``Bubba, I 
appreciate it. I'll make it up to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barch allowed Cobb to hit him three times, dropping to a knee  
each time and triggering the three-knockdown rule, Sports 
Illustrated reported. Cobb was declared the winner by TKO. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb was quoted in the article saying, ``whoever believes the  
fight is faked ought to try to take the punches he threw. I 
emphatically deny all the allegations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine also reported that Barch said he, Cobb and fight  
promoter Rick ``Elvis'' Parker shared a half ounce of cocaine after 
the fight. Sports Illustrated said Cobb had tested positive for 
cocaine use, but said in a followup item that it was marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayland told jurors the article by senior writers William Nack  
and Sonja Steptoe was accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	``They believed the story was true. They believed it then and  
they believe it now. ... They got the story right,'' Wayland said. 
``This story was not just about Tex Cobb. It was about the dark 
side of boxing. Whatever damage (Cobb) suffered is a result of his 
own actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Steptoe testified last month she had little evidence  
that Cobb was a willing participant in a fixed fight with Barch. 
</P>
<P>
	In taped testimony, ex-heavyweight champion Larry Holmes, who  
won a one-sided 15-round match against Cobb in 1982, said Cobb was 
a true contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb said after the article was published he was considered  
damaged goods, ending his boxing career and nearly ending his 
acting career he had begun after boxing. Shortly thereafter, the 
Abilene, Texas, native moved from Nashville to Philadelphia, his 
attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated for more than eight hours. The trial began  
May 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he quit fighting, Cobb has had roles in several movies,  
including 1997's ``Liar, Liar;'' ``Raising Arizona;'' ``Uncommon 
Valor'' and ``The Golden Child.'' He's also been in the TV shows 
``Moonlighting'' and ``MacGyver.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bochetto said Cobb has a small part as a football player in an  
upcoming Oliver Stone movie about the NFL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
