Nasdaq Composite Index        2,484.60  - 34.75
Gold(final) -    $259.30    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Jump by 14,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment benefits rose last  
week to the highest level since early January. But economists 
shrugged it off as a temporary blip in a job market that remains 
exceptionally healthy. They also expressed doubts that the one-week 
increase would influence the Federal Reserve very much as it 
considers at month's end whether to raise interest rates to slow 
down the economy and keep inflation under control. Federal Reserve 
Board Governor Roger Ferguson signaled today that Fed policy makers 
will be watching inflation indicators closely when they meet June 
29-30. The Labor Department said today that 323,000 U.S. workers 
filed new claims for jobless benefits for the week ending June 5 -- 
up 14,000 from the previous week. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan's GDP Expands  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Massive public works spending helped Japan's  
economy reverse itself in the first three months of this year, with 
the government reporting today an unexpectedly strong 1.9 percent 
growth rate -- the first sign of growth since the summer of 1997. 
The January-March gross domestic product increase was well above 
the 0.8 contraction in the last three months of 1998 -- the fifth 
straight quarter of decline. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Speaks Out for Integrity  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan urged  
Harvard graduates to strive for integrity and avoid the temptation 
to cut corners in their professional lives. In a speech prepared 
for commencement ceremonies in Cambridge, Mass., Greenspan conceded 
today that his advice ran the risk of ``sounding a bit uncool.'' 
But he said he believed strongly that ``your success in life and 
the success of our country is going to depend on the integrity and 
other qualities of character'' demonstrated by coming generations. 
``The true measure of a career is to be able to be content, even 
proud, that you succeeded through your own endeavors without 
leaving a trail of casualties in your wake,'' Greenspan said. 

</P>
<P>
	Medical Device Cos. Surveyed on Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned about risks to patients, the  
government is preparing a list of medical device makers with 
products that could have Y2K problems. In extreme cases, dangerous 
devices will be seized. The Food and Drug Administration also may 
issue public warnings or suggest voluntary recalls if the agency 
finds medical devices that could malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, 
Health and Human Services deputy secretary Kevin Thurm said today. 
He spoke at a hearing of the Senate's special panel on the year 
2000 computer problem. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Convicted in Big Pyramid Scheme  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A jury convicted businessman Patrick Bennett  
today on 42 counts in an indictment accusing him of orchestrating 
the biggest pyramid scheme in U.S. history. It was not able to 
reach a verdict on the most serious charge of conspiracy. 
Prosecutors had accused Syracuse businessman Bennett during two 
trials in U.S. District Court in Manhattan of cheating more than 
22,000 investors out of $700 million. The first jury convicted him 
of perjury and obstructing a federal investigation of his company 
but could not reach a verdict on the rest of the charges. A second 
jury convicted him today of 42 other counts, including securities 
fraud and money laundering. But the jury still was unable to reach 
a verdict on the first 11 counts of the indictment, which included 
conspiracy and mail fraud charges. Still, the convictions today 
were serious enough to lead to revocation of his bail. 

</P>
<P>
	Browser Discussed at Microsoft Trial  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Microsoft antitrust trial heard from the  
government's last rebuttal witness today. Princeton University 
computer science professor Edward Felten had said there was no 
technical reason for Microsoft to bundle its Web browser into its 
popular Windows operating system. In earlier testimony, he 
described a program he created to disable the browser, Internet 
Explorer, within Windows. He took the stand today after government 
attorneys introduced as evidence a newer version of his program, as 
well as a program to reinstall the browser. ``There are many ways 
in which Microsoft can go about delivering Windows 98 without IE,'' 
Felten said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Chevron, S.Africa Firm Work on Gas  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Chevron Corp. has formed a joint venture  
with the South African firm Sasol Ltd. for worldwide use of a 
technology for converting natural gas to a more easily used and 
transported liquid. The union could make Chevron one of the 
industry's most aggressive players in the emerging gas-to-liquids 
business. 

</P>
<P>
	Abortion Foe Fights Web Site Close  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- When MindSpring Enterprises shut down Neal  
Horsley's anti-abortion Web site with its photos of mangled fetuses 
and drawings of dripping blood, the company said the site violated 
its appropriate use policies. But Horsley said the move was a form 
of censorship and is suing the Atlanta-based Internet service 
provider for $251 million for allegedly destroying hundreds of 
e-mails when it booted him offline earlier this year. 

</P>
<P>
	Northwest, Attendants Reach Deal  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Northwest Airlines and its flight attendants  
announced a tentative agreement on a five-year contract today, 
averting a possible strike against the nation's fourth largest 
airline. Billie Davenport, president of Teamsters Local 2000, said, 
``We are proud to recommend it to our brothers and sisters for 
ratification.'' Doug Steenland, Northwest executive vice president, 
said the tentative agreement represents the importance of the 
flight attendants to the carrier. Details of the agreement were not 
disclosed. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Draft Customer Service Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's major airlines today decided  
against announcing a voluntary move aimed at holding off more 
serious mandatory customer-rights directives from Congress. Gerald 
Greenwald, head of United Airlines, and chairman of a trade group 
representing the country's biggest carriers, said the airlines had 
been ready to announce the plan but decided against it at the last 
moment for reasons he refused to explain. He promised an 
announcement in the near future. One part of the 12-point plan, a 
draft of which was obtained yesterday by The Associated Press, 
would have committed airlines to meeting customers' essential needs 
during long, on-aircraft delays. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Makes It Harder To Prove Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today made it harder for  
prosecutors to prove federal cases alleging bank, wire or mail 
fraud. The court ruled unanimously that prosecutors in such cases 
must prove that an allegedly fraudulent act affected the outcome of 
the transaction. The justices ordered a lower court to re-examine a 
Florida man's convictions for fraudulently obtaining more than $30 
million in loans for land purchase and development deals. 

</P>
