<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuit Targets Indian Trust Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accused of mismanaging $500 million in Indian  
trust funds, the government acknowledged in court Thursday it can't 
provide some account holders, many of them poor, with basic 
information about their money. 
</P>
<P>
	A class-action lawsuit is seeking to force the government to fix  
the accounting system and reconcile the 300,000 accounts. Lawyers 
for the account holders claim taxpayers could eventually be liable 
for billions of dollars in underpayments to the Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes before the trial started, government lawyers filed  
documents acknowledging that the Interior Department inadequately 
controls receipts and disbursement and doesn't provide regular 
reports and reconciliations of all accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not surprising that a reformed trust system cannot  
spring up overnight,'' Justice Department lawyer Tom Clark told the 
federal judge who is hearing the case. ``It can't be done by a 
stroke of a pen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one disputes that the government has mishandled the money for  
generations. 
</P>
<P>
	The money primarily comes from lease revenue and royalties that  
the Interior Department holds in trust for individual Indians. 
Complex land ownership has made it difficult to track the accounts, 
thousands of which are worth only a few dollars, and many records 
have been lost or destroyed over the years, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials contend they are working  
overtime to repair the system, but account holders say the efforts 
have been inadequate and halfhearted despite proddings from 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over 150 years, there hasn't been an audit or reconciliation  
of Indian money,'' said Elouise Cobell, a Blackfeet woman who is 
one of the five lead plaintiffs. ``The only way we're going to hold 
their feet to the fire is through a court.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is being heard by U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth,  
who earlier held Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Treasury 
Secretary Robert Rubin in contempt for their departments' delay in 
producing records for the lead plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is being tried in two phases. The first will focus  
on fixing the accounting system. The second will deal with 
reconciling the accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior also is responsible for $2.5 billion in tribal  
accounts. Tribes have been negotiating with the administration on a 
separate settlement of those funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not here to rehash the problems of the past. ... We're  
here to tell you how we're going to solve them,'' Justice 
Department lawyer Tom Clark told the judge. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior's Bureau of Indian Affairs is developing a new computer  
system for handling the accounts that will be tested for the first 
time later this month in Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of  
Congress, has questioned whether the BIA's new system will work, 
and Senate Republicans also have been highly critical of Interior's 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial was expected to take several weeks.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Foe Fights Web Site Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- When MindSpring Enterprises shut down Neal  
Horsley's anti-abortion Web site with its photos of mangled fetuses 
and drawings of dripping blood, the company said the site violated 
its appropriate use policies. 
</P>
<P>
	But Horsley said the move was a form of censorship and is suing  
the Atlanta-based Internet service provider for $251 million for 
allegedly destroying hundreds of e-mails when it booted him offline 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``If telephone companies shut people's telephones down because  
of what they believe or because of what they were saying and they 
weren't breaking the law, then I'm sure the American people would 
understand why that has to be stopped,'' Horsley said Wednesday 
from his Carrollton home. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, filed Tuesday in Gwinnett County Superior Court, seeks  
$1 million for breach of contract and the rest in punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	MindSpring spokesman Ed Hansen said he could not comment on  
pending litigation but read from a company statement that said 
``MindSpring stands behind our previous statements that Mr. 
Horsley's service was terminated for one or more violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``However, if this does go to court, it will become obvious how  
flagrant his violations were,'' Hansen added. 
</P>
<P>
	Horsley, 55, operates the ``The Nuremburg Files'' site, which  
contains Wild West-style wanted posters of abortion doctors. It 
also lists the names and addresses of abortion doctors, with those 
who have been killed crossed out and those injured listed in gray. 
</P>
<P>
	Three times, doctors on the list were killed, most recently last  
October when Dr. Barnett Slepian was gunned down in his home 
outside Buffalo, N.Y. His name on the site was crossed out that 
same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Horsley claims hundreds -- maybe thousands -- of messages and  
e-mails were destroyed when MindSpring pulled the plug in February. 
The site invites readers to send in abortion doctors' addresses, 
license plate numbers and the names of their children. 
</P>
<P>
	``When MindSpring closed us down, it was in the midst of four  
months of national and international publicity. We had seven 
million hits during that period,'' said Horsley, who now runs the 
site from his own server. 
</P>
<P>
	The site gained notoriety earlier this year when it became the  
subject of a lawsuit in Oregon. There, a federal jury ordered 
several anti-abortion groups that contribute to the site to pay 
$107 million in damages because the tactics amounted to illegal 
threats. Horsley was not a defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	Planned Parenthood, several abortion doctors and a clinic had  
sued the activists under the U.S. racketeering statute and a 1994 
federal law that makes it illegal to incite violence against 
abortion doctors or their patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Days after the verdict, MindSpring, which provided the Internet  
space for the site, closed it for violating the company's 
``appropriate use policies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Horsley's attorney, John Matteson said the punitive damages  
amount they are seeking is a percentage of what the company is 
worth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It takes that kind of money to get their attention and make  
some kind of impact on the wild things they're doing. They sit 
there like God erasing e-mail and deciding who can communicate with 
who,'' Matteson said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Delayed on Tobacco Displays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday refused to rule  
immediately on a petition to stop tobacco conglomerate Philip 
Morris' new retail marketing program, which three rivals say 
violates antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Frank Bullock said he expects to issue a  
ruling by the end of June on the preliminary injunction motion 
targeting Philip Morris' ``Retail Leaders'' program. Three 
competitors claim the program forces retailers to relegate their 
brands to the back shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit itself -- filed by R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.,  
Lorillard Tobacco Co. and Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp. -- will 
go to trial in the next 10 to 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The program, implemented by Philip Morris last fall, rewards  
stores that prominently display its brands with generous discounts. 
The three plaintiffs, however, said ``Retail Leaders'' also 
requires retailers to devote their prime cigarette display space to 
Philip Morris products. 
</P>
<P>
	``What `Retail Leaders' does is take us off the counter and put  
us on the floor,'' Lorillard attorney Jim Williams said in his 
closing statement Thursday. ``It's like a snowball running 
downhill, and it will accelerate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	RJR attorney Richard Cooper said in his closing statement that  
an injunction stopping ``Retail Leaders'' would preserve retailers' 
autonomy. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris attorney Jerome Chapman said the dispute doesn't  
belong in the courts. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs' witnesses warned earlier that Philip Morris  
could gain a 60 percent to 70 percent share of U.S. cigarette sales 
if ``Retail Leaders'' isn't halted. Philip Morris brands now enjoy 
a nearly 54 percent market share. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 09:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Retailer Ahold's Profits Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch food retailer Royal Ahold's  
profit in the first quarter rose 32 percent due to strong sales in 
the United States and Europe. It expects a profit rise of up to 20 
percent for the year. The earnings increase reported today was in 
line with market expectations, but Ahold's shares dropped 2 percent 
in trading on the Amsterdam stock exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, one of the world's largest supermarket owners with  
chains like Stop &AMP; Shop and Giant, earned 175 million euros, or 
$180 million, in the three months ended April 25 from 133 million 
euros a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales jumped 27 percent to 9.28 billion euros, or $9.65 billion,  
from 7.30 nillion euros a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal Ahold owns more than 3,600 supermarkets and specialty  
stores worldwide, and has more than 1,000 stores mostly along the 
eastern seaboard in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Among its U.S. store brands are Stop &AMP; Shop, Giant, Tops and  
Bi-Lo. Earlier this year, Ahold announced its intention to acquire 
Pathmark Stores Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Its operating profit rose 46 percent in the United States in the  
first quarter. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Record Industry Fights Pirates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The recording industry's attack on music piracy  
bit a chunk out of the booming illegal trade last year, but 
stronger laws and more aggressive prosecution are still needed to 
make any serious impact, industry enforcers said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fighting music piracy today means fighting a huge, organized,  
illegal international business,'' said Jason Berman, head of the 
International Federation of the Phonographic Industry, which 
represents 1,300 record companies in 70 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our industry dedicates large resources to that fight but we  
need, above all else, support of the governments,'' Berman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once the bailiwick of backroom bootleggers with a few cassette  
copying machines, music piracy has grown into a $4.5 billion 
industry with sophisticated global distribution networks and close 
ties to organized crime. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the federation formed its international anti-piracy  
team in 1997, recruiting investigators and industry experts to 
sniff out the operations that produce an estimated 2 billion 
counterfeit CDs and cassettes every year. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the unit seized more than 60 million illegally produced  
CDs -- half of them from Southeast Asia and Latin America -- and 
closed down major manufacturing plants in North America, Europe, 
the Middle East and Asia, the federation said. 
</P>
<P>
	Iain Grant, the organization's head of enforcement, said the  
Mafia sometimes uses lucrative bootleg CD operations to finance 
drug-trafficking and other criminal endeavors. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do not need to be a rocket scientist to expect that  
organized crime groups worldwide will get involved when there are 
profits which can be generated at this level,'' Grant said. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the federation assisted in the raid of a CD  
manufacturing plant in Naples, Italy, that resulted in the arrest 
of 14 reputed Mafia members and led investigators to various other 
criminal operations, Grant said. The plant was generating $100,000 
a week, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pirated recordings, most often sold at outdoor markets and by  
smaller independent shops that run little risk of getting caught, 
tend to be identifiable by shoddily copied liner art, Berman said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the sound quality can be as good as the real thing, he  
acknowledged. 
</P>
<P>
	Berman said the organization is hampered by inadequate laws and  
relatively light penalties for music piracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``No amount of investigative work on our part, no amount of  
money, resources, time and effort will succeed in reducing these 
incredible levels of piracy if governments don't take effective 
enforcement actions that include both substantial fines and prison 
sentences,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has had a harder time stemming illegal music  
copying via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, its only recourse is trying to shut down Internet  
sites with cease-and-desist orders, which it has done in thousands 
of cases. But there are an estimated 400,000 infringing sites left 
and more coming online every day, the federation said. 
</P>
<P>
	This battle has resulted in the formation of the Secured Digital  
Music Initiative, which seeks to develop a copyright directive that 
will set ground rules for Internet music commerce, Berman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Didn't Get What They Wanted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres accomplished what they came to  
Dallas to get -- home-ice advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's not quite as good as they hoped for after winning the  
opener of the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres' bid to return to Buffalo up 2-0 ended when Brett  
Hull clanked in a goal off a post with 2:50 left in Game 2 and 
Derian Hatcher added an empty-netter, giving the Stars a 4-2 
victory Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Buffalo goes home with the series tied at a game apiece. The  
Sabres will try adding to their 7-0 record at Marine Midland Arena 
this postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we are disappointed after winning the first game,''  
goaltender Dominik Hasek said. ``Now we are 1-1 after two games and 
we're started from the beginning. I like our chances with home-ice 
advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When they arrived in Dallas, Buffalo's goal was to return home  
tied after two games. The Sabres set their sights higher after a 
3-2 overtime victory in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	By losing, Buffalo drops a chance to become the fifth straight  
team to sweep the finals. The Sabres still like their chances of 
winning their first NHL title. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody said it was going to be a four, five-game series,''  
coach Lindy Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Dixon Ward said the Sabres, the seventh-seeded team from  
the East, proved in the first two games that they can play with the 
Presidents' Trophy-winning Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're for real,'' Ward said. ``I think we can take  
satisfaction out of the way we played. We've got a lot of 
confidence we can win this series. That's what we'll take home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo outplayed Dallas over the first two periods, matching  
the Stars' aggressive, hard-hitting style and controlling the puck 
much better. The Sabres allowed just 12 shots over the first two 
periods. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the way our hockey club played the first two periods,''  
Ruff said. ``We didn't really let them test Dominik.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars did test Hasek's will as they repeatedly ran into him  
in the crease. Dallas' Brian Skrudland was penalized for 
interference for an open-ice hit that sent Hasek into the boards. 
</P>
<P>
	There also was a four-on-four fight after the first period that  
stemmed from contact on Hasek. Six players were given 18 minutes in 
penalties because of the melee. 
</P>
<P>
	``The physical play doesn't bother me,'' Hasek said. ``It just  
pumps me up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres led or were tied for most of the game. Their first  
defict, which came early in the third period, lasted only 1:11 as 
Alexei Zhitnik tied the game at 2 with 14:24 left. 
</P>
<P>
	But over the last 10 minutes, Buffalo ran out of gas. The Sabres  
were outshot 13-3 and lost the majority of loose-puck battles. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek was the only reason the game remained close, just like in  
Game 1, when he foiled nine straight power plays. 
</P>
<P>
	In a four-minute span, Hasek fended off one shot during a brief  
6-on-5, five shots on the ensuing power play, then turned back 
three more when Dallas had a two-man advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	When it was over, Hasek skated behind the goal and sat down to  
catch his breath. He still had to finish off another 1:17 of 5-on-4 
play and he remained brilliant, kicking one rebound beyond the blue 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dallas' 18th shot of the period, Hasek finally cracked. Hull  
fired a slap shot to Hasek's left and it ricocheted off the left 
post and into the right side of the net. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres had another power-play chance in the final minutes,  
but couldn't get their third goal with the extra man. They also 
went without Hasek in net and Hatcher made them pay, firing in a 
long shot after Dallas had cleared the puck. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, it's back to Buffalo, where the Stars will have the same  
mentality the Sabres had in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to come into our building and hopefully try to get a  
split, (but) we haven't lost there yet,'' Ruff said. ``I think that 
is a big plus for us. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been extremely focused and played very well there. So  
we are looking for more of the same.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Leftist rebels attacked a small town  
with explosives and automatic weapons, killing eight police 
officers and a civilian, the mayor said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The guerrillas of the Revolutionary Armed Force of Colombia on  
Wednesday attacked El Espino, 160 miles northeast of Bogota, and 
destroyed several homes, the police headquarters and government 
offices, said Mayor Jorge Elias Carillo. 
</P>
<P>
	``They destroyed a city block,'' Carillo told Radionet radio.  
</P>
<P>
	Another eight police officers were missing and feared abducted,  
Carillo said. A spokesman at national police headquarters said he 
could not immediately confirm the information. 
</P>
<P>
	The FARC, Colombia's oldest and largest insurgency, already  
holds at least 450 soldiers and police prisoner from previous 
attacks on remote outposts. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia will stop allowing judges who  
preside over drug and terrorism cases to remain anonymous but will 
allow the identities of some witnesses and prosecutors to remain 
secret. 
</P>
<P>
	In a late-night session Wednesday, lawmakers renewed the state's  
right to shield the identities of the prosecutors and witnesses 
involved in preliminary investigations against criminals considered 
highly dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	As the cases go to trial, however, judges, lawyers and witnesses  
will now appear in public view. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia created its so-called ``faceless'' courts in 1991. At  
the time, authorities were besieged by violent cocaine cartels that 
assassinated hundreds of judges, prosecutors, and witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The system was due to expire June 30. It has been criticized by  
human rights organizations for violating due process and called 
outdated now that the drug rings have been dismantled. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A former priest has accused  
Brazil's newly appointed top law enforcement official of taking 
part in torture sessions almost three decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Antonio Monteiro, who left the priesthood and now teaches  
philosophy at the University of Alagoas, said he was arrested and 
tortured in 1970 by federal police in the northeastern state of 
Maranhao. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his torturers included Joao Batista Camelo, who was  
appointed this week as chief of the federal police, Brazil's 
equivalent of the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is shameful for Brazil,'' said Monteiro, who will testify  
to the Congressional Human Rights Commission in an effort to block 
the appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential press spokesman George Lamaziere said the  
government stood by Campelo, who has denied the accusations. 
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, a former sociology professor, 
also was persecuted and forced into exile by the military. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) -- Former Public Security Minister Juan  
Jose Echeverria and two of his sons have been ordered to face trial 
on charges of improperly arranging visas for Cubans, attorneys said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision reverses a ruling last month that had cleared them  
of charges. The new decision cannot be appealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors in April 1998 accused the Echeverrias and several  
other people with taking thousands of dollars to arrange visas for 
Cubans who should not have been eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	Echeverria, an attorney, was security minister from 1978 to 1980  
and is a relative of current President Miguel Angel Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors charge that Cubans were being asked to pay $5,000 to  
$7,000 for humanitarian visas that are supposed to be issued free 
of charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Once they arrived in Costa Rica, they often quickly went on to  
the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	REYNOSA, Mexico (AP) -- Mexican immigration authorities detained  
five people from Macedonia on Thursday as they attempted to cross 
into the United States, reportedly to seek political asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	A Yugoslav-born man with U.S. citizenship, Aco Ilinkoski, 42,  
was arrested for immigrant trafficking, Juan Triana Marquez of the 
National Migration Institute said. 
</P>
<P>
	The five people were arrested in Reynosa, a border city across  
from McAllen, Texas, and sent to Macedonia's consulate office in 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of how the five reached Mexico were not clear.  
</P>
<P>
	Triana Marquez said Ilinkoski would face criminal charges that  
carry a possible prison term of six to 12 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
