<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 21:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The National Baptist Congress of  
Christian Education is expected to draw at least 55,000 delegates 
to its convention June 21-25. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a meeting of church workers, from Sunday school teachers  
to church musicians. But candidates for president of the National 
Baptist Convention USA plan to add politicking to the agenda, 
rallying support for the September election. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Henry Lyons resigned as president after he was  
sentenced in March to 5 1/2 years in prison on racketeering and grand 
theft charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The interim president, the Rev. Stuart C. Cureton of Greenville,  
S.C., is to be among speakers at the gathering. He is not a 
candidate to replace Lyons at the National Baptist Convention in 
Tampa, Fla., in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The gathering will include workshops on subjects ranging from  
ministering to rural churches to teen-age pregnancy. The convention 
will close with a ``Christ Alive'' rally featuring the Rev. E.V. 
Hill of Mount Zion Baptist Church in Los Angeles, one of the 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be the candidates who will talk about morality,'' the  
Rev. Victor McKinney, co-chairman of the local organizing 
committee, said. ``They'll talk about sound leadership, integrity 
and honesty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Church rises from rubble    	
</P>
<P>
	SPENCER, S.D. (AP) -- One year after a tornado destroyed their  
place of worship, members of Trinity Lutheran Church celebrated 
their new edifice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The spirit of God is living in Spencer,'' the Rev. Tom  
Christopher said at the dedication. The 135-member church is the 
only one of four to rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	The town is rebuilding after the devastation but has lost about  
half of its population of 300. 
</P>
<P>
	For two months after the storm of May 30, 1998, Trinity's  
congregation worshipped in a tent, then moved to a garage. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a happy day for all of us,'' said Peg Wubben, a church  
member. ``This building is wonderful. But any place where two or 
three gather to worship God is a church.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Church of the Nazarene closed shortly after the tornado that  
killed the minister's wife; St. Matthew's Lutheran voted to disband 
in April, and St. Mary's Catholic Church joined St. Peter's Parish 
in Farmer. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Religion and public policy    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Alan Wolfe, a social scientist and author, has  
been chosen to head Boston College's new Center for Religion and 
American Public Life. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfe, who will become a professor of political science at the  
Jesuit-run school, said he envisions the center as a forum for 
prominent intellectuals and scholars to discuss issues such as 
cloning and euthanasia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Issues of religion and morality have not been central to the  
social sciences,'' Wolfe says. ``We will attempt to fill the void 
... .'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfe has been an instructor of political science for 33 years,  
most recently at Boston University. His books include ``One Nation 
After All.'' 
</P>
