</P>
<P>
 *Episcopalians identify with diversity    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A survey of 2,000 members of the Episcopal  
Church indicates that diversity in belief is nearly as much a mark 
of identity as prayer book worship. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, sponsored by the Episcopal Church Foundation, is to  
be mailed to every parish. It shows that more than 95 percent of 
those interviewed believe communion and liturgical worship 
according to the Book of Common Prayer are central to their 
religious lives. 
</P>
<P>
	On diversity, 78 percent believe members bring ``a wide variety  
of perspectives'' to congregations, and an equal number said 
Episcopalians are ``more likely to ask questions than answer 
them.'' Only 54 percent believe church traditions ``clearly define 
right and wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Living with questions of faith and tolerating ambiguities in  
beliefs are common patterns among many Episcopalians,'' the survey 
concludes. 
</P>
<P>
	The report includes these statistics: Episcopal membership has  
declined 36 percent from a peak of 3.6 million in 1967. However, 
between 1974 and 1997 average attendance rose 31 percent and the 
number of confirmed adults increased 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1991, liquid assets of all Episcopal churches have grown  
from $1 billion to $2.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Same-sex behavior and sexual morality in general are the  
church's most divisive issue, according to the report, though in 
many congregations ``these difficult questions were not the staple 
of daily life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *'Christ-centered' budgets    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Leaders of the Born Again Church passed  
the plate to help members pay their debts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American Dream is not God's dream for America,'' the Rev.  
Horace Hockett said. ``We want to kill the spirit of keeping up 
with the Joneses and teach people to live within their means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Members were asked to put the special offering in an envelope  
and list on the back their debts -- smallest, largest and total. 
About 400 people contributed, ranging from a few dollars to a check 
for $1,900. 
</P>
<P>
	From the pool of donors, church leaders say about 15 people will  
receive about $2,000 each. Recipients must not incur new debt for a 
year and must give a church offering and testify about the power of 
God and a ``Christ-centered'' budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Again leaders believe freeing members from debt will put  
them in a better position to give to Christian causes, including 
the church. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2,500-member congregation would like to build three more  
day-care operations and a new sanctuary and to increase its 
benevolence fund for local people with emergency needs. 
  	   	
</P>
