<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryan White Foundation Close to Broke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Ryan White Foundation, established to  
promote AIDS education after the death of its 18-year-old namesake 
in 1990, is nearly broke and has laid off its staff. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation has nearly deserted its suburban Indianapolis  
offices, leaving behind a message on its toll-free phone line 
saying it is closed for lack of funding. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeanne White-Ginder, White's mother and the group's founder,  
said donations topped $250,000 four years ago but have dwindled 
ever since. Board members also said celebrity support for the 
foundation has slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really been a hard time for the AIDS community,'' she  
said Thursday. ``People are under the misconception that the 
disease is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While its directors insist the foundation is still alive, a bin  
full of uncollected mail sat outside the office door Wednesday. 
Workers at a neighboring office said they last saw two foundation 
volunteers two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Maddox, chairman of the board, said volunteers are reading  
the mail, returning phone messages and mailing out brochures, 
though only sporadically. The board hopes to align with another 
AIDS group that has a more solid funding base. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're probably down to our last $1,000 right now,'' Maddox  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	White, a hemophiliac, contracted the AIDS virus through tainted  
blood-clotting products. He attracted national attention during his 
battle to attend school. 
</P>
<P>
	White received heaps of support from AIDS activists and  
celebrities such as Elton John, and that helped the foundation in 
its early years as it raised money for educational materials and 
Ms. White-Ginder's presentations at schools and conferences. 
</P>
<P>
	But foundation leaders said the group has lost its cause celebre  
status. 
</P>
<P>
	John formed his own AIDS organization in 1991. And Margaret  
Goldsmith, a board member and the wife of Indianapolis' mayor, said 
the last time she saw foundation co-founder Phil Donahue at a Ryan 
White event was nearly five years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
