<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Poll Method </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Associated Press poll on Hillary Rodham Clinton is based on  
telephone interviews with 1,016 randomly selected adults from all 
states except Alaska and Hawaii. The interviewing was conducted 
June 4-8 by ICR of Media, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were weighted to represent the population by key  
demographic factors such as age, sex, region and education. 
</P>
<P>
	In the poll, no more than one time in 20 should chance  
variations in the sample cause the results to vary by more than 3 
percentage points from the answers that would be obtained if all 
Americans were polled. 
</P>
<P>
	This margin of sampling error is larger for responses of  
subgroups, such as income categories. There are other sources of 
potential error in polls, including the wording and order of 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	The AP poll questions (because of rounding, sums may not total  
100 percent): 
</P>
<P>
	1. Is your opinion of Hillary Rodham Clinton favorable or  
unfavorable? 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable, 58 percent; unfavorable, 31 percent; don't know, 9  
percent; refused, 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	2. As you may know, Mrs. Clinton is deciding whether to run for  
the U.S. Senate in New York. Do you think she should run or not? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes should run, 54 percent; no should not run, 34 percent; don't  
know, 9 percent; refused, 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	3. In general, do you think it is appropriate for a president's  
spouse to run for office or do you think it is not appropriate? 
</P>
<P>
	Appropriate, 73 percent; not appropriate, 20 percent; don't  
know, 6 percent; refused, 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	4. In your opinion, which job would allow Hillary Rodham Clinton  
to be most effective in public life after Bill Clinton leaves 
office? 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. senator, 36 percent; head of a foundation, 18 percent;  
writer and lecturer, 19 percent; lawyer, 13 percent; don't know, 12 
percent; refused, 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	5. Is your opinion of Bill Clinton favorable or unfavorable?  
</P>
<P>
	Favorable, 48 percent; unfavorable, 44 percent; don't know, 7  
percent; refused, 2 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
