<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caller to Mobile Phone May Soon Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a move that could attract more consumers to  
mobile phones, the Federal Communications Commission is proposing 
to make it easier for wireless carriers to bill callers rather than 
receivers of mobile-phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission sees the rules as a way to boost use of wireless  
phones and foster competition between providers of wireless and 
regular phone service. The rules, which the FCC hopes to have in 
place by the first quarter of 2000, would enable wireless providers 
to have callers pay for mobile phone calls just as they do with 
regular phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to introduce wireless services to a whole new class of  
consumers,'' FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said in an interview 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, the receiver of a mobile-phone call -- not  
the caller -- typically pays the charges. As a result, many 
Americans switch off their phones to avoid unwanted calls. In 
Europe and Asia, however, it's the caller who usually pays. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed rules, which will be open for comment following the  
today's announcement, don't force wireless carriers to charge 
callers but are supposed to make it easier for them to offer the 
``calling party pays'' service. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the issues the FCC plans to address in reaching a final  
rule is how consumers would know whether they were calling a 
wireless phone, which might mean greater charges than a call to a 
regular line. 
</P>
<P>
	An option is to have a notification voice message that tells  
callers they have reached a wireless number and how much they will 
be charged after they dial a wireless phone. 
</P>
<P>
	Another possibility is to have a prefix number specifically set  
aside for use with wireless phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``The single most important issue we have to deal with is how do  
we protect consumers,'' Kennard said. ``We want to make sure they 
know what they're getting into.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the FCC will work with state regulators and consumer  
groups on how to inform customers of such a service. 
</P>
<P>
	Several companies now provide some form of the caller-pays  
approach, and others have test marketed the service in certain 
states. One issue the wireless industry will have to consider is 
how to handle billing, since companies will be charging callers who 
are not their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC hopes that by offering the service, wireless providers  
will be able to compete more effectively against regular telephone 
providers. Consumers might be more encouraged to use mobile phones 
-- even possibly as their primary phone -- if they do not have to pay 
to receive calls. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wireless phone should be a substitute, not just a complement,  
for wireline phones,'' Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC was also expected to vote on a report today on the  
wireless industry that shows competition growing among providers, 
an increase in the number of subscribers to wireless services and 
lower prices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 01:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
