<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman With AIDS To Set Out on Trail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGOR, Maine (AP) -- Dawn Averitt is packing some of the usual  
items as she starts hiking the 2,160-mile Appalachian Trail: 
sleeping bag, plenty of dried noodles and macaroni, fresh socks, 
bug repellent. 
</P>
<P>
	But she's also toting a lot of medicine on her back.  
</P>
<P>
	Averitt, 30, of Raleigh, N.C., takes 28 pills and liquid  
medications every day to keep AIDS at bay. She is having her 
prescription drugs mailed to two dozen points along the trail for 
the walk from Maine to Georgia she planned to start today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be a little more precise in our planning,'' Averitt  
said on the eve of her hike up mile-high Mount Katahdin, the 
trail's northern terminus and the starting point for what she 
anticipates will be a six-month trek. 
</P>
<P>
	For Averitt, this ``very personal journey'' represents the  
fulfillment of a childhood dream and an affirmation that people 
with AIDS can take on big challenges and meet them. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,500 prospective ``thru-hikers'' set out on the trail  
each of the past three years, but only 300 completed the trip, said 
Brian King of the Appalachian Trail Conference in Harpers Ferry, 
W.Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who have done it include a blind man, diabetics, people  
with kidney transplants and a man with multiple sclerosis who hiked 
the trail three times, King said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Regimbal, 27, of Bar Harbor set out from Katahdin two  
years ago, using the trail name ``Positive Woman,'' a reference to 
her HIV status. But she became sick and had to leave the trail. 
</P>
<P>
	Averitt, the founding director of an advocacy organization for  
women with AIDS, will be accompanied by her brother, a friend and 
her dog, who carries his own food in a red pack. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of hikers travel from south to north. Averitt  
chose to end in her native Stone Mountain, Ga., in hopes of 
arriving in time to spend Thanksgiving with her family in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Averitt traces her disease to a 1988 sexual assault in Spain  
when she was 19. Six months later, she tested positive for HIV and 
was diagnosed with full-blown AIDS five years after that. 
</P>
<P>
	After working for two years in the Washington press office of  
U.S. Sen. Sam Nunn, Averitt returned to Atlanta and founded the 
Women's Information Service and Exchange, a nonprofit organization 
that provides treatment information and advocacy for women with 
HIV. 
</P>
<P>
	Averitt's latest project is the Living Well Fund, an  
organization that helps identify innovative grassroots projects 
worthy of financial support. 
</P>
<P>
	She hopes her upcoming journey will show AIDS is not a death  
sentence and that people can live well, regardless of the 
challenges they face. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mine happens to be AIDS, but everybody has challenges,'' she  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
