<HEADLINE> AP Picks Torchia for S.Korea Bureau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Christopher Torchia, news editor for The  
Associated Press in Jakarta, has been named chief of bureau in 
Seoul, South Korea. Washington newsman Slobodan Lekic will succeed 
him in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointments were announced Thursday by AP President Louis  
D. Boccardi. 
</P>
<P>
	Torchia joined the AP in Albany, N.Y., in 1989 and worked in  
Boston and on the International Desk before transferring to Bogota 
in 1994. He was promoted to news editor in Jakarta three years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Torchia, 31, is a native of Oceanside, N.Y., and a graduate of  
Yale University. 
</P>
<P>
	He succeeds Reid Miller, who is retiring after more than 42  
years with the AP, the last three as chief of bureau in Seoul. 
Miller, 64, was a newsman in Phoenix and Miami and correspondent in 
Pittsburgh and also served as assistant chief of bureau in 
Washington, D.C., and chief of bureau in Salt Lake City, Miami and 
Nairobi. 
</P>
<P>
	Lekic, 48, joined the AP in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in 1988,  
before being assigned to Washington. He is a native of Belgrade and 
a graduate of Belgrade University. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
