<DOCNO> APW19990610.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 06:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Jump by 14,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits shot up last week to the highest level since 
early January. The Labor Department reported today that 323,000 
Americans filed new claims for jobless benefits last week, up by 
14,000 from the previous week. The increase was unexpected. 
Analysts had expected the number of claims for unemployment 
benefits to inch down slightly. Government analysts noted that the 
reporting period included the Memorial Day holiday. Weeks including 
a holiday have often been erratic in terms of the number of people 
showing up in benefit claims offices. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Economy Shows Signs of Growth  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy grew a surprisingly robust 1.9  
percent in the first three months of the year, largely because of 
increased public spending, the government announced today. The 
increase in gross domestic product is the first since the summer of 
1997 and marked an end -- although perhaps only temporary -- to the 
nation's longest recession since World War II. ``Nobody expected 
such high numbers,'' said Akio Yoshino, director of Credit Suisse 
Asset Management in Tokyo. ``Japan's prolonged contraction in the 
economy has at last bottomed.'' Economists in Tokyo had expected, 
on average, a 0.1 percent contraction. Japan's GDP shrank 1.2 
percent in the January-March quarter of 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Bank of England Cuts Interest Rate  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England lowered its base lending rate  
by a quarter of a percentage point to 5 percent today in hopes of 
further encouraging economic growth. The cut, announced after the 
monthly meeting of the bank's monetary committee, resumes a process 
of incremental monthly reductions in the base rate for loans to 
banks. The Bank of England decided in April to hold the base 
lending rate steady at 5.25 percent after having cut it for seven 
consecutive months. The committee based the latest reduction on its 
assessment that Britain's inflation rate was likely to come in 
below the government's targeted level of 2.5 percent, the bank 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cathay Pacific, Pilots Reach Deal  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways and its pilots reached a  
deal today that will cut the cockpit crew's pay in exchange for 
stock options and end a dispute that has grounded hundreds of 
flights. The agreement was reached less than 24 hours before the 
company was threatening to fire its pilots. ``There are no winners 
or losers,'' said John Findlay, general secretary of the Hong Kong 
Aircrew Officers Association. ``This is a victory for common sense, 
for the people and the economy of Hong Kong.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Draft Customer Service Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's major airlines are drafting a  
plan for better treatment of their passengers, a voluntary move 
aimed at holding off more serious mandatory directives from 
Congress. One part of the 12-point plan, a draft of which was 
obtained yesterday by The Associated Press, would commit airlines 
to meeting customers' essential needs during long, on-aircraft 
delays. That would include making ``every reasonable effort to 
provide food, water, restroom facilities and access to medical 
treatment.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Prices Rise  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian shares finished mostly higher today, with  
the big Tokyo market surging ahead despite concerns that U.S. 
interest rates might be on the way up. Prices in Seoul jumped more 
than 6 percent to a nearly two-year high. Hong Kong blue chips 
bucked the trend, retreating modestly late in the session, despite 
an earlier rally on news that mainland China had trimmed interest 
rates. In Tokyo, shares soared 2.9 percent to their highest level 
in a month on optimism that Japan's economy might finally be 
recovering. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 480.12 points 
to 17,102.62. It was the Nikkei's highest finish since May 6, when 
it closed at 17,300.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Sinks 75, Nasdaq Gains 44  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks rallied yesterday, but failed  
to lift the broader market as the threat of higher interest rates 
kept investors on edge and alert to changes in bond market yields. 
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 75.35 to close at 10,690.29, 
extending Tuesday's 143.74-point decline. Broader market indicators 
were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 1.31 to 1,318.64, and 
the Nasdaq composite index, which has a high representation of 
technology stocks, rose 44.79 to 2,519.35. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures as of yesterday's close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,690.29  - 75.35
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1377  Declines 1533  Unchgd  608
NYSE Volume:         630,303,700
Most Active NYSE issue:         AT&AMP;T Corp 53 3/4   +   5/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1318.89  + 1.56
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          772.99  +   .07
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2506.46  - 31.90
Gold(final) -    $260.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 14,000 to 323,000  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Producer prices  

  	   	
</P>
