<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Pushes Europe, Japan on Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Japan's economic growth spurt earlier this  
year does not lessen the need for the world's second largest 
economy to continue efforts to emerge from its worst recession in 
50 years, the Clinton administration said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told reporters the risk that the  
Asian currency crisis will trigger a global recession ``has very 
substantially diminished.'' But, Rubin said, world growth remained 
too lopsided with the United States the only major economy now 
doing well. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong U.S. growth and weak performance elsewhere has pushed  
America's trade deficit to all-time highs, triggering protectionist 
pressures and political headaches for the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said the need for more balanced global growth would come  
up in talks this weekend in Germany with finance ministers from the 
world's seven leading industrial countries -- the United States, 
Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is ... critically important that Europe and Japan do their  
part because the international system cannot sustain indefinitely 
the large imbalances created by the disparities in growth and 
openness between the United States and its major trading 
partners,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan reported Thursday that its economy, which has been mired  
in recession for more than a year, managed to show an unexpected 
spurt of growth in the first three months of this year, an increase 
of 1.9 percent that reflected massive public works spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin played down the significance, saying Japan still faced  
challenges in sustaining economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key is to have in place policies that promote strong  
domestic demand-led growth,'' Rubin said. ``That remains critically 
important for Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said Saturday's discussions were aimed at preparing the  
agenda for the June 18-20 meetings of President Clinton and leaders 
of the other G-7 countries and Russia at their annual economic 
summit in Cologne, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Developments in Kosovo probably will dominate those talks,  
including what donor countries will be willing to contribute to 
reconstruction efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said that Europe, the United States, Japan and the  
international lending agencies such as the World Bank would all 
play a role in that effort but that the Cologne meeting would not 
come up with a formal plan on how to proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic summit also will review efforts to deal with the  
nearly two-year-long global financial crisis, including proposals 
to overhaul the financial architecture to make future Asian-style 
currency crises less likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said the G-7 finance ministers hope to put forward a  
``package of concrete proposals'' for the leaders to consider. But 
he did not indicate there would be any significant new measures 
beyond current efforts in such areas as boosting financial 
disclosure by developing countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The G-7 nations have been unable to resolve a number of  
differences on approach, especially on ways to make sure rich 
investors do not get bailed out when international rescue packages 
are put together. 
</P>
<P>
	The wealthy countries also remain split on the best approach to  
reduce the heavy debt burdens of the world's poorest countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Settles Ohio Radiation Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMISBURG, Ohio (AP) -- The U.S. Department of Energy has  
settled a lawsuit by hundreds of nuclear weapons plant employees 
who say they were exposed to dangerous radiation and not told about 
it for years. 
</P>
<P>
	The department agreed to pay lifetime health insurance coverage  
for as many as 1,800 current and former workers at the Mound 
nuclear plant in the Dayton suburbs. The deal, subject to approval 
by a federal judge, is expected to cost several million dollars, 
depending on insurance costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal requires the Energy Department to provide the coverage  
to Mound workers who contract any of several types of cancer, 
including brain, nervous system, bladder, bone, lung, pancreatic, 
digestive and oral cancers. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant began operating in 1948 and made triggers and  
detonators for nuclear weapons. The Energy Department has halted 
those operations to focus on cleaning up waste at the site, which 
officials want to convert into an office park. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve employees and the Oil, Chemical &AMP; Atomic Workers union  
filed the lawsuit in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement includes no admission of wrongdoing. Energy  
Secretary Bill Richardson said it is intended to address the 
workers' worries about what radiation exposure may have done to 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants were former plant operator EG&AMP;G Mound Applied  
Technologies Inc. and its predecessor, Monsanto Research Corp. The 
Energy Department provided the plant contract. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 09:00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A City Divided: White Sox Vs. Cubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Chicago Cubs pitcher Terry Mulholland usually can  
tell right away if someone is a Cubs fan or a White Sox fan. 
</P>
<P>
	A Cubs fan will say hello, maybe shake his hand and talk for a  
little. A White Sox fan will give him the once-over and that's it. 
</P>
<P>
	It's nothing personal. But in Chicago, a person is either a  
White Sox or Cubs fan. There's no switching allegiances and no 
rooting for both teams. And there's definitely no fraternizing with 
the enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you go into that series, you know it's more than just  
playing another team as far as fans are concerned,'' Mulholland 
said. ``You know people in the stands are hyped up. They have 
greater expectations than most other games so it adds to the 
electricity of the ball park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Williams, a Hall of Famer with the Cubs who's now the  
team's dugout coach, says the rivalry is ``just like 
Alabama-Auburn. You can lose to anybody, but don't lose to the Sox. 
I guess they say the same things over there with the White Sox.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen husbands and wives, sisters and brothers, split  
their allegiances because they want to have something to fight 
about,'' Williams said. ``It's a rivalry for bragging rights for 
the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Which makes this one of the best weekends of the year for  
Chicago baseball fans. Or one of the worst, depending on one's 
loyalty. The first of two Crosstown Series begins Friday at Wrigley 
Field, so Cubs and White Sox fans will be arguing loudly for three 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Who's got the better team, the Kiddie Corps or the Geezers?  
Who's a better power hitter, Frank Thomas or Sammy Sosa? Whose 
bullpen is more dangerous -- and that's not a compliment these days 
-- and which pitcher has the best stuff? Which field is better, 
Wrigley or Comiskey Park? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a city divided for almost a century,'' Cubs first  
baseman Mark Grace said. ``Fans get into it and there will be great 
arguments all around the pubs for that week. It's good stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even for the players, though their passions don't run nearly as  
deep as their fans. They say there's no animosity between the 
teams. Sosa even wore a White Sox uniform for a few seasons, while 
White Sox pitcher Jaime Navarro had some of his best years on the 
North Side. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it comes to this series, there's something special,  
Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be three days of almost 50,000 or whatever you  
can get in the ballpark,'' he said. ``It's not a bitter rivalry. 
It's more, `We think we've got a better team than you,' and that's 
just the way it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas has played for the White Sox his entire career and knows  
exactly what he's in for this weekend. But the rest of the South 
Siders might not. The White Sox have the second-youngest team in 
the majors, and manager Jerry Manuel said it's tough for them to 
fully appreciate the rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, they know bragging rights for the Windy City are at stake  
and they've been told repeatedly how much it means to the fans. But 
just wait until they get to Wrigley on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The South Side and North Side fans don't like each other and  
they get into that series,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs and White Sox have played each other often through the  
years, with the White Sox having a 120-82-6 advantage. But most of 
the games were in spring training or exhibitions, so they don't 
count. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to interleague play, however, they do now. The White Sox  
won the 1997 series at Comiskey and the Cubs responded last year 
with a 3-0 sweep at Wrigley. And this year? 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, the way I look at it, they should beat us because  
of the inexperience of this team and they have a veteran team,'' 
Thomas said. ``But you never know what might happen. There's a lot 
of teams supposed to beat us and we're holding our own.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
