<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, GOP Reach Deal on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House gave divided blessings Thursday to a  
peacekeeping operation in Kosovo after Republicans extracted a 
written promise from President Clinton that it could be performed 
``without harming military readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a 270-155 vote, the House removed from a $288.8 billion  
defense spending bill a GOP-drafted provision that would have 
barred U.S. funds from being used in Kosovo after Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote came moments after Clinton, in a letter to all House  
members, promised to seek congressional authorization for an 
international peacekeeping force expected to include 7,000 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Services  
Committee and the author of the provision that had drawn a 
presidential veto threat, announced the letter would allow him to 
support the effort by Democrats to strip the provision from the 
defense bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall defense bill -- minus the Kosovo restrictions -- was  
passed later on a 365-58 vote. It contains a 4.8 percent military 
pay raise for the year 2000 and measures to beef up security at the 
nation's nuclear labs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress would be the laughing stock of the world,'' if the  
legislation with the restrictions had passed, just a day after the 
dramatic Kosovo peace agreement, said Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, 
the senior Democrat on the House Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Skelton led the effort to strike the offending language from the  
spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In agreeing to remove the restriction on Kosovo funds, the House  
averted what Democrats contended could have been an embarrassing 
predicament on a day when the peace plan was being widely 
celebrated. 
</P>
<P>
	But many Republicans persisted in demanding that Congress  
restrict spending for Kosovo, arguing it was draining other 
military accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	And, even despite Clinton's conciliatory gesture, 142  
Republicans voted to keep the fund cutoff provision in the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a new and perhaps more troubling phase for our  
country,'' Spence said earlier in a day of tense debate. 
``Administration policy has been contentious and confusing, not 
only for Congress but for the American people as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skelton said the president told him he ``fully intends'' to send  
a request to Congress well before Sept. 30 to formally seek funds 
for the peacekeeping operation. He made a similar promise in a 
phone conversation with House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said he should put it in writing, however.  
</P>
<P>
	And late Thursday afternoon, he did.  
</P>
<P>
	In the letter, he said he had directed a detailed review to be  
made of the costs of the peacekeeping operation -- and that he would 
send to Congress ``in a timely manner'' specific legislation 
seeking approval of the funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Skelton said the request would be submitted well before the  
Sept. 30 end of the present fiscal year. More importantly, Clinton 
promised the money wouldn't come from other parts of the Pentagon's 
budget and could be spent ``without harming military readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That seemed to ease the concern of many Republicans, who said  
they were afraid the peacekeeping efforts in Kosovo would further 
strain an already stretched Pentagon budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter ``changed the landscape,'' said John Feehery, a  
spokesman for Hastert. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen said the peacekeeping operation  
is likely to cost U.S. taxpayers $1.5 billion to $2 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart called the effort by  
Republicans to withhold funds from Kosovo ``a classic case of 
trying to snatch defeat from the jaws of victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many House Republicans have been critical of the  
administration's Kosovo policy. In late April, the House declined 
on a tie vote to even support the air campaign that was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Accusing the House of erratic behavior on Kosovo in the past,  
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., told colleagues, ``Now 
we have an opportunity to win the peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some top Republicans conceded they had mixed feelings.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a terrible time to pull the plug. This is not the time  
to give signals of uncertainty,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	But, on the other hand, he questioned why Clinton hadn't  
specifically asked Congress for funds apart from the Pentagon's 
regular budget to pay for the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're doing no favor to the cause of international stability  
by weakening the rest of the military to pay for something that is 
going on in Kosovo,'' Hyde said. 
</P>
<P>
	On other votes, the House approved an amendment to allow  
military troops to assist federal law enforcement in drug 
interdiction and terrorism at U.S. border areas. It was the third 
year in a row the House passed the amendment by Rep. James 
Traficant, D-Ohio, but in the past it died in negotiations with the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	It also approved a measure allowing members of the military to  
put part of their pay into 401(k) type investment plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The underlying bill would also authorize a 4.8 percent military  
pay raise for 2000, up from the 4.4 percent one proposed by 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	It also contains amendments approved on Wednesday that would  
beef up security at the nation's nuclear labs and demand a 
withdrawal of U.S. forces from Haiti by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure will next have to be reconciled with a Senate-passed  
version, which contains many of the same provisions -- although 
without the restrictive language on Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
