<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Energy Rejects Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- A unanimous vote by Columbia Energy Group's  
board of directors to reject NiSource Inc.'s unsolicited $5.7 
billion buyout offer wasn't enough to send NiSource packing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're assessing all of our options now,'' NiSource spokeswoman  
Maria Hibbs said Thursday after Columbia Energy announced its 
decision. ``... The key point is we're not going to go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy contends it isn't for sale.  
</P>
<P>
	``We believe in the future of Columbia as an independent public  
company,'' Columbia Energy chairman, president and chief executive 
Oliver G. Richard III wrote in a letter to NiSource chairman and 
CEO Gary Neale. ``Our decision not to pursue your proposal is 
final.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Richard, Columbia Energy obtained an opinion from  
Salomon Smith Barney ``that the proposed consideration is 
inadequate.'' He said Columbia Energy's board was committed to 
preventing another company from taking advantage of a ``current 
anomaly'' in which the Virginia company's stock value doesn't 
reflect its true earnings potential. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy's shares closed Thursday up 18 3/4 cents to $62 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Merrillville, Ind.-based NiSource made a hostile bid  
of $68 cash for each share in Columbia Energy. The proposed buyout 
would have made NiSource, the parent company of Northern Indiana 
Public Service Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in Massachusetts, one of 
the nation's biggest natural gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy, based in Herndon, Va., had 1998 revenues of  
nearly $6.6 billion. It is involved in natural gas exploration, 
production, transmission, storage and distribution as well as 
propane sales and electric power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Columbia Energy attempted to buy Pittsburgh-based  
Consolidated Natural Gas. But CNG last month rejected the offer to 
proceed with an already-planned merger with Richmond, Va.-based 
Dominion Resources Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Neale had said he hoped shareholder pressure within Columbia  
Energy would force its board to negotiate. At least three 
class-action shareholder lawsuits were filed to get talks going, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Columbia has sophisticated shareholders who understand the  
value of their investment and they told us clearly they wanted 
management to meet with NiSource,'' Ms. Hibbs said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
