<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Americans Seek Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of a House panel that deals with  
the census says it's time that all Americans who live overseas are 
included in the population counts done every 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Only U.S. government employees and their dependents who live  
outside of the United States are counted in the census because 
records of their whereabouts are available. 
</P>
<P>
	The Census Bureau has no plan to include other U.S. citizens  
overseas in the count that begins in April, and a coalition of 
groups representing those Americans wants that changed. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., also wants them to be counted.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have to come up with a way to count overseas citizens,'' he  
said Wednesday at a hearing of his House Government Reform census 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	``They vote and they pay taxes, a lot of them, and they have  
every right to be counted. We need to find a way to do it, 
certainly for 2010,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The Census 2000 Coalition has a plan to include them in the next  
census that is similar to the post card system overseas Americans 
use to vote by absentee ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kenneth Prewitt, the Census Bureau director, said it was too  
late to change the 2000 census without jeopardizing its accuracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff from the bureau recently discussed the plan with coalition  
representatives but concluded that the agency ``cannot credibly 
enumerate the population of American citizens living abroad,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There also are concerns about how to correct invalid responses  
as well as how to conduct what essentially would be a worldwide 
count, Prewitt added. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the number of private American citizens living in  
other countries range from 3 million to 10 million, various 
witnesses testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucy Laederich, president of the Federation of American Women's  
Clubs Overseas Inc., said excluding them from the census means they 
aren't part of the count that is used to redistribute the 435 seats 
in the House after every census. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans abroad accounted for 4 percent of the 1996 vote, she  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	``We care enough to vote and we care enough to assist others in  
voting, and yet the great numbers of overseas Americans are not 
taken into account in the distribution of voting districts,'' she 
told Miller in a letter. ``We believe that it is unbelievably 
unjust to forget these Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prewitt said the bureau tried counting them in 1960 and 1970,  
but was disappointed with the results. He did not rule out future 
counts, however, and told Rep. Carolyn Maloney of New York, the 
panel's top Democrat, that he would support legislation she is 
drafting for a census in 2003 of private Americans overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said Maloney's effort, if enacted, could lay the  
groundwork for including Americans in the census conducted in 2010. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
