<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Jockeys Were 1st Pro Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *AP Sports Writes    	
</P>
<P>
	Ed Hotaling doesn't buy the common belief that baseball players  
in the 1840s were the first pro athletes in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The first pro athletes were black jockeys, ``who were riding  
before George Washington's days,'' Hotaling said in an interview 
about his recent book, ``The Great Black Jockeys: The Lives and 
Times of the Men Who Dominated America's First National Sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hotaling was angered when he was told by someone involved with  
the National Hall of Fame of Racing that the first black race 
riders weren't professionals because they were slaves and were told 
what to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were real jockeys because they wore uniforms,'' Hotaling  
said. ``I found descriptions of uniforms they wore in the late 
1600s'' that were documented in newspaper called the South Carolina 
Gazette. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were professionals because it was their job,'' said  
Hotaling, a writer and producer for the NBC television station in 
Washington, who became interested in black jockeys while writing a 
history of racing at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The skill of slave jockeys and trainers enabled them to cross  
state lines, which was a rigidly enforced taboo of slavery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Great Black Jockeys'' covers their rise and demise and in  
so doing follows the course of racing from the 17th century to the 
early years of the 20th century. There are about 12 black jockeys 
currently riding, none on the highest level, according to Hotaling. 
</P>
<P>
	Black race riders were gradually forced out in this century as  
the sport became more lucrative, Jim Crow laws were enforced and 
blacks migrated to cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Up until the Civil War, racing was bigger in the South than in  
the more puritanical North, and that is why many of the jockeys and 
trainers were slaves, although there were white jockeys and 
trainers. 
</P>
<P>
	It often was plantation owner vs. plantation owner in a match  
race, but such events drew crowds and race meetings developed. Such 
events were well documented. 
</P>
<P>
	``The owners kept track of results because they would sell their  
horses later,'' Hotaling said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotaling documents the famous black jockeys such as Isaac  
Murphy, Willie Simms, Jimmy Winkfield, Lonnie Clayton and James 
``Soup'' Perkins, all major stars in the late 1800s and the early 
part of this century. Murphy won the Kentucky Derby in 1884 and in 
1890-91. Simms won the Derby in 1896 and 1898 in his only tries. 
Winkfield won the race in 1901-02. 
</P>
<P>
	The last black to ride in the Derby was Henry King, who was 10th  
in 1921. 
</P>
<P>
	Even more interesting are Hotaling's tales about slave jockeys  
named Cornelius, Simon and Jesse. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornelius rode the great Boston to 18 wins in 19 races in  
1836-38 at tracks like the Union Course on New York's Long Island. 
All of the races were in three or four-mile heats. 
</P>
<P>
	Simon became a major racing figure in the 1790s and early 1800s.  
</P>
<P>
	As for Jesse, Hotaling writes, ```Hold him, Jesse,' shouted the  
president of the United Sates, Andrew Jackson. Jesse couldn't have 
weighed much more than a hundred pounds, but he was at the controls 
of a 1,000-pound thoroughbred stallion. Jesse was a slave at the 
White House -- and a professional athlete, a rider for the 
president's racing stable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Great Black Jockeys'' was published this year by Forum.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mavericks, Kings Fined Over Salaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks and Sacramento Kings were  
fined $25,000 each by the NBA on Thursday for salary-cap 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Nelson, coach and general manager of the Mavericks, arranged  
for Gary Trent, his fiancee, their infant son, Trent's parents and 
his fiancee's mother to spend a week at his Maui, Hawaii, vacation 
home last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings recently provided several players with an  
expenses-paid trip to Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson said he hoped the vacation would serve as a goodwill  
gesture to the 6-foot-8, 250-pound Trent, whom the Mavericks are 
aggressively trying to re-sign. 
</P>
<P>
	Trent averaged 16 points and 7.8 rebounds this season and was  
third in the balloting for the league's Most Improved Player award. 
His salary this season was $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson has not been bashful in efforts to persuade Trent to  
remain in Dallas. But the Mavericks can't exceed the salary cap to 
re-sign him, so they are limited to paying Trent no more than $5 
million over the next two years. A team can exceed the salary cap 
in re-signing a player only if he has been on the roster three or 
more seasons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
