<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 08:03:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lauds Serb Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is ``very upbeat, very  
satisfied with a job well done,'' the White House said today as 
Serb troops began withdrawing from Kosovo and NATO suspended 
airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 4,000 heavily armed U.S. troops moved toward the  
shattered Balkan province. The U.S. Marines and Army soldiers 
converging on Kosovo's borders are to begin keeping the peace once 
a newly signed agreement takes hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who was expected to spend the day conferring by  
telephone with world leaders, ``is very upbeat, very satisfied with 
a job well done by NATO forces -- both military and diplomatic,'' 
said White House press secretary Joe Lockhart. 
</P>
<P>
	``But also, the president does understand the job that's ahead  
of us as far as implementing this plan and beginning the process of 
returning refugees to their homes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president was in the Oval Office, on the phone with British  
Prime Minister Tony Blair, when national security adviser Sandy 
Berger came in and announced NATO was satisfied with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic's early troop withdrawals and was 
ready to suspend its bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is to travel Friday to Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo.,  
home of the B-2 bombers that flew long-range missions to 
Yugoslavia, to thank U.S. troops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that one MUP unit has left'' Kosovo, Pentagon  
spokesman Kenneth Bacon said this morning, referring to the special 
police forces of the Yugoslav and Serbian Ministry of Internal 
Affairs. ``We'd like to see a lot more flow'' of troops across the 
border out of Kosovo, the spokesman added. He said the police unit 
departed the war-torn Serb province at about 7 a.m. EDT, several 
hours later than NATO had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that the Serb withdrawal is under way, the U.N. Security  
Council will consider a resolution authorizing entry of a 
50,000-strong, NATO-commanded peacekeeping force into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 2,000 Marines aboard ships in the Aegean Sea moved ashore  
in Greece today at about dawn local time before heading overland to 
Macedonia to spearhead the entry into Kosovo. At the same time, 200 
Army troops were to begin flying to Macedonia from U.S. bases in 
Germany, the Pentagon said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Pentagon officials said today that 1,700 Army troops, part  
of an Apache armored helicopter force that has yet to see combat in 
Kosovo, moved by road today from Albania into Macedonia to assemble 
at Camp Able Sentry, the staging area for peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial contingent of U.S. peacekeepers, which will enter  
Kosovo after the first British forces, will have tanks and other 
heavy armor, attack helicopters and other weaponry. Bacon said it 
probably would take at least 24 hours after Serb troops begin 
withdrawing before the lead elements of the U.S. peacekeeping force 
could enter Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Already we are moving our forces to be prepared to go in very  
quickly, so that there will not be any kind of a significant gap 
between Serb forces leaving and the ... (peacekeepers) going in,'' 
Defense Secretary William Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mines will be a chief concern for peacekeepers, along with  
snipers and Serb military stragglers, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	After 78 days of NATO bombing, Yugoslav generals signed a  
military pact Wednesday that laid important ground rules for the 
end of hostilities. Tens of thousands of Serb troops will leave 
Kosovo using approved routes and under a strict timetable, Cohen 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Serbs live up to what they have signed, this will end  
the killing and begin the peace,'' Cohen told a Pentagon news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The military-technical agreement signed in Macedonia Wednesday  
gives Serb troops 11 days to complete a three-stage withdrawal of 
all military and police forces. NATO originally had sought a 
seven-day pullout. 
</P>
<P>
	There are an estimated 40,000 Serb army, police and paramilitary  
forces in Kosovo, where the pre-bombing population of 2.1 million 
was 90 percent ethnic Albanian. Kosovo is the southernmost province 
of Serbia, the dominant republic in the Yugoslav federation. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO began bombing to try to halt alleged Serb atrocities  
against Kosovo residents of Albanian ancestry. NATO planes have 
flown more than 34,000 missions over Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO will monitor the withdrawal of Serb forces in a number of  
ways, including by flying reconnaissance planes and drones. 
</P>
<P>
	Within three days, all Yugoslav aircraft and air defense weapons  
must withdraw at least 15 miles outside Kosovo's borders, and 
within two days the Yugoslav authorities must provide NATO with 
records and locations of all mines and other explosive devices they 
placed in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, the United States will patrol a section of  
southeastern Kosovo with a force of 7,000 Army troops. That force 
will comprise the main American contribution to a 50,000-strong 
NATO-commanded peacekeeping force, dubbed KFOR, to move into Kosovo 
as Serb troops depart. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-term U.S. contingent, dubbed Task Force Falcon, will be  
made up of forces stationed at U.S. bases in Germany. It will 
replace Marine and Army troops sent in to secure the province in 
the first days and weeks of peace. 
</P>
<P>
	It will take about 30 days to move the 7,000 soldiers and  
equipment from Germany, Bacon said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
