<DOCNO> APW19990610.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:40:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, Russia Discuss Kosovo Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian and U.S. officials grappled Thursday with  
the sticky question of Moscow's precise role in the peacekeeping 
operation for Kosovo during talks meant to spell out future 
cooperation with NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott headed a delegation  
trying to forge a compromise on how Russian troops will work with 
forces authorized by the United Nations to secure peace in the 
troubled Yugoslav province. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO says its forces will make up the core, but Russia says it  
will not put its troops under the alliance's command. 
</P>
<P>
	No breakthroughs were announced, though both sides expressed  
optimism that a compromise could be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are tough issues,'' Talbott told reporters. ``It's a  
work in progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Boris Yeltsin, meanwhile, praised NATO's decision to  
suspend its bombing campaign in Yugoslavia on Thursday after his 
government gave preliminary approval to send Russian peacekeeping 
troops into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``A (bombing) pause is good, but it's not enough,'' Yeltsin said  
in statement. ``I evaluate this as the first step in the right 
direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian leader -- who has spoken out strongly against the  
airstrikes since they began in March -- also called for a major 
reconstruction effort in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton spoke to Yeltsin by phone and thanked him for  
Russia's mediation efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Yeltsin's support for the peace plan, many Russian  
political and military leaders have expressed strong opposition, 
charging that Russia yielded to NATO's demands and failed to defend 
Yugoslavia, an ally. Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin defended the 
government's compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Russia made large concessions on Kosovo, but they are  
justified because an end must be put to the war,'' Stepashin told 
visiting 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev gave a ``preliminary  
order'' authorizing the deployment of troops, and an airborne 
brigade of 2,500 was making preparations, the Interfax news agency 
reported. It was not clear when they might reach Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo peace plan calls for up to 50,000 peacekeeping troops  
and NATO insists it will lead the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel very strongly, and I think that our Russian colleagues  
agree, that unity of command is very important, and unity of 
command means that all of Kosovo will be under one command 
arrangement,'' Talbott said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that anything that would undercut or diminish the  
international military presence was not acceptable. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott also said that Kosovo ``has been the single most serious  
test of (U.S.-Russian) relationships since the end of the Cold 
War.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians already take part in a Western-led peacekeeping  
operation in Bosnia, and the United States and its allies envision 
that as the model for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are arrangements, for which there's precedent in Bosnia,  
that would still allow Russian forces to participate,'' Talbott 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials have suggested that Kosovo could be divided  
into sectors for troops from various countries. But U.S. and NATO 
officials have said they don't envision a special ``Russian 
sector'' in Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  N. Korea Soccer Team Holds Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MCAFEE, N.J. (AP) -- Hard by the driving range at the Ballyowen  
golf course, not far from the clubhouse and the first fairway, sits 
a soccer field. One of the club's directors still plays the game 
and convinced his associates to build it. 
</P>
<P>
	They built it, and the North Korean women's soccer team came. On  
Thursday, the Women's World Cup's most secretive squad practiced in 
the midst of rolling green hills and beautiful links. It was a site 
they are never likely to see at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we have a golf course in my country,'' one team  
official said. ``But I am not sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What is for sure is that the Koreans aren't comfortable in the  
media spotlight. Their 20-player roster list includes names and 
uniform numbers. Nothing else. No positions, heights, weights, 
ages, hometowns or international appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one of those players, captain Kim Kum Sil, was made  
available to speak at the lone media session team officials will 
allow. Most of the questions were answered by technical advisers 
and the secretary-general of the North Korean soccer federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must not distract the players,'' secretary-general Ryu Song  
Il said when asked if the players would be mingling with 
Korean-Americans during the tournament. ``Doing any kind of 
activities that might affect players while they are conditioning 
and training is not good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although the players appeared to be having a good time during  
the practice session -- as they jogged a lap, they headed straight 
through the sprinklers that were watering the grass, giggling and 
trying to see who could force the other to get most wet -- Kim said 
they are not yet comfortable with their surroundings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been here six days, and our prime task is to qualify  
for the Olympics in Sydney,'' she said. North Korea must make the 
quarterfinals to have a shot at the 2000 Games. ``A lot of things 
have changed, such as the time change. We are having jet lag and we 
still are not accustomed to the climate change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are trying to get accustomed to them and the things we can  
concentrate on as soon possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only one Korean player, Kim Sun Hui, previously has been to the  
United States. She played in an All-Star game before the draw 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the players, who all wear their hair short and run with  
similar gaits, speak English. Of the 34 people traveling with the 
Korean delegation, only a handful can converse in English. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two chose to do so on Thursday, and one was a translator.  
</P>
<P>
	Ryu, who speaks English, was asked about training facilities  
back home. He was standing perhaps 200 yards from the majestic 
clubhouse when he said: 
</P>
<P>
	``It is true we are suffering at home. It is temporary due to  
natural disasters and unforeseen circumstances. We believe our 
people will overcome those difficulties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not encountered any difficulties in training for the  
World Cup, thanks to the meticulous care of our federation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A member of that federation, Kim Hak-Yong, the team's technical  
official, praised the rapid development of the players, who have 
played Asian power China tight the last two years and beaten Japan, 
the other tournament representative from Asia. North Korea finished 
third in an international event in Bulgaria earlier this year that 
was won by Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The countries we have played have been in the World Cup, and  
this is our first time,'' Kim Hak-Yong said. ``They have more 
experience than us in women's football. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think women's football is one of the sports close to Korean  
women in a physical sense. In elementary schools and higher schools 
we have a football class, and each school district has 
extracurricular activity for football. We have a program to bring 
up the women at all levels and in every age group. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of girls who look forward to becoming a football player  
believe this World Cup is an inspiration to the development of our 
team,'' he concluded. ``There is a bright future for the 
development of women's football in our country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
