<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Football League To Be Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The latest attempt at a pro football alternative  
to the NFL will be unveiled Friday, a new 12-team spring league 
that its sponsors say will begin in February 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 12 owners are singers Wayne Newton and Dionne Warwick  
and among the founders is Dennis Murphy, who was involved the World 
Hockey Association, the American Basketball Association and other 
sports ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been two challenges to the NFL in the last three  
decades -- the World Football League, which played in the late 
summer and fall and lasted two years in the 1970s and the United 
States Football League, which played in the spring from 1983-85. 
</P>
<P>
	The USFL, which produced numerous NFL players and coaches went  
out of business after being awarded just $3 in an antitrust suit 
against the established league. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been talk of other leagues, including one sponsored by  
NBC and Turner Sports after they lost television contracts with the 
NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	This one is called the International Football Federation.  
</P>
<P>
	A similarly named league was introduced at a lavish news  
conference in the 1980s, but never got beyond the announcement 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We blew the budget on the press conference,'' a participant  
explained later. 
</P>
<P>
	The new ITF hopes to put five of its franchises in NFL cities --  
New York, Boston, Chicago, Detroit and Denver. Three more will be 
in locations deserted by NFL teams -- Los Angeles, Houston and 
Orange County, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The other four franchises are listed for Hartford, Conn., San  
Jose Calif., Toronto and Orlando, Fla. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
