<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: UN Troop Deployment Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Plans for moving NATO troops into  
Kosovo from Macedonia on Friday appear to have been delayed. 
Sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity said the operation 
had been pushed back, possibly as many as 24 hours. Troops were 
still at the border at dawn and showed no sign of preparing to move 
out. Without citing a source, a British newspaper, The Daily 
Telegraph, reported the operation was postponed because some 
contributing nations, including the United States, said they were 
not ready. The U.N. Security Council on Thursday approved a 
resolution authorizing a peacekeeping force of as many as 50,000 
troops, including 7,000 Americans. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Cuba Clash Over Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and Cuba on Thursday  
hurled insults and accusations at each other during a Security 
Council discussion of Kosovo. Cuba launched the back-and-forth with 
a speech in support of Yugoslavia that condemned NATO's airstrikes 
as a genocide that served to consolidate U.S. control over the 
world. Deputy U.S. Ambassador Peter Burleigh fired back, saying, 
``Apparently, the well-documented phenomenon of massive ethnic 
cleansing, the terrorization and brutalization of the civilian 
population is not allowed to register on the official Cuban mind.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Vatican Satisfied With Kosovo Plan  
</P>
<P>
	SIEDLCE, Poland (AP) -- The Vatican says its safitsfied with the  
Kosovo peace plan. The endorsement comes despite its criticism of 
the NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia and the Serb 
repression of the Kosovo Albanians. Asked whether Pope John Paul II 
-- who is on a 13-day pilgrimage to Poland -- favored the use of 
international troops in the region, a Vatican spokesman said, 
``naturally, steps must be taken to protect the refugees.'' 

</P>
<P>
	North, South Korea Dispute Continues  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A tense military confrontation between  
North and South Korea moved into its fourth day Friday, when four 
northern naval ships sailed back into disputed waters in the Yellow 
Sea. The North Korean patrol boats again took up positions inside 
the rich crab fishing area before dawn Friday, escorting about a 
dozen fishing boats, the South Korean Defense Ministry said. North 
Korean warships have been sailing in and out of the disputed waters 
since Tuesday. Their main mission appears to be guarding northern 
fishing vessels operating in the area, ministry officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	New E-Mail Computer Virus Spreading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new computer virus was spreading across the  
Internet Thursday, infecting machines by e-mail and ruining 
computer files. Anti-virus teams in the government and at 
universities were trying to determine the severity of the outbreak 
of ``Worm.Explore.Zip.'' General Electric temporarily shut down its 
e-mail system when the virus was detected, but damage was minimal 
because computer personnel were on the lookout for the bug. 
Microsoft cut off its corporate e-mail connection with the Internet 
for two hours as a precaution. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers Can Recycling for House  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House has killed a provision that would  
have required its offices to begin recycling their trash. Following 
objections from Republicans on Thursday, the language was struck 
from a $1.9 billion bill financing Congress' own operations next 
year. The House has had a voluntary recycling program for a decade. 
But The Associated Press reported last month that most 
congressional offices were still mixing garbage, aluminum cans, 
bottles and different grades of paper. Many federal agencies and 
local governments separate their trash and sell recyclable 
material. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Up at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks gained on Friday, spurred by the  
announcement a day before that Japan's economy posted robust growth 
in the first quarter of the year. The Nikkei Stock Average gained 
237.75 points to 17,340.36 at the end of the morning session. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 480.12 points, or 2.89 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Beat Sabres 4-2  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Brett Hull scored the winning goal for the Dallas  
Stars with 2:50 remaining and the Stars staved off a loss by 
beating Buffalo 4-2 Thursday night to even the Stanley Cup series 
at a game apiece. Hull, one of the NHL's top scorers for years but 
absent from the Stanley Cup finals since his rookie year in 1986, 
beat Dominik Hasek with a wicked slap shot from above the right 
circle dot. The goal capped a Dallas comeback that saw the heavily 
favored Stars contained by the Sabres' smothering defense for two 
periods, only to bury Buffalo with 19 shots in the final period. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  

  	   	
</P>
