<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Plans Iowa Straw Poll Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- There are early signs that Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush is working to organize supporters to turn out for 
this summer's Republican straw poll, viewed as an early test of 
strength in a crowded GOP field. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign's approach to the straw poll is one of the first  
tactical decisions Bush must make, and the early signs indicate a 
cautious stance designed to minimize risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides insist that no final decision has been made, but say  
they'd be foolish not to ``do some basics'' to keep their options 
open. 
</P>
<P>
	A phone-bank operation is up and running to identify potential  
backers, as is a direct mail operation and there are reports of 
buses being reserved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know they've done a huge paid telemarketing effort in the  
past week or two,'' said David Kochel, an aide to former Tennessee 
Gov. Lamar Alexander. ``We've gotten all kinds of feedback from our 
supporters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides described the effort as simply laying the groundwork  
should a decision be made to compete intensely in the straw poll. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to do the advance work and you're going to do the  
preparation just so you have that option,'' said Bush spokesman 
Eric Woolson. ``If you don't do some basics that limits your 
options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush faces a dilemma in approaching the high-profile August  
event. He is far ahead in most of the early polls, but doesn't make 
his first campaign swing in the state until this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Other campaigns have been organizing in the state for months and  
even years, and are considerably ahead on that front. If Bush 
chooses to compete in the event, it isn't likely he could match the 
soaring expectations his high poll standings would bring. 
</P>
<P>
	But ignoring the event brings risks as well. By ducking the  
straw poll entirely, Bush risks an embarrassingly poor showing as 
other candidates organize busloads of backers. 
</P>
<P>
	A middle-ground is where Bush has apparently settled, one that's  
been urged by several strategists in the state. That calls for 
quietly organizing backers without a high-profile campaign that 
would raise expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to be serious about it and they're going to be  
putting an effort into it,'' said Bob Haus, an aide to publisher 
Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know they talked to some people about buses,'' said Monte  
Shaw, an aide to former cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	The phone bank operation is the first step in a classic  
organizational tactic of blanketing a state with phone calls to 
identify backers, following up with direct mail and then sending in 
field organizers to turn out identified backers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a way to do things with money you couldn't otherwise do  
with volunteers,'' said Kochel. ``You pay for a bunch of phone 
calls out of a professional center, then you turn that response 
over to a turnout program. Yeah, they're working the straw poll.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a basic technique,'' said Haus.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's been the subject of discussion,'' said Woolson, who  
said no final decision has been made. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
