<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Pfizer Inc. fell 5 3/8 to 99 9/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Investment firms downgraded Pfizer stock after the U.S. Food and  
Drug Administration Wednesday curbed use of the antibiotic Trovan. 
The FDA cited 14 cases of liver failure and six deaths associated 
with the medication. 

</P>
<P>
 *Coach USA Inc. rose 4 3/4 to 38 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Houston-based Coach, an operator of motorcoach and tour  
services, said Wednesday it may be acquired by an unidentified 
party for $42 a share, or $1.07 billion. 

</P>
<P>
 *America Online fell 5 1/2 to 105 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch analyst Henry Blodget predicted AOL will have  
slower-than-expected subscription growth in its fiscal fourth 
quarter. Blodget said subscriber growth in international markets is 
not meeting expectations. 

</P>
<P>
 *Ralston Purina Co. rose 1 13/16 to 29 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	In a widely expected move, Ralston Purina Co. has decided to  
spin off its Eveready battery business to shareholders. Eveready, 
which makes up roughly 40 percent of Ralston's business, has been 
struggling to hold its position as the No. 2 battery maker. 

</P>
<P>
 *Department 56 Inc. fell 5 1/8 to 26 5/8    	
</P>
<P>
	The maker of collectible figurines and gifts says it is unlikely  
to meet its sales goals for 1999. Department 56 said difficulty 
integrating a new system has caused problems in taking customer 
orders. 

</P>
<P>
 *Computer Associates fell 4 7/16 to 47 1/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Analysts at Prudential Securities and Brown Brothers Harriman  
cut their ratings on shares of Computer Associates. Two other Wall 
Street firms, however, maintained ``buy'' recommendations. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *PRI Automation Inc. rose 3 1/4 to 36 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Intel Corp.'s decision to make chips on larger wafers is  
expected to benefit PRI, a maker of robots and automation gear for 
semiconductor plants. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating 
on the stock. 

</P>
<P>
 *Knight/Trimark Group Inc. fell 2 13/16 to 56 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	After a Knight/Trimark executive speculated Wednesday that  
Merrill Lynch might use Knight/Trimark technology for its online 
trades, Merrill Lynch issued a statement saying it has no plans to 
expand its relationship with Knight/Trimark or other firms. 

</P>
<P>
 *MessageMedia Inc. rose 1 9/16 to 12 15/16    	
</P>
<P>
	MessageMedia will acquire Decisive Technology for about $50  
million in common stock. Both companies are Web-based providers of 
customer relationship management technology. 

</P>
<P>
 *Com21 Inc. rose 1 1/4 to 19 3/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Com21 announced a new product Wednesday that uses a cable modem  
to set up and operate virtual call centers, remote offices and 
telecommuting systems. The product will be available in the third 
quarter. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
