<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Device Cos. Surveyed on Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned about risks to patients, the  
government is preparing a list of medical device makers with 
products that could have Y2K problems. In extreme cases, dangerous 
devices will be seized. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration also may issue public warnings  
or suggest voluntary recalls if the agency finds medical devices 
that could malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, the Health and Human 
Services deputy secretary, Kevin Thurm, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He spoke at a hearing of the Senate's special panel on the year  
2000 computer problem. The Senate, meantime, tried to finish work 
on a bill, eagerly sought by business and high-tech groups, that 
would limit the ability to sue over Y2K-related breakdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would give companies a 90-day period to fix  
computer problems before lawsuits can be filed, encourage 
mediation, make it harder to file class action lawsuits and cap 
punitive damages that small businesses must pay. 
</P>
<P>
	A vote on passage was expected Tuesday on the measure, written  
by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., with the help of several Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration supports the idea of stopping frivolous  
lawsuits but has threatened a veto, saying the bill would hurt 
consumers and small businesses with legitimate legal claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA action on medical devices came amid concerns that the  
health industry may be one of the most vulnerable to problems from 
computers that read only the last two digits in dates and mistake 
2000 for 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who with Sen. Robert Bennett,  
R-Utah, heads the special Y2K committee, said many hospitals and 
medical offices have failed to respond to industry surveys on Y2K 
preparedness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tolerating the 'unknown' elements in health care is a  
dangerous policy,'' Dodd said. 
</P>
<P>
	Responses so far to the surveys do not indicate any widespread  
problems that would put patients at risk, Thurm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thurm said the FDA assessment would be finished by Oct. 1, a  
date that an official of the General Accounting Office, the 
investigate arm of Congress, said should be moved up to ensure time 
to deal with troubled equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO's Joel Willemssen said the FDA has developed a draft  
list of about 70 ``computer-controlled potentially high risk 
devices'' that include a powered emergency ventilator, infusion 
pump, glucose test system and fetal cardiac monitor and radiation 
therapy simulation system. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 

</P>
<P>
	The litigation bill is S. 96.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
