<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Says Tyson Can Train There </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Former heavyweight champion Mike Tyson has been  
granted permission to train in Arizona for a boxing match in 
Nevada, possibly in August, Arizona and Maryland officials 
confirmed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he's looking forward to getting back into training  
and boxing,'' said Paul Kemp, an attorney for Tyson. 
</P>
<P>
	Kemp said he does not know when Tyson plans to leave for  
Arizona. He must arrive at least by Monday, when he is to report to 
the Maricopa County Adult Probation Department in Phoenix, said 
John MacDonald, communications officer for the Arizona Supreme 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson, paroled last month until February, pleaded no contest to  
misdemeanor assault charges that stemmed from a fender bender in 
Gaithersburg last August. He will continue with anger management 
counseling, as well as meeting his community service requirements, 
while in Arizona, Maryland corrections officials said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxer last fought in January and was behind on all three  
cards before he knocked out Francois Botha in the fifth round at 
Las Vegas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
