<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miss. Gov. Gets Uninvited Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Gov. Kirk Fordice isn't running for  
re-election, but you wouldn't know it with all the publicity the 
two-term Republican is getting these days. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few weeks after ducking out of the spotlight amid  
questions about his marriage, Fordice threatened a reporter who 
asked him about a European vacation he took with a woman while his 
wife, Pat, remained in Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice, a critic of President Clinton's affair with intern  
Monica Lewinsky, scolded Bert Case after the WLBT reporter asked 
about the vacation with a Memphis, Tenn., widow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me tell you something, you invade my privacy this way, six  
months from now, I'll whip your a--,'' a red-faced Fordice told 
Case, according to a videotaped recording of Tuesday's 
confrontation. ``You have no damn business playing these games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest furor follows recent attention given to Fordice's new  
home -- one Mrs. Fordice said she was never invited to -- and the 
1996 car crash hours after the governor was seen having lunch with 
a woman while his wife was out of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice, 65, leaves office in about six months because of term  
limits. He has said he has no interest in higher office. 
</P>
<P>
	Caller after caller to Wednesday's ``Supertalk'' program on  
radio station WFMN said Fordice should resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety-nine percent were hard on him,'' said Paul Gallo, after  
callers used words like ``hypocrite,'' ``buffoon'' and ``national 
embarrassment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Mississippians are generally very forgiving people. It's the  
inflammatory, in your face, don't-give-a-hoot attitude that people 
have found very offensive,'' Mississippi Baptist leader Paul Jones 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Friedeman, a minister and conservative columnist who urged  
Fordice to step down, said presidential candidate Dan Quayle might 
reconsider having the governor as a national campaign cochairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle's communications director, Jonathan Baron, said the  
former vice president will talk to Fordice soon, and ``until they 
have a conversation it will be inappropriate for me to comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor had completed his recent European trade mission and  
was joined on vacation by Ann G. Creson, WLBT reported, citing 
travel agency documents. The two spent several days touring France 
and were photographed together in the Memphis airport upon their 
return last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Press secretary Robbie Wilbur said Tuesday that Fordice made  
arrangements for the trip. Wilbur did not return phone calls 
Wednesday, and Mrs. Fordice's assistant said she had no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice and his wife's marital troubles date to 1993, when he  
announced they were having ``irreconcilable differences.'' A day 
later, she issued a statement saying she would continue serving as 
first lady unless forced out. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Mrs. Fordice said her husband of 44 years had  
bought a $230,000 home outside Jackson and never invited her to see 
it. She said she did not want a divorce, though she knew her 
husband's new home ``wasn't for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors have said Fordice spends his weekends there, but they  
refuse to talk about other occupants. Fordice and the first lady 
both live in the official governor's mansion during the week. He 
has simply said the home is part of his private life. 
</P>
<P>
	Creson wouldn't comment Wednesday. Her husband of 43 years, Roy  
Franklin Creson Jr., died in November from cancer at age 66. He was 
the retired owner of Creson-Watson Manufacturing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice and Creson were sweethearts in junior high school in  
Memphis and became reacquainted at a reunion in 1992, the year 
before the governor disclosed ``irreconcilable differences'' with 
his wife, WLBT said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, the governor crashed a state-owned car after he  
was seen having lunch with a woman near Memphis while his wife was 
in France. A waiter recalled serving wine to the governor and his 
female companion. It was never firmly established whether the woman 
was Creson. 
</P>
<P>
	Passers-by pulled Fordice from his car after it careened off a  
highway and caught fire. He was hospitalized for three weeks with a 
bruised heart and lung, fractured vertebrae, several broken ribs 
and a broken collarbone. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice has said he does not remember why he was in Memphis that  
day. 
</P>
<P>
	Some state Republicans wonder if Fordice's support is what they  
need for upcoming elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any candidates are going to closely associate  
with him,'' said Alvin Endt, a GOP state representative from Ocean 
Springs who has supported Fordice. ``They're not going to ride his 
coattails after this. If they do, they're crazy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
