<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chevron, S.Africa Firm Work on Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Chevron Corp. has formed a joint venture  
with the South African firm Sasol Ltd. for worldwide use of a 
technology for converting natural gas to a more easily used and 
transported liquid. 
</P>
<P>
	The union could make Chevron one of the industry's most  
aggressive players in the emerging gas-to-liquids business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gas-to-liquids technology is so promising that its development  
could create an entire paradigm shift throughout the petroleum 
industry,'' said Richard Matzke, president of Chevron Overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	He said trillions of cubic feet of natural gas is available in  
vast but hard-to-reach reserves, too far from markets to be 
captured and transported at a profit. Converting it to a liquid 
means it can be profitably produced and more easily and cheaply 
moved to world markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing about natural gas is that it's very abundant, and  
the price reflects that,'' Collins &AMP; Co. analyst Brian L. 
Eisenbarth said Thursday in San Francisco. ``You have to keep costs 
down as low as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies, including Royal Dutch/Shell Group, Exxon Corp.  
and BP Amoco PLC, are working on similar technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Sasol, the world's largest synthetic-fuel producer, is based in  
Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	A Chevron spokeswoman said the company anticipates spending  
billions of dollars to develop the technology. Competitors say if 
Chevron follows through, it could be the leader in the fledgling 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron is building a conversion plant in Nigeria, which is set  
to be completed in 2002. The $1 billion project, also with Sasol, 
will be the largest natural-gas-to-liquids project in the world. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
