<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee State Shakes Up Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee State University is firing one  
official and moving assistant football coach Johnny Cole out of the 
athletic department because of rule violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The school hopes the moves will keep the NCAA from taking  
harsher action against the school. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves follow a four-month investigation by the school into  
eight allegations of infractions of NCAA rules. The allegations 
dealt with scholarships, recruiting, practice limits, monitoring 
and coach conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that the recommendations are meaningful. They are  
substantial,'' Anita Jenious, chairwoman of Tennessee State's 
investigative committee, said Wednesday. ``Certainly we can't 
speculate as to what the committee on infractions will decide, but 
we do believe that these actions that we recommended ... are very 
strong and a step in the right direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne Bell, Tennessee State's NCAA compliance coordinator, will  
be fired as of June 21. And effective July 1, head coach L.C. Cole 
will be put under a pay freeze and recruiting restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The school is also limiting its season to 38 recruitment visits  
for the next two years and cutting out two football scholarships 
for the next three years. It will also increase staffing and 
improve monitoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Two athletic directors have already lost their jobs over the  
infractions, and an assistant coach has been reprimanded. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee State denied one allegation and took no position on  
two others. 
</P>
<P>
	The school will appear before the NCAA Division I Committee on  
Infractions at its September meeting in Tucson, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee State denied having too little control over the  
football program, and it took no position on allegations that L.C. 
Cole gave money and free game tickets to a University of Alabama 
student he was recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnnie Cole will be reassigned to the school's division of  
student affairs July 1 and is barred from taking part in student 
athletics. His future at the school will be determined in December. 
If he returns as coach, he would have to attend rule compliance 
seminars. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been on two years probation since last fall and was  
barred from one conference game. 
</P>
<P>
	His brother, L.C. Cole, also has been on probation since the  
fall, was suspended from one conference game and must attend rules 
seminars. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee State also promised to fill vacant positions, and if  
the Tennessee Board of Regents approves, the athletics department 
will report to the president's office. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
