<DOCNO> APW19990610.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 13:20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Pacific, Pilots Reach Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Averting a showdown that could have led to a  
strike or the mass firing of Cathay Pacific Airways pilots, the 
airline and union reached a deal Thursday that cuts salaries in 
exchange for stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots said they got a slightly better deal than what Cathay  
offered earlier, ending a dispute that had grounded hundreds of 
Cathay flights over the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay had been demanding that pilots take pay cuts of 7 percent  
over the next two years but said they could have stock options to 
cash in when the company's fortunes turn around. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline has suffered serious losses because of the Asian  
economic crisis and Hong Kong's recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The highly paid senior pilots will have to take those cuts but  
junior pilots can expect salary increases of 3 percent to 5 percent 
over the next three years, said Tony Tyler, Cathay's director of 
corporate development. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cathay Pacific has achieved what we set out to do,'' Tyler  
said. ``In the end, all the ingredients were there to come to an 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay stands to save $180 million over the next decade, he told  
a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no winners or losers,'' insisted John Findlay,  
general secretary of the pilots union, the Hong Kong Aircrew 
Officers Association. ``This is a victory for common sense, for the 
people and the economy of Hong Kong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay had persuaded flight attendants to agree to concessions  
earlier in the year but ran into a tougher fight against the 
pilots, who began calling in sick en masse, saying they were too 
stressed to fly. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute devastated Cathay's flight schedule for nearly two  
weeks, affecting more than 85,000 passengers in and out of Hong 
Kong's Chek Lap Kok airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay canceled 75 of its 119 flights on Thursday, for example,  
but said it had hired other airlines to fly 46 of the services on a 
charter basis to keep as many passengers as possible in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay could not say when it will be able to operate a full  
schedule, though Tyler said the company would bounce back ``as 
quickly and as efficiently as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyler said it was too soon to say how many millions of dollars  
Cathay lost in the sickout. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots approved the deal in a special meeting Thursday  
night. Findlay said the union had gotten a slightly better deal on 
the payout of the stock options, and he predicted the agreement 
could bring a quick end to the sickout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope things will return to normal as soon as possible,''  
Findlay said outside Hong Kong's Labor Department, where government 
officials had brought the two sides together. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
