<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Announces Halt to Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- NATO today suspended its airstrikes  
against Yugoslavia after verifying the withdrawal of Serb forces 
was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``A few moments ago I instructed Gen. Wesley Clark to suspend  
NATO's air operations,'' said NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana. 
</P>
<P>
	``The withdrawal of Yugoslav security forces from Kosovo is  
taking place in accordance'' with the peace implementation deal 
worked out between NATO and Yugoslavia on Wednesday, Solana added. 
NATO began the allied air campaign on March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the first troops of the international peacekeeping force  
would deploy in a few hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``If everything goes okay ... tomorrow we may see the first KFOR  
(Kovoso peacekeeping) soldiers deployed in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The signoff in the allied air campaign was required in  
accordance with the peace accord that the commander of NATO troops 
in Macedonia, Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, signed late Wednesday in 
Macedonia after long and tortuous talks with his Yugoslav 
counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's formal ending of the air campaign came just hours after  
the first Serb forces left Kosovo in a convoy to comply with the 
peace agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Allied troops, meanwhile, were flowing into the Balkans today in  
preparation for deployment in Kosovo, where some 860,000 ethnic 
Albanians have fled -- most to Albania and Macedonia -- since March. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said 1,200 extra troops had moved to Macedonia in the past  
24 hours, bringing to 18,500 the level of allied troops in Kosovo's 
southern neighbor. It said the buildup will continue rapidly over 
the next few days as some 50,000 troops form the Kosovo force 
assemble. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO was already scaling down its air attacks before today's  
announcement. The alliance said its planes flew only 60 strikes 
over the previous 24 hours, compared to several hundred at the 
height of the 78-day bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news agency reported that the last  
air strikes occurred in the early evening Wednesday, when the city 
of Urosevac in southern Kosovo was hit, several hours before the 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The enemy aircraft fell silent after that,'' said Tanjug.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
