<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Resolves Patent-Law Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court resolved a major patent-law  
dispute in the government's favor today, narrowing a specialized 
court's authority to second-guess federal officials' decisions on 
which inventions deserve patent protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-3 ruling said such decisions by the Patent and Trademark  
Office must be given more deference by a federal appeals court that 
specializes in technical cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than being able to overturn the office's patent decisions  
if they are ``clearly erroneous,'' the U.S. Court of Appeals for 
the Federal Circuit must employ a more deferential standard 
included in a federal law, the Administrative Procedures Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Under that standard, the appeals court can overturn a Patent and  
Trademark Office decision only if it is deemed ``arbitrary, 
capricious'' or ``unsupported by substantial evidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case decided today began with a 1990 patent application nine  
people filed for a method of improving security for computer 
transactions, such as credit card purchases or banking on the 
Internet. They assigned their interest in the invention to Compaq, 
based in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patent and Trademark Office denied the application, saying  
the method was merely an obvious variation of previous inventions. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruled  
that the patent office was wrong and the patent must be issued. 
That court relied on its longstanding practice of reversing patent 
office decisions found to be ``clearly erroneous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Circuit said its traditional, less-deferential  
standard encouraged the patent office to state more clearly its 
reasons for granting or withholding a patent. 
</P>
<P>
	In appealing to the Supreme Court, the government said the  
Federal Circuit used the wrong standard. A majority of the justices 
agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We conclude that (the Administrative Procedures Act) does  
apply, and the Federal Circuit must use the framework set forth in 
(it),'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Anthony M.  
Kennedy and Ruth Bader Ginsburg dissented. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Lehman vs. Zurko, 98-377.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
