<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Cuts Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England on Thursday lowered its base  
lending rate by a quarter of a percentage point to 5 percent -- its 
lowest level in 22 years -- in hopes of further stimulating economic 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The cut, announced after the monthly meeting of the bank's  
monetary committee, resumes a process of incremental monthly 
reductions in the base rate for loans to banks. The Bank of England 
decided in May to hold the base lending rate steady at 5.25 
percent, after having reduced it in six of the previous seven 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee based the latest reduction on its assessment that  
Britain's inflation rate was likely to come in below the 
government's targeted level of 2.5 percent, the bank said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to push rates to their lowest level since 1977 took  
financial markets by surprise. Neil Parker, an economist at The 
Royal Bank of Scotland called the move a mistake made in response 
to the continued strength of the British pound. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel that to set monetary policy on the basis of a volatile  
instrument such as the pound can only mean extra volatility in 
interest rate markets,'' Parker said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But labor unions, which complain that a strong pound hurts  
British exports and endangers industrial jobs, applauded the move. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Bank has shown clear vision and foresight,'' said John  
Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress. He said 
British interest rates were still higher than those in continental 
Europe but that Thursday's cut ``takes us a heartening step 
closer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unions and manufacturers say higher interest rates in Britain  
are a major reason for the strong pound, which makes British-made 
goods more expensive than competing products denominated in the 
euro and other currencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
