<HEADLINE> Former Conde Nast President Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Robert J. Lapham, president of  
Conde Nast Publications during the period in which it added the 
magazines Gentleman's Quarterly, Self, Vanity Fair and Gourmet, has 
died at 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Lapham died last Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	After stints with Seventeen and Esquire, Lapham joined Conde  
Nast in 1954 as West Coast advertising and office manager for Vogue 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1961, he moved to New York to become Conde Nast's advertising  
director. Later, he became general manager, then vice president and 
was appointed president in 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was a former board member and vice chairman of the  
Magazine Publishers Association and was chairman of the Publishers 
Information Bureau. 
  	   	
</P>
