<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About hearing Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts about hearing loss:  
</P>
<P>
	--You hear when the outer ear funnels sound waves into the ear  
canal, where they strike the eardrum and cause it to vibrate. Tiny 
bones in the middle ear conduct the vibrations to microscopic hairs 
in the inner ear, where they're converted to nerve impulses that 
the brain deciphers as sound. 
</P>
<P>
	--A number of conditions can cause hearing to deteriorate. Often,  
aging and noise are culprits. Symptoms include trouble hearing 
conversations, particularly in crowded or noisy rooms; asking 
people to repeat themselves; missing the doorbell or telephone; 
having people complain that you keep the TV too loud. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hearing aids often help. A doctor or audiologist, a specialist  
in hearing, first must test to determine the type of hearing loss 
and then fit an appropriate aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizations such as the American Speech-Language-Hearing  
Association in Rockville, Md., or the National Council on the Aging 
or Better Hearing Institute, both in Washington, can help patients 
find hearing professionals or additional information. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
