<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Pact Signed Ending Kosovo Conflict  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After 78 days of NATO bombing, Yugoslav  
generals signed a military pact yesterday outlining rules for the 
end of hostilities. Tens of thousands of Serb troops will leave 
Kosovo using approved routes and under a strict timetable, Defense 
Secretary William Cohen said. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said 
it probably would take at least 24 hours after Serb troops begin 
withdrawing before the lead elements of the U.S. peacekeeping force 
could enter Kosovo. NATO began bombing to try to halt alleged Serb 
atrocities against Kosovo residents of Albanian ancestry. NATO 
planes have flown more than 34,000 missions over Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	New Grave Site Spotted in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Aerial photographs taken weeks apart show what  
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon identified yesterday as a mass 
grave site in west-central Kosovo. The first picture, taken May 15, 
shows neat lines of what apparently are individual graves. The 
second, taken June 3, shows only a dark splotch where the graves 
had been. NATO and humanitarian groups have identified a half-dozen 
or more suspected mass grave sites in Kosovo, where Serb forces are 
accused of massacres, systematic rape and other atrocities against 
ethnic Albanians. NATO began bombing March 24 to stop alleged Serb 
aggression. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan's Economy Said To Grow  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- After five quarters of contraction, Japan's economy  
grew in the first quarter of the year, according to a report 
released today that attributes the expansion to increased public 
spending. Gross domestic product grew 1.9 percent in the 
January-March quarter from the last quarter of 1998, said the 
report Japan's leading economic newspaper. The Economic Planning 
Agency was to officially announce the figures at 0630 GMT. 

</P>
<P>
	Rubin Warns of World Economy Threat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A devastating chain-reaction of trade  
protectionism may be set off by Congress if a bill to sharply limit 
foreign steel shipments into the United States is pushed ahead, 
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned yesterday. Delivering what 
is expected to be one of his last speeches as a member of President 
Clinton's Cabinet, Rubin said he was worried about demands for the 
erection of trade barriers in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Vote Count Continues in Indonesia  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police tightened security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count aroused anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging was again plaguing the 
country. Election officials denied any improprieties, saying they 
have been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in Monday's 
parliamentary election, billed as the country's most democratic 
vote in 44 years. By today, unofficial results released to 
journalists showed that 8.2 percent of the votes had been 
tabulated, a fraction of what had been promised. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Close Up  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues closed at  
17,102.62 points on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, up 480.12 
points from Wednesday. 

</P>
<P>
	New Moms Stay Longer in Hospital  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New mothers are staying in the hospital about  
half a day longer on average, says the first study since a public 
outcry over ``drive-by deliveries.'' The trend began even before a 
federal law requiring insurance coverage of 48-hour stays went into 
effect. In the early 1990s, many insurance companies began paying 
only for 24-hour hospital stays for vaginal childbirth, but doctors 
say first-time mothers who generally have longer labors and more 
questions about newborn care often need a second day. Following 
complaints about inadequate care, states began passing laws 
requiring insurance to pay for 48-hour stays. 

</P>
<P>
	Royals Crown Cardinals 17-13  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Mark McGwire hit one of his longest home  
runs of the year in a losing cause as Joe Randa went 5-for-5 and 
the Kansas City Royals scored eight in the eighth to beat St. Louis 
17-13 last night. With one on and two outs in the fifth, McGwire 
hit a drive that witnesses said bounced off the last row of seats 
in the left-field bleachers and rolled almost to the concession 
stand. McGwire's second homer in two days and 19th of the year 
trailed only the 484-foot monster he hit on May 22 at Los Angeles 
and a 435-footer on June 3 at Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Beat Pacers 101-94  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Undaunted by an early 14-point deficit, the  
New York Knicks put together one of their best all-around games of 
this postseason and stunned the Indiana Pacers 101-94 Wednesday 
night. The win gives the Knicks a 3-2 lead in the Eastern 
Conference finals and a chance to win the series at home Friday 
night in Game 6. Marcus Camby came off the bench to provide 21 
points and 13 rebounds, while Latrell Sprewell took the ball to the 
hoop with a vengeance and scored 29. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
