<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Labonte Brings Momentum to Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- If success breeds success, Bobby Labonte  
figures to be the driver to beat in the NASCAR Kmart 400 at 
Michigan Speedway Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte, who won twice at this 2-mile banked oval in 1995, had  
been running well this season for the Joe Gibbs team. But he hadn't 
been winning until last week when he drove his Pontiac to a victory 
at Dover, Del. 
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence means a lot in racing, just like it does in other  
sports,'' Labonte said Thursday. ``We were able to build off past 
weeks to get to last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing wrong with coming in to Michigan with a win,  
no matter where it was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The difference at Dover was a set of shocks Labonte borrowed  
from teammate Tony Stewart's car. 
</P>
<P>
	They worked so well that Labonte set a track record at Dover  
Downs International Speedway while earning the pole for the MBNA 
Platinum 400. 
</P>
<P>
	The car's setup for the Michigan track will be different, but no  
less important. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to get your car set up right here,'' Labonte said.  
``That's the big thing, to get good power and a good setup. We've 
been fortunate, we've run well every time we've been here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte gives much of the credit to Jimmy Makar, his crew chief  
since 1995 when he joined the Gibbs team. 
</P>
<P>
	In his win at Dover, a key call by Makar played a major role in  
the triumph. Makar brought in Labonte to top off his fuel tank just 
before the end of the final caution period on lap 293. 
</P>
<P>
	It was just enough to get him to the finish.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like gas-mileage racing because you want to have the  
fastest car and run away,'' Labonte said. ``But it was a great call 
by Jimmy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision cost Jeff Gordon the Dover race for the second  
straight year. He was forced to stop for a splash of gas with five 
laps remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is hoping to win on pure power at the bigger, faster  
track in Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those deals where we like coming to this track,''  
Labonte said. ``It seems like we've got a good setup for it and 
good combination for it between Jimmy Makar and myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is third in the Winston Cup point standings with 1,915.  
Dale Jarrett is first with 1,984 and Jeff Burton, a three-time 
winner, has 1,933 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been competitive week in and week out,'' Labonte said.  
``We've had some decent finishes, and we haven't had too much bad 
luck. We hope we can keep it going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Martin, the defending champion in this race -- the 14th of  
34 this season -- is fourth in the standings with 1,854 points. 
Martin, after a career-best seven victories last year, has won only 
once this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Gordon, he could be in the right place to start making  
things happen. Martin, second to Gordon last season, has won four 
times at Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte's teammate, Stewart, is fifth with 1,700 points. Gordon,  
last year's Winston Cup points champion, is sixth with 1,645 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, who has had a run of bad luck lately, won at Michigan  
last August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
