<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More People Shoud Use Hearing Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Do you frequently ask people to repeat  
themselves, have trouble following conversations at a party or get 
complaints about your loud TV? 
</P>
<P>
	You might need a hearing test.  
</P>
<P>
	Experts say hearing aids could help many of the 19 million  
Americans over age 45 who have hearing loss -- but an estimated 
three out of five patients over 65 and six of seven middle-aged 
patients don't use them. 
</P>
<P>
	Why? A major new survey of 2,300 hearing-impaired people found  
denial, embarrassment and cost all play a role. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors say these people should take a closer look. They're no  
longer selling your grandfather's hearing aid. Just in the last two 
years, hearing-aid technology has boomed, with new digital models 
that can put the processing power of a laptop computer deep into 
the ear canal. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem: Hearing aids can be very expensive -- from $700 for  
a good but no-frills traditional model to $5,000 for a pair of 
hidden-inside-the-ear digital aids -- and most insurance does not 
pay for them. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet demand is poised to surge as baby boomers age. Not only does  
hearing loss often come with aging, the baby boomers are suffering 
earlier than their parents did thanks to noisier surroundings. Loud 
music, jet planes, city traffic -- they all take a toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over time, as you're exposed to more and more noise, it's  
putting more stress on the auditory system,'' says audiologist Tomi 
Browne of Alexandria, Va. ``We are seeing more and more folks in 
their 40s and 50s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why no insurance coverage? Insurance traditionally pays ``for  
the catastrophic costs associated with illness,'' says Richard 
Coorsh of the Health Insurance Association of America. Adding 
hearing aids would be pricey. ``It boils down to whether a group 
wants to pay for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But too many people don't realize hearing loss has serious  
health consequences, contends James Firman of the National Council 
on the Aging. The council's new survey of 2,300 hearing-impaired 
people found those without hearing aids were more likely to be 
depressed, anxious and isolated from society. 
</P>
<P>
	More than two-thirds of nonusers said their hearing wasn't bad  
enough for an aid even though 36 percent did wonder why relatives, 
tired of repeating themselves, frequently snap at them. One in five 
said hearing aids would make them feel old or be embarrassing. Half 
cited cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Key to a good hearing aid is testing by a professional to  
uncover your type of hearing loss, and then getting an appropriate 
hearing aid fitted properly, said Harry Sauberman, who oversees 
hearing aids for the Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not fit properly, the best hearing aid will not  
function,'' he stressed. 
</P>
<P>
	Your choices:  
</P>
<P>
	--Traditional analog aids amplify all sound.  
</P>
<P>
	--Programmable aids are computer programmed to match a patient's  
specific hearing loss. You may need only high-frequency sounds 
amplified, or need to hear conversation in a noisy restaurant 
without the background noise amplified. 
</P>
<P>
	--Digital aids are more computerized, automatically adapting to  
different listening environments for greater clarity. 
</P>
<P>
	Size varies dramatically. Aids that squeeze deep into the ear  
canal typically have enough power for moderate hearing loss and 
cannot be seen. But they have tiny batteries that need frequent 
replacement, a drawback for people with dexterity problems. 
Slightly bigger aids sit in the outer ear, and behind-the-ear 
models are very visible but may be vital for more severe hearing 
loss. 
</P>
<P>
	While digitals and in-the-ear models are hot sellers, Sauberman  
cautions that only with hearing tests and trying on different 
models can you find the aid best for you. 
</P>
<P>
	You may need repeat visits to fine-tune and adjust the hearing  
aid for maximum performance. But in most states, you can return a 
hearing aid for a refund within 30 days if it does not fit or work 
properly. 
</P>
<P>
	Firman warns against buying cheaper mail-order hearing aids  
because there's no way to get a proper fit or fine-tuning. If a 
hearing aid is out of reach financially, groups like the Lions 
Clubs offer financial assistance in many cities, and hearing 
centers and aging organizations offer information on such programs. 
</P>
<P>
	And while hearing aids help significantly, they ``will never  
restore the normal hearing you once had,'' Sauberman cautions, 
saying too-high expectations often frustrate users. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
