<DOCNO> APW19990610.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Tests TV's Fairness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was the kind of feel-good national exposure  
most politicians can only dream of: a few minutes on the ``Today'' 
show, collecting musical instruments for charity while chatting 
with Katie Couric and Matt Lauer. 
</P>
<P>
	Standard work for a first lady. But now that Hillary Rodham  
Clinton has inched closer to a Senate candidacy, such appearances 
become an awkward test of how practices that ensure political 
fairness on TV apply. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all uncharted territory,'' said Jeff Zucker, executive  
producer of ``Today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton consented to a brief sit-down interview with  
Couric, during which she revealed her enthusiasm for the New York 
Knicks. Her appearance was organized through Save the Music, a 
charity started by the cable network VH1 that distributes recycled 
musical instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing outside the show's storefront studio in Rockefeller  
Center, she made small talk with the tourists who come to watch the 
show each day. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is beautiful. Is this yours?'' she asked a woman who was  
donating her grandmother's violin. Mrs. Clinton said she had 
already donated one of her husband's saxophones. 
</P>
<P>
	Out of fairness, Zucker said that he had unsuccessfully sought  
to have New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani appear this week on 
the show. Giuliani, a Republican, is considered a possible opponent 
if Mrs. Clinton runs for the Senate in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that she's a potential candidate, you do have to think of  
things like this,'' he said, ``and we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Executives at ABC briefly talked about the impact on a  
prospective campaign when ``Good Morning America'' was invited to 
televise a town meeting on teen violence from the White House two 
weeks ago with President and Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The importance of the issue in the wake of Littleton outweighed  
the political considerations, said ABC News President David Westin. 
Future decisions will be made on a case-by-case basis, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, one of the factors we will take into account is if  
it is more a matter of image in a political race or if it's 
newsworthy,'' he said. ``If it's newsworthy, we have to cover it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal equal time provisions, which ensure broadcasters give  
fair exposure to candidates, didn't apply to Mrs. Clinton's 
``Today'' appearance on Thursday for three reasons, said Andrew J. 
Schwartzman, president of the Washington-based Media Access 
Project. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules don't kick in until a person is a declared candidate.  
Even if Mrs. Clinton had declared, only other Democrats would be 
entitled to equal time until the party determines its nominee, 
Schwartzman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, NBC has a Federal Communications Commission  
exemption for the ``Today'' show that affects most political 
interviews, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is clearly benefiting from a journalistic  
honeymoon, said Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media 
and Public Affairs in Washington. In recent months, evening news 
shows have run 28 stories about her potential Senate candidacy and 
six stories about Vice President Gore's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would think the morning news shows would act more like  
journalism instead of entertainment puff shows,'' Lichter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zucker said if Mrs. Clinton appears on ``Today'' again, it will  
be in a political interview. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 18:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olson's Struggles Hurt Diamondbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Gregg Olson's recurring late-inning failures have  
created a big problem for the Arizona Diamondbacks, who aren't sure 
where to turn for relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Olson's six blown saves in 14 chances have left manager Buck  
Showalter with no certain closer, a gaping hole for an ambitious 
team that thinks it can make the playoffs in just its second year 
of existence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we've struggled in those situations this year,''  
Showalter said. ``We're going to take each situation as it comes. 
Oly has pitched real well at times and has struggled at times. I'm 
well aware of that, and it's a job you can't afford to have a lot 
of inconsistency in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That inconsistency was never more apparent than Tuesday night  
against the Chicago Cubs, when Olson entered with a runner at 
third, no outs and Arizona ahead 3-2. Olson struck out Sammy Sosa 
and got Glenallen Hill to pop out. 
</P>
<P>
	He walked Henry Rodriguez intentionally, then threw a fat pitch  
over the plate that pinch-hitter Tyler Houston sent over the 
right-field fence for a three-run homer. The Cubs went on to win 
5-3. 
</P>
<P>
	If they give up on Olson, whose confidence seems to be shaken,  
the Diamondbacks aren't loaded with options. There aren't any 
proven closers out there to be acquired, and Arizona's young farm 
system isn't loaded with prospects. The Diamondbacks are extremely 
reluctant to give up any of the few they have. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at all the options to address it,'' general  
manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``We're looking at every way to go 
at it, whether it's from within or looking at other teams. But 
people who have good closers, they're not anxious to give them 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks might try to pry away a reliever from one of  
the teams that have depth in the bullpen, such as Cincinnati, 
Pittsburgh or the New York Mets. But there's no guarantee that 
pitcher would be any better than Olson, who has 211 career saves. 
</P>
<P>
	When Showalter has gone to someone other than Olson, the results  
have been mixed. As a team, Arizona has blown 10 of 21 save 
opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	The most intriguing prospect is 20-year-old South Korean  
Byung-Hyun Kim, who has a nasty sidearm delivery, an apparent 
abundance of confidence and about four different sliders that 
either rise or fall as they cross the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim has had some big success in his few save appearances, but  
has been hit hard at times. He also had the odd fortune of being 
thrown out of the game Wednesday night when a bandage reeking of 
analgesic balm flew out of his sleeve. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim started the season in Double-A, quickly rose to Triple-A and  
was with the big club before May ended. Showalter has liked Kim 
from the start but is torn about how quickly to use him as a 
closer. Logic would say to break him in slowly, as the Diamondbacks 
have done with Vladimir Nunez, who got his first career save in 
Arizona's 8-7 victory over Chicago Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We brought Vlade in stages. We're trying to that with Kim,''  
Showalter said. ``And he already has had failure. You've got to ask 
yourself do you do harm in the long-run. It's a tough situation. 
There are a lot of things to think about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even though he got the save Wednesday, Nunez was hit hard twice.  
Matt Williams made a diving catch of a line drive on one of the 
hits and the other was a fly ball to deep center that Steve Finley 
chased down. 
</P>
<P>
	Another option might be Darren Holmes, the closer for Colorado a  
couple of seasons ago but usually used as a set-up man by the 
Diamondbacks. Holmes, too, has had some dramatic failures this 
year. He's blown saves in both his opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes says as far as he's concerned, the job still belongs to  
Olson. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are throwing daggers, but nobody knows what it's like  
to be in that position unless you've been in it,'' Holmes said. 
``You're a hero or a goat. I was talking to Oly today and I said of 
our last three losses, I have two and you have one, and we were 
this close to being heroes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He held his fingers a centimeter or so apart to show the margin  
of error for the guy who takes the mound in the ninth inning to 
hold on to a narrow lead. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
