<DOCNO> APW19990610.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 08:50:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat, Corn, Soybeans Move Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures prices advanced early today on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn and soybean futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat bounced higher after heavy rainfall fell in winter wheat  
growing regions. That likely will delay some harvesting of mature 
crops and leave them vulnerable to pests. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans were pressured by forecasts for beneficial  
rainfall in Midwest growing regions, which should prove timely 
after several days of above-average temperatures. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.56 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.20 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1/2 cent to 
$1.25 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.70 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .20 cent to 66.52 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .30 cent to 77.57 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .42 cent to 50.35 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 1.25 
cents to 48.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
