<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Arrested Over Library Books </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) -- A woman who borrowed seven library books  
to read to her 2-year-old son was handcuffed and arrested when they 
became more than a year overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	For each of the missing seven titles, Davis was charged with a  
count of failing to show up in court to account for the overdue 
books. She faced an $82 fine for each book plus $791 in bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabrina Davis, 22, admitted she failed to return the Clearwater  
Library books on time, but said she couldn't afford the late fees. 
She was arrested Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were dropped Tuesday when her boyfriend returned the  
books. Davis was released after spending a night in jail and 
promising to pay $220 in court costs by Dec. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an experience for me,'' she said. ``I've never been  
arrested. I've never been handcuffed. I've never been behind 
bars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they usually resort to arrests after a patron  
fails to heed eight written or telephone notices over about 18 
months. Davis was ordered to come to court in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people return the materials once they receive a notice to  
appear in court, to avoid substantial fines, Assistant City 
Attorney Rob Surette said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since January, the cases of 87 patrons have been referred to the  
court system, library director Arlita Hallam said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
