<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ovitz Expands Internet Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Hollywood superagent Michael Ovitz is  
expanding his collection of Internet investments by partnering to 
buy a controlling interest in Scour.Net, a search engine that 
locates video, audio and picture files on the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz and his investment partner Yucaipa Cos. -- the holding  
company led by Ron Burkle, a former grocery store magnate -- 
announced Thursday that they purchased 51 percent of Scour.Net for 
an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal marks the third joint Internet venture for Ovitz and  
Yucaipa Cos. since the Beverly Hills-based holding company hired 
former Disney Online President Richard Wolpert to lead its 
high-tech investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The group holds minority interests in the online game company  
GameSpy Industries and is developing CheckOut.com, an electronic 
commerce site. 
</P>
<P>
	Scour.Net is designed to allow users to quickly download music,  
video clips and images from movies, television shows and other 
entertainment venues. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolpert and Peter Levin, a partner in Ovitz's technology  
investments, will become members of Scour.Net's board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	The various sites that comprise the Ovitz-Yucaipa ventures will  
be linked, but will operate independently, Wolpert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scour.Net was created in 1997 by five computer students at the  
University of California, Los Angeles and is a unit of Los 
Angeles-based Scour Inc. The Ovitz-Yucaipa stake is limited to the 
Web site and does not include an equity share of Scour Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``This investment will help us forge ahead to bring on new  
strategic partners which will allow us to further expand and grow 
Scour.Net,'' said Dan Rodrigues, CEO of Scour.Net. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz, founder of Creative Artists Agency, was once known as the  
most powerful man in Hollywood. He left CAA to become president of 
The Walt Disney Co. Ovitz left Disney less than a year after taking 
the post because of a falling out with Disney Chairman Michael 
Eisner. After leaving Disney, he founded Artists Management Group, 
whose clients include director Martin Scorsese, Robin Williams, 
Marisa Tomei and Mimi Rogers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz also is leading one of two competing groups seeking to  
bring a National Football League franchise to Los Angeles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
