<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. To Give $39M for Phone Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the nation's largest providers of  
telephone entertainment service has agreed to forgive $37 million 
and reimburse $2 million in charges to consumers who contested 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Trade Commission, which announced the agreement  
Thursday, had accused American TelNet of ``cramming'' -- or putting 
unauthorized charges onto consumers' phone bills. The calls 
apparently were made, but by third parties who illegally gained 
access to the lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Plantation, Fla., company, which did not admit wrongdoing,  
said it settled with the government to avoid lengthy and costly 
litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said American TelNet deprived consumers of their right  
to contest such charges and billed them even though the calls had 
not been made from their phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers are frustrated when phantom charges for services  
they didn't authorize appear on their phone bills,'' said Jodie 
Bernstein, director of the FTC's bureau of consumer protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The 900-number calls were primarily for sex entertainment lines  
and some psychic hotlines as well, the FTC said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the commission, one woman was attending a surgical  
preparation class an hour away from her home when the call to the 
entertainment line supposedly was made from her phone number. 
</P>
<P>
	Another woman, a 74-year-old paraplegic who lives alone and has  
one wireless phone attached to her wheelchair, was billed for 
dialing the 900 number at a time when she did not have access to 
the phone. 
</P>
<P>
	One business was charged for a toll call allegedly made from a  
phone in the elevator of its building, even though the phone had no 
dial pad. 
</P>
<P>
	Entertainment telephone service can include adult-oriented talk  
lines, psychic hot lines and other 900 numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The case highlights the problems that both providers and  
consumers face from ``phreaking.'' The Internet is filled with 
sites instructing hackers on how they can gain access to someone's 
phone line, enabling them to make unauthorized long-distance calls. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the FTC complaint filed in U.S. District Court in  
Miami, American TelNet receives ``tens of thousands complaints from 
consumers every year as a result of its deceptive and sloppy 
marketing practices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, when consumers called to contest the charges, they were  
told the matter would be investigated and a reply issued in a week, 
the FTC said. But the company simply generated a form letter saying 
the bill was accurate and should be paid, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, American TelNet will have to suspend  
billing while it investigated charges, and establish a way to 
determine whether charges were correctly tracked to consumers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
