<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Adds 5 Events to Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Olympic organizers are adding seven  
events, mostly for women, that are expected to pay for themselves 
in the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States could win more Olympic medals with the  
addition of women's bobsled and men's skeleton, a head-first 
version of luge. 
</P>
<P>
	Both events have a ``very good'' chance of producing medals for  
American teams, said Cathy Priestner-Allinger, sports director for 
the Salt Lake Organizing Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Women would get their own skeleton competition under the games'  
expansion approved Thursday by the SLOC management committee, which 
also added cross country ski sprints and 1,500-meter short-track 
speed skating for men and women. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1,500-meter races are expected to be big ticket-sellers,  
offsetting the added costs of the other new events. All will work 
off existing Olympic venues and can easily can be added to the 
games' schedule, Allinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee, which has final say over  
the type and number of Olympic events, is expected to ratify Salt 
Lake's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion would push the number of events to 79, 11 more  
than in the 1998 Winter Games in Nagano and almost evenly split by 
gender. 
</P>
<P>
	The new events were approved even as Salt Lake struggles to fill  
a $300 million revenue gap and trim a $1.45 billion budget. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC president Mitt Romney said the events make the sports  
schedule more equitable for women and will pay for themselves on 
ticket sales. In fact, he says, the events could produce a $200,000 
net gain -- a ``budget-enhancing opportunity'' that outweighs the 
financial risks. 
</P>
<P>
	In other action, the SLOC management committee:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Approved an $150 daily housing allowance for athletes who  
prefer to stay in one of a dozen residences in Park City and Heber 
City that are closer to skiing events instead of the Olympic 
Village at the University of Utah in Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Noted the 1,000-day countdown to the 2002 Paralympic Winter  
Games for disabled athletes with a cake and by sending a Paralympic 
flag to City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Approved a contract with Wige-MIC of Germany for computer  
software that will provide instant competition results to 
scoreboards, broadcasters and a database. Terms of the contract, 
approved behind closed doors in an executive session, were not 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Approved, also in executive session, a fund for merit raises  
for SLOC employees. The size of the pay fund was not disclosed. 
Salary increases will be awarded next month after job evaluations. 
SLOC has about 230 employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
