<HEADLINE> Migrant Ministry Aids Peach Pickers / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARNER ROBINS, Ga. (AP) -- For the Carrazco family, a trip to the  
doctor's office is a luxury they can't afford. So, like the 
families of many migrant workers, the doctor comes to them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes we don't make enough money'' to cover medical care,  
said Daniel Carrazco, 38, who gets up at 4 a.m. to pick peaches in 
nearby Crawford County and reports to a second job, in a plant that 
makes septic tanks, at 10 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	On one evening last week, Carrazco sat under a canopy at the  
roving Migrant Health Fair as a nurse pricked his finger to check 
glucose and hemoglobin levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrazco, a Mexican-born father of three, was among about 120  
farm workers and relatives at Warner Robins' First Hispanic Baptist 
Mission. Most of the workers were single men who had only recently 
arrived from Mexico. A few, like Carrazco, brought wives and 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	With volunteer medical specialists, including doctors and  
dentists, the mission has been providing free health care for 10 
years, primarily for the migrant workers who flock to mid-central 
Georgia to harvest the peach crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrazco brought his wife, Manuela, and their three children:  
Laura, 14; Adriana, 12; and Daniel Jr., 8. Carrazco has been 
working in the peach orchards since 1981 and brought his family to 
Georgia in 1992. He's now a citizen and the others are legal 
residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura, the family spokeswoman, said the health fair is  
important. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people come from places in Mexico where they don't have  
doctors,'' she said. ``And sometimes they don't go to doctors here 
because they're afraid of immigration. They're afraid they'll be 
sent back to Mexico. They need to work. They need the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the 20-week harvest season, the ministry reaches those in  
need by bringing the health fair to farms throughout peach country. 
The Georgia Baptist Convention provides an air-conditioned, 48-foot 
trailer that has an examination room, sterilizers and two dental 
chairs with X-ray machines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can do almost everything in here,'' said Dr. Steve Wilson,  
a local family practitioner. ``We can stitch up cuts. We fill 
cavities, pull teeth that need to be pulled and put sealant on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they discover any life-threatening conditions, the doctors  
can arrange emergency treatment at local hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	That evening last week the workers arrived in vans or pickup  
trucks. After registering, they moved from one station to the next 
for blood and blood pressure testing, dental screening, eye tests 
and several other checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the tests were conducted outside under one of three  
large canopies, and others were performed in the air-conditioned 
comfort of the mission. 
</P>
<P>
	A pharmacy provided prescription and nonprescription drugs for  
ailments ranging from skin rashes to arthritis. 
</P>
<P>
	The last stop was the dining room, where volunteers served chili  
and soft drinks. They gave each person a health kit containing 
personal hygiene essentials, such as shampoo and toothbrushes. Then 
the workers attended a briefing on health hazards, including 
smoking and chewing tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	The mission, supported by the 54 Southern Baptist Convention  
churches that make up the Rehoboth Baptist Association, also offers 
English classes, used clothing and religious training for migrants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
