<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Jump by 14,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits shot up last week to the highest level since 
early January. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported today that 323,000 Americans filed  
new claims for jobless benefits last week, up by 14,000 from the 
previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase was unexpected. Analysts had expected the number of  
claims for unemployment benefits to inch down slightly. Government 
analysts noted that the reporting period included the Memorial Day 
holiday. Weeks including a holiday have often been erratic in terms 
of the number of people showing up in benefit claims offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The big jumps in claims last week pushed them to the highest  
level since the week of Jan. 9, when they were at 358,000. After 
that increase jobless claims declined for nearly two months. They 
remained below 300,000 for nine straight weeks, the longest stretch 
in 26 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for jobless claims, which helps  
smooth out week-to-week volatility, also was up slightly to 
308,250. That was the highest level since May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the increase in jobless claims, the number of  
Americans putting in for unemployment benefits is still low and 
depicts a tight labor market. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the government reported that the nation's unemployment  
rate edged down to 4.2 percent, returning to a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, manufacturing has lost more than 453,000 jobs in the past  
14 months due to the global financial crisis, which has cut into 
exports and increased cheap imports into this country. But the rest 
of the U.S. economy, powered by strong consumer spending, is 
continuing to show robust growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said that for the week ending May 29, 18  
states and territories reported declined in jobless claims while 35 
had increases. The state data lags a week heind the national 
figures 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina had the biggest declines in benefit applications,  
a drop of 1,210, which was attributed to fewer layoffs in the 
electrical equipment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states with big drops in benefit claims were: California,  
down 815; Orgeon, down 723; Georgia, down 390; and Tennessee, down 
205. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the largest increase in jobless claims was  
Michigan, with a jump of 1,938 applications, an increase that was 
blamed on layoffs in the auto industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states with big increases in benefit claims were: Texas,  
up 1,676; Mississippi, up 1,328; Arizona, up 1,203; and Missouri, 
up 1,046. The increase in Texas was blamed on layoffs in the 
apparel and trade industries, while the increase in Mississippi 
because of layoffs at apparel and electrical equipment factories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
