<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sauter Wins Pole for Truck Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Jay Sauter, who's struggled with  
qualifying throughout a 70-race NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series 
career, recorded the fastest single lap in the tour's history 
Thursday night to win the pole position for the Pronto Auto Parts 
400 race at Texas Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauter, driving a Chevrolet Silverado, lapped the 1.5-mile  
superspeedway at 179.718 mph, the fastest of four drivers who 
shattered Jack Sprague's year-old qualifying record of 178.642. 
</P>
<P>
	Sauter's pole run was the first for Richard Childress Racing,  
the tour's pole leader, since Oct. 5, 1995. The team's former 
driver, current NASCAR Winston Cup star Mike Skinner, got his 15th 
and final pole at Sears Point Raceway near Sonoma, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tested real good here in the spring and these guys put an  
awesome truck under me today,'' the 36-year-old Wisconsin veteran 
said. ``It was a good run. I've loved this race track from the 
first time I came here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sauter, ranked 10th in the driver standings, last won at  
Martinsville, Va. last September. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Sauter on the front row will be Stacy Compton. The Dodge  
driver narrowly missed his third pole of the season, recording a 
lap of 179.390. Dennis Setzer was third at 178.761 in another 
Dodge, followed by Ron Hornaday's Silverado, which also broke 
Sprague's Texas Motor Speedway mark at 178.660. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Bliss, the second driver to qualify, held onto the No. 5  
spot with a lap of 178.218. Bliss held the provisional pole until 
Hornaday made his run. Sauter took the pole late in the order, 
after a 15-minute delay for track cleanup following Eric Norris' 
accident in Turn 2. The television stunt coordinator's Ford was 
severely damaged but the son of TV and film actor Chuck Norris 
escaped injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprague, Terry Fisher, Bryan Reffner, Andy Houston and David  
Starr rounded out the top 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornaday enters Friday's event with a 37-point lead over  
Compton, who has finished in the top four in eight of nine races 
this season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
