<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 07:50:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Chief Rides High on a Hog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When AT&AMP;T chief executive C. Michael Armstrong  
takes his wife for a spin on his motorcycle, she holds on tight and 
says, ``Don't tilt it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Employees and shareholders can sympathize.  
</P>
<P>
	Sure, they're trusting, even thrilled, to be barreling down a  
new path with Armstrong -- confident in his plan to snap up cable TV 
wires around the country so AT&AMP;T can offer a cutting-edge 
combination of television, telephone and Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, when someone else is steering, it's hard not to  
wince at every bend in the road. In this case however, the biker in 
question doesn't seem bent on reckless living or daredevil stunts. 
</P>
<P>
	A nearly four-decade career with just three companies; a  
long-lasting marriage to the sweetheart he met at age 14 -- these 
are not the traits of a free-wheeling cowboy. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it's a more sober sort of risk-taker that AT&AMP;T hired to  
reinvent a lethargic phone company -- to reprise his turnaround 
earlier this decade of the defense contractor Hughes Electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	While he's never had a motorcycle accident, Armstrong said in a  
recent interview, ``We've all had `situations.' When you ride a 
motorcycle, it's very difficult to ride it with any regularity and 
not have been confronted with some dangerous situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Professionally, some would say his worst ``situation'' came in  
the 1980s, at the tail-end of his three-decade-plus career at IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong joined IBM in 1961 and by the mid '80s had worked his  
way into senior management. It was his team that squandered the 
company's leadership in the personal computer revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Although IBM's PC started out as the industry standard, its PC  
division was tied to the company's sluggish bureaucracy. It failed 
to innovate and was eventually overtaken by faster-moving 
competitors such as Compaq. 
</P>
<P>
	That brush with failure didn't make Armstrong a squeamish driver  
when he moved on to Hughes in 1992, and AT&AMP;T five years later. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he was the first outsider ever hired to run Hughes and  
the first import to lead AT&AMP;T in eight decades, he didn't hesitate 
to cut thousands of jobs as a prelude to a full makeover at both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	At Hughes, he steered the company away from its core military  
electronics business, ultimately selling it to Raytheon, to go full 
bore into the commercial satellite businesses -- including DirecTV, 
the TV service that uses small satellite dishes instead of cables. 
</P>
<P>
	The transition at AT&AMP;T has been even more radical. It's not a  
sheepish man who decides, in the space of just 10 months, to spend 
more than $100 billion of his new employer's money on an uncertain 
strategy in an entirely different industry. 
</P>
<P>
	What's more, Armstrong goal in purchasing the big cable TV  
companies Tele-Communications Inc. and MediaOne Group is a lot more 
ambitious than just transforming the No. 1 long-distance phone 
company into the No. 1 cable company. 
</P>
<P>
	His strategy is to transform the cable industry into something  
new by upgrading the coaxial cables bringing TV to America's homes 
into a ``broadband'' pipe for two-way, high-speed communications. 
</P>
<P>
	While the pace he's set for AT&AMP;T has been breathless, none of  
the past year's moves could be accurately described as a shot from 
the hip. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, 60, strikes a confident, charismatic chord in public  
-- aided by an imposing six-foot frame, a twinkle in the eyes and 
the type of snow-white hair and male-pattern baldness that makes 
him look more distinguished than old. 
</P>
<P>
	But in person, Armstrong can be soft-spoken, almost  
grandfatherly. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Detroit at the tail-end of the Depression, Charles  
Michael Armstrong was the oldest of three boys. His future wife, 
Anne, lived 16 houses down the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``We started going together -- they called it `going steady' in  
those days -- when we were 14 years old,'' Armstrong said. They 
dated through high school, went to the same college in Oxford, 
Ohio, and married soon after. 
</P>
<P>
	``So our lives have been, from the very beginning, common  
lives,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Common, except that his career has now forced them to move 16  
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's gotten (the moving) down pretty well,'' said Armstrong,  
who had just bought a home near Hughes' headquarters in Southern 
California, when he was asked to lead AT&AMP;T. ``My wife had 
completely redecorated it, and we moved in and lived in it seven 
days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who has three daughters with seven grandchildren,  
only recently moved into his newest home after living for more than 
a year in a hotel near AT&AMP;T's offices in suburban New Jersey so he 
could immerse himself in the new job at hand. 
</P>
<P>
	When he arrived at AT&AMP;T late 1997, there were meetings, meetings  
and more meetings. The get-to-know-you sessions he convened back 
then took nearly three months to adjourn. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were days when we started a meeting that was supposed to  
go half a day on Monday morning, and on Thursday we were still 
going at it. Calendars got blown away,'' said Richard Roscitt, 
president of AT&AMP;T Solutions, which manages communications networks 
for other companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a better listener than I would have guessed,'' said  
Roscitt, a 26-year veteran at AT&AMP;T. ``He has an enormous ability 
to, as he likes to call it, drill down to the details, and retain 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was the much same deal when he arrived at Hughes in 1992,  
when ``Mike spent the first six months getting educated,'' said 
Richard Dore, a Hughes spokesman who worked with Armstrong. 
</P>
<P>
	At meetings, Dore said, he would grow impatient ``if you started  
straying too much. Sometimes people make presentations and there's 
a lot of fluff, and fluff takes too much time. He wants to cut to 
the chase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, Armstrong's aggressive moves at AT&AMP;T have  
energized the company's troops by guaranteeing a role for a 
century-old company on a field dominated by youngsters like America 
Online. 
</P>
<P>
	In so doing, Armstrong has emerged as one of the nation's most  
prominent executives, a nimble power-broker on par with Microsoft's 
Bill Gates and News Corp.'s Rupert Murdoch, and far more 
well-regarded at that. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 20:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  N.Korean Soccer Players Meet Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MCAFEE, N.J. (AP) -- Dressed in bright red team jackets or in  
three-piece suits, the advisers, technical directors and translator 
for the North Korea women's soccer team could have been at a trial. 
They answered questions readily, but without revealing anything 
noteworthy. They seemed anxious to finish with the media. 
</P>
<P>
	In the background, the 20 players chatted as they took off their  
warmups and prepared for a workout at the Ballyowen Field, hard by 
the first hole of the year-old Ballyowen golf course. Then they 
stretched, jogged a lap -- and headed straight through the 
sprinklers watering the grass. Their giggles and shenanigans while 
trying to see who could force the other to get most wet drew smiles 
from reporters, if not from Korean officials. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is any pressure on the players of the most mysterious  
team in the Women's World Cup, it's difficult to sense. They seem 
to be having a ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that they will admit it when asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have been here six days, and our prime task is to qualify  
for the Olympics in Sydney,'' said captain Kim Kum Sil, the lone 
player made available for interviews Thursday at the only media 
session team officials planned to allow. North Korea must make the 
quarterfinals to have a shot at the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of things have changed, such as the time change. We are  
having jet lag and we still are not accustomed to the climate 
change,'' she said. ``We are trying to get accustomed to them and 
the things we can concentrate on as soon possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That shouldn't be very difficult, considering the way they are  
being sheltered. Then again, for a nation whose athletes rarely 
travel outside of Asia, that's an understandable approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must not distract the players,'' said Ryu Song Il,  
secretary-general of the North Korean Olympic Committee, when asked 
if the players would be mingling with Korean-Americans during the 
tournament. ``Doing any kind of activities that might affect 
players while they are conditioning and training is not good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Koreans head for Los Angeles this weekend, where they will  
practice leading up to their tournament opener against Nigeria on 
June 20. They play Denmark in Portland, Ore., on June 24, then face 
the host Americans on June 27 in Foxboro, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Although little is known about them, they have limited  
experience on the world stage and have not been a soccer power in 
previous years, the Koreans remain confident they can advance to 
the second round, if not further. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time our country is attempting the Women's  
World Cup,'' technical director Kim Hak-Yong said. ``Women's soccer 
was not started long ago in my country, but it has gained a strong 
reputation so far. I think my team will play as a good, strong team 
this time. How we play against strong teams will demonstrate how 
we've prepared for this World Cup.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
