<HEADLINE>  N.Korean Soccer Players Meet Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MCAFEE, N.J. (AP) -- Dressed in bright red team jackets or in  
three-piece suits, the advisers, technical directors and translator 
for the North Korea women's soccer team could have been at a trial. 
They answered questions readily, but without revealing anything 
noteworthy. They seemed anxious to finish with the media. 
</P>
<P>
	In the background, the 20 players chatted as they took off their  
warmups and prepared for a workout at the Ballyowen Field, hard by 
the first hole of the year-old Ballyowen golf course. Then they 
stretched, jogged a lap -- and headed straight through the 
sprinklers watering the grass. Their giggles and shenanigans while 
trying to see who could force the other to get most wet drew smiles 
from reporters, if not from Korean officials. 
</P>
<P>
	If there is any pressure on the players of the most mysterious  
team in the Women's World Cup, it's difficult to sense. They seem 
to be having a ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that they will admit it when asked.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have been here six days, and our prime task is to qualify  
for the Olympics in Sydney,'' said captain Kim Kum Sil, the lone 
player made available for interviews Thursday at the only media 
session team officials planned to allow. North Korea must make the 
quarterfinals to have a shot at the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of things have changed, such as the time change. We are  
having jet lag and we still are not accustomed to the climate 
change,'' she said. ``We are trying to get accustomed to them and 
the things we can concentrate on as soon possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That shouldn't be very difficult, considering the way they are  
being sheltered. Then again, for a nation whose athletes rarely 
travel outside of Asia, that's an understandable approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must not distract the players,'' said Ryu Song Il,  
secretary-general of the North Korean Olympic Committee, when asked 
if the players would be mingling with Korean-Americans during the 
tournament. ``Doing any kind of activities that might affect 
players while they are conditioning and training is not good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Koreans head for Los Angeles this weekend, where they will  
practice leading up to their tournament opener against Nigeria on 
June 20. They play Denmark in Portland, Ore., on June 24, then face 
the host Americans on June 27 in Foxboro, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Although little is known about them, they have limited  
experience on the world stage and have not been a soccer power in 
previous years, the Koreans remain confident they can advance to 
the second round, if not further. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time our country is attempting the Women's  
World Cup,'' technical director Kim Hak-Yong said. ``Women's soccer 
was not started long ago in my country, but it has gained a strong 
reputation so far. I think my team will play as a good, strong team 
this time. How we play against strong teams will demonstrate how 
we've prepared for this World Cup.'' 
  	   	
