<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sonics' Employee Award Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court reinstated $5.2  
million in damages Thursday to six former ticket-sellers for the 
Seattle SuperSonics who were fired after protesting the loss of 
their overtime pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled that employees can't be fired for complaining to  
their employers about wage violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The ticket-sellers said they were fired for protesting to the  
basketball team's management about elimination of their overtime. A 
federal judge later ruled the overtime cutoff illegal and the 
workers were awarded damages. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of the award was thrown out last October by a  
three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. The 
panel said employees couldn't sue for retaliation under federal 
labor law because they had complained only to their supervisors and 
did not file a formal complaint with the government before suing. 
</P>
<P>
	After the full court ordered a rehearing, a new panel ruled 9-2  
Thursday that the law applied to complaints made to employers. 
</P>
<P>
	The law was intended to ``ensure that employees are not  
compelled to risk their jobs in order to assert their wage and hour 
rights,'' said the opinion by Judge Stephen Reinhardt. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of seven other appellate courts have reached the same  
conclusion, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the former ticket-sellers said the ruling should  
benefit employers as well as employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think employers have any interest in their employees'  
being forced to go to court before trying to work things out,'' 
Spencer Hall said. ``It would encourage litigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Full House Sports and Entertainment, the Sonics' managing  
company, said it would appeal to the Supreme Court. ``Our legal 
counsel has advised us that we have strong grounds for appeal,'' 
company president John Dressel said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The case dates from mid-1994, when the Sonics eliminated the  
$2,000 annual overtime allowances paid to ticket-sellers and 
stopped paying them overtime. An employee who complained said she 
was told by a team official that William Ackerley, the chief 
operating officer, didn't care about the law and wouldn't pay 
overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The team eventually paid them for lost overtime. But nine  
ticket-sellers were fired in December 1994 after Full House Sports 
took over the team's business management. The court said the only 
seller who kept his job was the one who hadn't complained. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. District court jury awarded the six $697,000 in back pay  
and $450,000 for emotional distress. Jurors also awarded $12 
million in punitive damages, an amount the judge reduced to $4.18 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel's ruling last October would have  
eliminated the punitive damages and reduced the emotional distress 
award. The opinion by Judge Melvin Brunetti said the distress 
damages, $75,000 per employee, were ``grossly excessive'' because 
evidence showed their suffering was ``not that severe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's ruling disagreed with Brunetti and upheld the entire  
damage award. Judges Pamela Rymer and Ferdinand Fernandez 
dissented. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
