<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Knight Investigated in Assault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight is  
being investigated for assaulting a fellow patron at a restaurant, 
Monroe County Prosecutor Carl Salzmann said today. 
</P>
<P>
	No charges have been filed, but Knight may face a misdemeanor  
charge of battery, which carries a maximum penalty of six months in 
jail and a $5,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said the 38-year-old man who claims he was assaulted  
also could be charged with provocation, a Class C infraction that 
carries a $500 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you provoke somebody to commit battery, and a battery  
occurs -- do you charge both people?'' Salzmann asked. ``That's what 
we're trying to figure out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said he had a preliminary report from Indiana State  
Police on the incident, but wanted more information before deciding 
whether to charge either or both men. 
</P>
<P>
	The altercation occurred about 9:30 p.m. Monday at a Mexican  
restaurant in Ellettsville, about five miles from Bloomington, 
Salzmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight had been dining with his wife and her two sisters when  
the other man, who was dining with a friend, took offense to 
comments he overheard Knight making. The man confronted Knight as 
he was preparing to leave, claiming the comments he had overheard 
were racist, Salzmann said. The other man was white. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight paid his bill and walked to the parking lot, where the  
altercation continued and the man claims Knight grabbed him around 
the throat and lifted him into the air, Salzmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other man then returned to the restaurant and called police.  
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said the man later sought medical treatment.  
</P>
<P>
	A state trooper, along with an Ellettsville police officer,  
responded and took pictures of injuries the man said he had 
suffered, Salzmann said. They also questioned the man, his friend, 
Knight's wife, one of her sisters and the restaurant manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said he still wants state police to talk to several  
unbiased witnesses, including other restaurant workers and patrons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
