<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bombing of Yugoslavia Is Suspended  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Serb troops began withdrawing from Kosovo,  
President Clinton today warned Slobodan Milosevic that NATO's 
78-day bombing campaign is suspended but not formally terminated. 
``We now have a moment of hope,'' the president said. ``We have to 
finish the job and build a peace.'' The president then spoke by 
telephone with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, praising his 
leadership and the diplomatic role played by former Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin. Clinton said American forces ``performed 
superbly, risking their lives,'' and called the Serbs' apparent 
capitulation a vindication of U.S. efforts. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Set To Adopt Kosovo Resolution  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council is meeting this hour  
on a resolution authorizing an international force to move into 
Kosovo to ensure the safe return of 860,000 ethnic Albanian 
refugees. The meeting follows an announcement from NATO suspending 
its airstrikes against Yugoslavia after verifying the withdrawal of 
Serb forces was underway. The draft resolution also calls on the 
United Nations to start rebuilding the province and create a 
civilian administration that would lay the groundwork for a future 
autonomous government. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Strikes Down 'Street Gang' Law  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today struck down a Chicago  
law aimed at preventing street gang members and their friends from 
hanging out in public. The 6-3 decision ended a constitutional 
dispute that captured the attention of states and communities 
across the nation. The court said the 1992 anti-loitering ordinance 
violated the rights of the people police arrested because it did 
not give them adequate notice what was forbidden. In striking down 
the ordinance as too vague, today's decision acknowledged ``the 
serious and difficult problems'' street gangs cause for Chicago. 

</P>
<P>
	IRS Forces Christian Coalition Split  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service has ruled that  
the Christian Coalition is not entitled to tax-exempt status, 
forcing the once-vaunted political powerhouse to split into two 
entities and be ``dramatically reshaped,'' officials close to the 
group said today. The IRS first denied tax-exempt status to the 
group last year and the Christian Coalition was notified in recent 
weeks that it would lose the appeal, according to the officials. A 
spokesman for the organization said the new entity could form a 
political action committee, and will open chapters overseas. 

</P>
<P>
	FEC Allows Matching Internet Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government today gave a major boost to  
political fund raising in cyberspace, ruling that presidential 
candidates can qualify for federal campaign assistance for 
donations they raise over the Internet. The Federal Election 
Commission voted 6-0 to allow presidential candidates who take 
credit card donations on their Web sites to qualify for federal 
matching dollars during the primary elections. ``We recognize the 
reality that the Internet is here and a big part of our life,'' FEC 
Chairman Scott Thomas said after the vote. 

</P>
<P>
	India Continues Assault in Kashmir  
</P>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- Indian troops relentlessly shelled Islamic  
militants in the mountains of Kashmir today, pushing ahead with 
their assault despite the mounting confrontation with Pakistan. 
Voicing concern, the Group of Eight leading industrial nations and 
Russia urged both countries today to sign the international treaty 
banning nuclear testing. India says the militants crossed the 
unmarked cease-fire line from Pakistan last month and control about 
40 square miles in the Indian-controlled part of Kashmir. Pakistan 
says Kashmiri ``freedom fighters'' are battling in the disputed 
territory. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Slips 95; Nasdaq Falls 28  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 95.93 points at 10,594.36. Decliners outnumbered advancers on 
the New York Stock Exchange 1,795-841. The Nasdaq Composite Index 
was down 28.55 at 2,490.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Bob Knight Investigated in Assault  
</P>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Indiana basketball coach Bob Knight  
faces possible battery charges after a disagreement with a man in a 
restaurant who accused the coach of making racist remarks. Monroe 
County prosecutor Carl Salzmann said he will likely decide whether 
to charge either or both men later today. A misdemeanor battery 
charge carries a maximum penalty of six months in jail and a $5,000 
fine. The other patron could be charged with provocation. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
