<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Extend Fall; Dow Off 141.53 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks extended their losses today as a strong  
economic report from Japan increased fears that continued growth in 
the U.S. economy may prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it looks like interest rates are going up, stocks are going  
down,'' said John Cleland, chief investment strategist at Security 
Benefit Group in Topeka, Kan. ``It's that simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 141.53 at 10,548.76 after falling 219 points over the previous 
two sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was down 21.83 at 1,296.81, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was off 38.71 at 2,480.64. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government said the nation's gross domestic product  
grew 1.9 percent in the first three months of the year -- a larger 
increase than expected, and the first since the summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That set off fears that Japanese demand for U.S. goods will  
swell, boosting the domestic economy even further and setting off 
inflationary pressure. The threat of inflation has prompted the Fed 
to say it might raise interest rates if it determines that higher 
rates would cool off a surging economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices, which are highly sensitive to inflation, fell  
today, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.04 
percent. Analysts consider bond yields above 6 percent to be 
detrimental to stocks, as investors may turn to the lucrative, 
stable return of bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bond market has really set the leadership for the stock  
market today,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment officer at 
BankBoston. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks like Chase Manhattan, down 1 5/8 to 72 3/16, were  
mostly lower. Higher interest rates can hurt bank profits as 
lending volume shrinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer stocks also fell today. Those shares, which tend to be  
expensive, also tend to flag in high interest-rate environments as 
investors become less willing to pay high prices relative to 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology companies are also battling customers' uncertainty  
over the Year 2000 computer bug, analysts said. Microsoft fell 2 
11/16 to 79 5/8 and Cisco Systems fell 3 1/2 to 110 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Pfizer fell sharply for a second straight day, losing 5 1/8 to 99  
13/16. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration Wednesday restricted 
the use of Pfizer's antibiotic Trovan. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders remain focused on the Friday morning release of the  
producer price index. That report is expected to offer the latest 
hint of whether inflationary pressures have crept into the U.S. 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to establish that the U.S. economy is not boiling to  
the point of explosion,'' Riley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 556.0 million shares, 
ahead of Wednesday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 8.98 at 620.30, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 5.28 at 767.71. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
