<HEADLINE> Marlins' Counsell Wants To Be Traded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Craig Counsell, a World Series hero two years ago,  
is upset about his shrinking role with the Florida Marlins and says 
he wants to be traded. 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell didn't complain publicly when he lost his starting job  
at second base to Luis Castillo during spring training. But after 
being taken out of the second game of a doubleheader Tuesday 
against Baltimore in the eighth inning, Counsell voiced his 
frustration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can handle being a utility player, and I can handle losing  
my job in spring training,'' Counsell told reporters Wednesday. 
``But now they're telling me I can't play defense?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager John Boles sent Castillo into the game as a defensive  
replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell, who scored the winning run in the 1997 World Series,  
has started just 10 of 60 games and has a .152 average in 66 
at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've tried to accommodate him,'' general manager Dave  
Dombrowski said. ``But he has value. He could be an everyday second 
baseman for some big-league clubs. ... We're not going to give him 
away.'' 
  	   	
</P>
