<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Emerges As Peace Mediator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- German soldiers, long burdened by  
Germany's history of aggression, are preparing to enter Kosovo in 
the coming days representing their nation's new role as Continental 
peace mediator. 
</P>
<P>
	The German Cabinet and parliament were set to approve deployment  
of an 8,500-strong contingent Friday as part of the international 
peace force. 
</P>
<P>
	The deployment to guarantee the safe return of Kosovo Albanian  
refugees marks ``the end of the Yugoslav wars'' after nearly 10 
years of bloodshed, Germany's Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer 
declared triumphantly. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischer has particular reason to celebrate. Making his debut in  
the diplomatic arena, the former taxi driver is credited with a 
large share of the diplomacy that enabled a peace deal with 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the often-tense maneuvering, Fischer balanced  
Germany's troubled history, his own past as a peace activist and 
the German public's reluctance to engage in war with his conviction 
that NATO bombs were necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we accept in Europe such a throwback back to the policies  
of the 1930s, I'm sure Milosevic wouldn't have stopped in Kosovo. 
We needed years to accept war,'' Fischer said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me appeasement is not a bad word. But at the end when you  
realize there is no other means, you have to use'' force, Fischer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only weeks ago, as the threat grew that the NATO air campaign  
would be widened into a ground war, Fischer was the target of the 
nation's angst over the involvement in its first armed conflict 
since Adolf Hitler waged war on Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	As anti-war sentiment grew, Fischer was hit in the face by a  
paint balloon during a special meeting of his Greens Party to 
discuss Kosovo. He defied party pacifists who demanded an immediate 
bombing halt. 
</P>
<P>
	Though stung by the confrontation, Fischer persevered on the  
diplomatic front. ``The situation was often very difficult,'' he 
conceded Thursday, ``then all of a sudden it broke open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During three days of tough negotiations with foreign ministers  
from the world's richest democracies and Russia, Fischer 
demonstrated iron-willed politicking to secure a compromise to end 
the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Having helped ensure agreement on peace terms, Fischer turned  
his energy toward using the deal to push for a speedy end to the 
bombing. On Wednesday, he was overheard forcefully pressing the 
merits of a bombing pause. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's critical role in resolving the Kosovo crisis helps  
redefine a nation viewed for so long -- even by allies -- as a 
potential threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are all going to have a very interesting time  
studying the lessons of this struggle,'' Secretary of State 
Madeleine Albright said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Fund-Raising Bid Decried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The fund-raisers for Senate Democrats have  
come under fire for petitioning federal agencies for materials 
including letters and constituent requests sent to and from Senate 
Republicans up for re-election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., accused Democrats of looking for  
``trash at the expense of the privacy of my constituents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee defended the  
practice Thursday, saying the committee had no intention of 
violating anyone's privacy. Spokesman Jim Jordan described the 
requests as routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republican attacks on the use of the Freedom of Information  
Act are indeed attacks on open government,'' Jordan said. ``One 
wonders whether or not there are specific transactions made by some 
of these senators that they simply don't want opened to public 
view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said their concerns involved individual privacy.  
Although agencies are required by law to withhold confidential and 
other private information, Republicans said mistakes sometimes 
happen and that senators could lose constituents' trust. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would put a permanent chill on the ability of senators to  
help constituents in need,'' Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., complained 
this week in a letter to President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	A request to the Department of Health and Human Services, a copy  
of which was obtained by The Associated Press, seeks ``letters, 
written materials, reports, constituent requests and other relevant 
material'' to and from senators or their aides. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Burns and Santorum, information was sought on  
Sens. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.; John Ashcroft, R-Mo.; Bill Frist, 
R-Tenn.; Slade Gorton, R-Wash.; Rod Grams, R-Minn.; James Jeffords, 
R-Vt.; Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said Democrats made requests with ``numerous federal  
agencies'' but he would not name them. He said the Democratic 
committee would contact those agencies to clarify its needs and 
expectations with regard to privacy rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan said Republicans in the past have made similar requests  
of Democrats, citing contacts that Democratic senators had with 
various agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Republican Senatorial Committee, however, said it  
has made no Freedom of Information Act requests since Sen. Mitch 
McConnell, R-Ky., took over as chairman in 1997. Spokesman Stuart 
Roy said he did not know if there were any such requests before 
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
