<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Evangelical Leaders Issue Platform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leaders of Evangelical Protestantism, who rarely  
speak with one voice, have issued a joint statement of doctrine 
defining what unites the movement and what distinguishes it from 
other forms of Christianity. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, the statement reaffirms the Evangelical  
belief that Jesus Christ ``is the only way of salvation. ... The 
Bible offers no hope that sincere worshippers of other religions 
will be saved without personal faith in Jesus Christ.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other Christians have promoted a more liberal and universal  
concept of salvation. 
</P>
<P>
	Evangelicalism -- a conservative wing of Protestantism  
representing, by some estimates, one-fourth of Americans -- is a 
network of denominations, congregations and independent ministries. 
Evangelicals generally share the same outlook, but the movement 
rarely takes joint action. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Evangelicalism's best-known figures, including religious  
broadcasters Jerry Falwell, D. James Kennedy, Pat Robertson and 
Charles Stanley, endorsed the statement. The 129 signers also 
include Bill Bright of Campus Crusade for Christ and prison 
evangelist Charles Colson. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Graham did not sign, but one of his top aides served on  
the 15-member drafting committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The text -- which appears in the latest issue of Christianity  
Today magazine -- was also endorsed by leaders at four of the most 
important Evangelical seminaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Christianity Today executive editor David Neff said that  
Evangelicals ``have never put forth a large-scale defining document 
about the gospel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The project began as a bid to define conservative Protestant  
views of salvation in contrast to those of Catholicism. But it 
quickly took up other topics, including disagreements with more 
liberal strains of Protestantism. 
</P>
<P>
	The text states that the Bible is ``infallible'' but says little  
about how to interpret Scripture. Evangelicals are divided, for 
example, over how literally to take the story of creation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Evangelical movement has a subtle difference with Catholics  
on the role of faith and good works in salvation. Both groups teach 
that all people are sinful, but the Evangelical platform denies 
that people have any inherent righteousness. Catholicism has a 
slightly more optimistic view of humanity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:49:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Cos. Face Last Tariff Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. steel producers seeking tariffs to block  
low-priced shipments from Japan face their final -- and toughest -- 
hurdle Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission will decide whether the  
domestic industry is hurt by Japanese pricing practices already 
deemed illegal by the Commerce Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Tariffs on hot-rolled carbon steel, the industry's leading  
product, would effectively make Japanese shipments too expensive to 
sell in the United States. The U.S. industry believes such 
sanctions are necessary to counter last year's surge in imports, 
which it blames for thousands of layoffs nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's vote could affect future shipments from Japan  
as well as from other countries looking for signs of what practices 
are permissible. A negative vote also could boost support in 
Congress for global quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't give us the (tariffs), I think people would be  
outraged,'' said William Klinefelter, Washington representative of 
the United Steelworkers of America union. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry credits the threat of tariffs for the roughly  
40 percent drop in overall steel shipments from Japan and other 
countries since November. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot-rolled shipments from Japan dropped to 7,428 metric tons in  
April, compared with 405,974 in November. By comparison, shipments 
of the same product from Korea, which was not a target of the trade 
cases, remained at roughly 60,000 metric tons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department ruled in April that Japan violated U.S.  
trade laws by dumping hot-rolled steel in U.S. markets at prices 
below production costs or home-market prices. The department 
proposed tariffs of as much as 67 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But before any tariffs are imposed, the trade commission must  
determine that the dumping has injured or threatens to hurt U.S. 
industry. While Commerce finds dumping in nearly all cases it 
reviews, the commission finds injury only about half the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ITC is the only place you can go to get even the potential  
of an objective review of the facts,'' said Russell Smith, a lawyer 
for Japanese steel producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-member trade commission's vote Friday comes nearly a  
year after domestic producers filed their complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	The factors the trade commission uses to evaluate injury are not  
as clear-cut as those used by Commerce, and include individual 
commissioners' assessments of the economic health of U.S. 
producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports rose following the Asian economic crisis, which drove  
down demand for steel abroad and forced foreign producers to turn 
to the healthy U.S. economy for sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry accuses Japanese, Russian and Brazilian  
producers of dumping hot-rolled steel in the United States at 
unfair prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has tentatively struck deals with  
Russia and Brazil in which those countries could avoid tariffs by 
voluntarily reducing steel shipments. That leaves Japan as the 
remaining target. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
