<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miss. Gov. Announces Divorce Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Gov. Kirk Fordice ended years of  
speculation about another woman in his life when he announced 
Thursday that he is ending his marriage of 44 years to wed his 
childhood sweetheart. 
</P>
<P>
	The 65-year-old two-term Republican, who has courted the  
religious right and harshly criticized President Clinton's affair 
with Monica Lewinsky, said he and Memphis widow Ann G. Creson will 
marry as soon as his divorce from Pat Fordice is final. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice is barred from serving a third term and has already said  
he will not seek another office when his term is up in January. He 
could become the first sitting governor of Mississippi to get 
divorced. 
</P>
<P>
	The news came on the heels of a report that Fordice vacationed  
in Europe with Ms. Creson while Mrs. Fordice remained in Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fordice marriage has repeatedly been in the news, and the  
quick-tempered governor has always insisted that his private life 
should stay private. Last month, it was revealed he bought a house 
in a Jackson suburb without inviting his wife to live there. 
</P>
<P>
	Three years ago, the governor was seen having lunch and holding  
hands with a woman near Memphis while his wife was in France. The 
woman was never identified. The story came out after Fordice was 
seriously injured in a car wreck on the way home. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, he lashed out at a TV reporter who confronted him  
about the European trip, telling the reporter he would ``whip your 
ass'' if he didn't leave his personal life alone. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice press secretary Robbie Wilbur said that for now, both  
Fordices are living in the Governor's Mansion. He did not know if 
Mrs. Fordice plans to remain there. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Fordice's attorney, L.C. James, said his client was asked  
to join the governor in the announcement about the divorce, but 
``right now, her present inclination is to not have a divorce take 
place anytime in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	``She would prefer to have their lives restored to some sort of  
normalcy so that she can focus on her duties as first lady,'' James 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice attorney Jim Becker said in a statement that the  
Fordices had been estranged for some time and the divorce would be 
resolved ``equitably and with dignity.'' The couple, whose 44th 
wedding anniversary is in August, have four children and 10 
grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a sad day, a sad situation for them. It's sad for a  
public figure, especially one who has promoted the importance of 
the family,'' said Forest Thigpen, head of a group that lobbies on 
pro-family issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice is serving as a national co-chairman of Dan Quayle's  
presidential campaign. Quayle is portraying himself as the family 
values candidate of the GOP presidential field in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle's spokesman, Jonathan Baron, said Thursday that the  
former vice president is standing behind Fordice, adding, ``We are 
pleased to have such support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Creson, Fordice's junior high sweetheart, did not return  
calls to her home Thursday. Her husband of 43 years, Roy Franklin 
Creson Jr., died in November of cancer at 66. He was the retired 
owner of a manufacturing company. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice and his wife's marital troubles date to 1993, when he  
announced they were having ``irreconcilable differences.'' A day 
later, she issued a statement saying she would continue serving as 
first lady unless forced out. 
</P>
<P>
	This spring, Mrs. Fordice said her husband had bought a $230,000  
home outside Jackson and never invited her to see it. She said she 
did not want a divorce, though she knew her husband's new home 
``wasn't for me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
