<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auditor: AMA Loses Money, Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- An auditor's report shows the American Medical  
Association lost money on operations last year -- and lost about 
2,700 members. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of $2.6 million in membership dues was the biggest  
factor in the AMA's operating loss, the report showed. The AMA lost 
$141,000 on operations, compared to an operating income of $6.3 
million in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are always concerned about operating losses, and we are  
doing everything we can with membership activities,'' said Dr. 
Timothy Flaherty, the AMA's secretary-treasurer. 
</P>
<P>
	Flaherty said the AMA probably would have made money on  
operations but has undertaken a costly project to accredit doctors' 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Membership in the nation's largest organization of doctors has  
been declining for years. The latest wave has been blamed largely 
on the AMA's decision in 1997 to endorse products marketed by the 
Sunbeam Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA backed away from that deal after an outcry from its  
members and outside critics, but had to pay $9.9 million to settle 
a lawsuit brought by Sunbeam. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
