<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Wants To Cut Kosovo Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even as members of both parties welcomed the  
Kosovo peace accord, the Republican-led House forged ahead today on 
legislation that would bar funds for peacekeeping operations there. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said they were incredulous at the timing.  
</P>
<P>
	``Never in the history of this country has a Congress voted to  
deprive America of an American victory in the field after it has 
been achieved,'' said Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, senior Democrat 
on the House Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans declined to back away from a provision in a  
defense spending bill that would bar funds for either a military or 
peacekeeping mission in the Balkans after Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The president could spend money for such an operation only by  
citing national security concerns and sending separate legislation 
to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a new and perhaps more troubling phase for our  
country,'' said the Armed Services Committee chairman, Rep. Floyd 
Spence, R-S.C. ``Administration policy has been contentious and 
confusing, not only for Congress but for the American people as 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP provision has drawn a veto threat from the  
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and some Republicans are trying to strike that  
provision from a $288.8 billion defense authorization bill. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., supports the restriction  
but praised the peace agreement and U.S. forces in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the people of Yugoslavia see this as an opportunity to  
replace their leadership, especially Mr. Milosevic,'' Hastert said 
in reference to the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also are opposing use of U.S. taxes in rebuilding  
Serbia, outside the province of Kosovo, as long as Milosevic 
remains in power. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton expressed his opposition to the provision in separate  
late-morning phone calls to both Hastert and Skelton. 
</P>
<P>
	Skelton said the president told him he fully intends to send a  
request to Congress well before Sept. 30 to seek money for the 
peacekeeping operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican officials said Clinton made a similar pledge in his  
conversation with Hastert -- and he also suggested it was premature 
to discuss the peacekeeping operation in any detail during the 
current debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, as the House resumed debate on the defense measure,  
Hastert told reporters, ``We are thrilled, very very happy, 
relieved that there is an agreement in Kosovo. ... I think we can 
all be very happy and prayerful that that's happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Hastert added that the United States had already paid too  
much of the cost of the operation. When it comes to peacekeeping 
and rebuilding, he said he wants to make sure ``we aren't saddled 
with picking up the major part of the that burden as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the House voted late Wednesday to end another U.S.  
peacekeeping force -- the one that has been in Haiti since March 
1995. The House voted 227-198 to pull the permanent force out of 
the Caribbean nation by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our troops have been fired on in Haiti. ... Things have gone  
sour in Haiti,'' said Sen. Porter Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the 
House Intelligence Committee and the sponsor of the amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not fair to leave our troops in Haiti in an open-ended  
deployment,'' agreed Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., chairman of the 
House International Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a permanent force, the measure would allow  
``periodic, noncontinuous'' troop deployments there. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents complained that the peacekeeping force in Haiti  
numbered fewer than 500 troops. ``Haiti does not have an army now 
because they agreed to get rid of it,'' said Rep. John Conyers, 
D-Mich. ``Our troops are not in jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House also rejected, as it has done in past years, a  
proposal to liberalize the ban on abortions at military hospitals 
overseas. It turned back, 225-203, a proposal to allow the 
procedures if the woman paid for it with her own funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The House was also expected to take up a proposal by Rep. Tillie  
Fowler, R-Fla., that would require the president to get express 
prior approval from Congress before sending any forces to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the House voted 428-0 for a package of amendments  
from members of a House committee that last month concluded China 
stole U.S. nuclear secrets over a 20-year span. 
</P>
<P>
	The package beefs up counterintelligence programs at the Energy  
Department, requires polygraph tests of employees at national 
laboratories, restricts lab visits by foreigners and requires a 
barrage of new reports to Congress on technology exports. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1401  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
