<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Makes It Harder To Prove Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today made it harder for  
prosecutors to prove federal cases alleging bank, wire or mail 
fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled unanimously that prosecutors in such cases must  
prove that an allegedly fraudulent act affected the outcome of the 
transaction. The justices ordered a lower court to re-examine a 
Florida man's convictions for fraudulently obtaining more than $30 
million in loans for land purchase and development deals. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also ruled 6-3 that in tax fraud cases -- where proof  
of legal relevance also is required -- a judge's failure to submit 
that question to the jury sometimes can be considered harmless. The 
justices upheld Ellis E. Neder Jr.'s conviction of tax fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hold that materiality of falsehood is an element of the  
federal mail fraud, wire fraud and bank fraud statutes,'' Chief 
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Neder, of Jacksonville, was charged with fraudulently obtaining  
loans for his projects from 1984 to 1988. He defaulted on the loans 
and failed to report $5.7 million in income on his tax returns, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was charged with mail fraud, wire fraud, bank fraud and tax  
fraud. The trial judge told jurors that if they decided Neder's 
statements were false, the judge would decide whether they were 
``material,'' or legally relevant to the outcome of the 
transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Neder was convicted on numerous counts and sentenced to 12 years  
and three months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, the Supreme Court ruled that jurors, not judges, must  
decide issues of legal relevance if they are an element of a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Neder's  
convictions. The court ruled that the mail, wire and bank fraud 
laws did not require proof that Neder's statements were legally 
relevant. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court said the tax fraud law does require such  
proof. But because Neder did not dispute the issue, the judge's 
error in failing to submit the issue to the jury could be 
considered harmless, the court said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neder's lawyers argued to the Supreme Court that legal relevance  
is always an essential element of a fraud charge, even if it is not 
spelled out in the law. They also said a judge's failure to let a 
jury decide on an essential element of the tax fraud charge cannot 
be considered harmless. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court reversed the 11th Circuit court on the bank,  
wire and mail fraud issues. The justices ordered the lower court to 
decide whether the error in failing to have the jury decide on 
legal relevance could be considered harmless in Neder's case. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices upheld the lower court on the tax fraud issue.  
Joining Rehnquist in that part of the opinion were Justices Sandra 
Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, Clarence Thomas and Stephen G. 
Breyer. Justice John Paul Stevens agreed with the result but for 
different reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Antonin Scalia, David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg  
dissented from the ruling on the tax fraud charge. A failure to 
have a jury rule on an essential element of a charge can never be 
considered harmless, Scalia wrote for the three. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Neder vs. U.S., 97-1985.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
