<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faulk a No-Show at Rams Minicamp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Marshall Faulk is back to his no-deal, no-show  
stance. 
</P>
<P>
	While the running back waits for his contract to be reworked,  
he's sitting out the St. Louis Rams' minicamp that began Thursday. 
Coach Dick Vermeil said it was out of sight, out of mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, I'm disappointed he's not here, but that's his  
prerogative,'' Vermeil said. ``I thought he would be here, but he 
and his agent made that decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, it's a dead issue. He is not the  
topic of conversation around here. He knows where he belongs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Rams acquired Faulk from the Indianapolis Colts two  
days before the draft, he said he would attend no team functions 
until he got a new deal. He changed his mind for the first minicamp 
last month and showed up as an act of ``good faith,'' but 
apparently has had another change of heart. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams are believed to be offering Faulk a multiyear deal that  
would pay him about $5 million a year and Vermeil said he thought 
the negotiations were going well. Faulk's agent, Rocky Arceneaux of 
St. Louis, wasn't that upbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Arceneaux said he and the Rams have spoken only once this week  
and that no deal was imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt he showed some good faith and we thought that would  
give the negotiations a little more momentum,'' Arceneaux said. 
``It didn't give them enough momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just decided that in Marshall's best interests it was best  
he not go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his holdout, Faulk has been working out in St. Louis with  
noted trainer Bobby Kersee. 
</P>
<P>
	The minicamp is mandatory, so Faulk could be fined for failing  
to show. That appears unlikely, since the team's stance has been 
that Faulk would be treated as if he were a first-round draft pick. 
Unlike Vermeil, the Rams front office doesn't appear concerned 
about signing Faulk until training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither, really, are his teammates.  
</P>
<P>
	``We understand he has to do what he has to do,'' tight end  
Roland Williams said. ``He came to the first minicamp and let us 
know how he felt about the team and how much he wants to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk rushed for 1,319 yards and caught 86 passes last year and  
is set to make a base salary of $2.2 million next season under 
terms of the original seven-year deal he signed out of college. The 
Rams acquired him for second- and fifth-round draft picks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
