<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar edged lower against the yen Thursday  
after riding a foreign exchange rollercoaster that included an 
unusual intervention by the Bank of Japan that boosted the U.S. 
currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also fell against the euro as traders bought euros  
and dumped Swiss francs, helping the euro strengthen overall. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 118.84  
Japanese yen, down from 118.93 late Wednesday. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0489, up from $1.0465. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar initially fell during Asian trading after Japan's  
Economic Planning Agency reported that the economy grew in the 
first quarter, marking the first expansion after five quarters of 
contraction. Japan is experiencing its worst recession since World 
War II. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar rose as the Bank of Japan intervened in currency  
markets on the dollar's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually a country intervenes on behalf of its own currency, but  
Japanese officials recently expressed dissatisfaction with 
dollar/yen volatility. The dollar was worth more than 122 yen at 
the beginning of the month; it fell as low as 117.63 yen after the 
data were released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank confirmed the operation, also a rarely seen phenomenon.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think essentially it was a smoothing operation,'' said  
Dennis Heidt, chief currency dealer at Banque Paribas. ``They 
thought the currency was getting too volatile. I don't think it was 
any line in the sand: 'It won't go below 117.''' 
</P>
<P>
	But after the intervention, the market considered itself  
overextended and gradually sold off after the dollar reached 119.95 
yen in less than 30 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It went too far too fast,'' Heidt said. Meanwhile, ``the move  
down was gradual and orderly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other late trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.5225 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.5222, and 1.4624 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.4730. The British pound rose to $1.6054 from $1.6026. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 
1.8646 German marks, down from 1.8688; 6.2539 French francs, down 
from 6.2696; and 1,845.02 Italian lire, down from 1,851.85. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
