<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Budget Strategy Passing Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Speaker Dennis Hastert's new strategy on  
spending bills passed its latest test Thursday as the House 
approved a $1.92 billion measure financing Congress' own 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	As it did, the Clinton administration issued its first veto  
threat of the year against spending legislation, complaining that a 
Senate measure would cut funds for local police, the 2000 census 
and other programs too deeply. The threat was a vivid reminder that 
repeated budget clashes between President Clinton and lawmakers 
remain a near certainty this year. 
</P>
<P>
	House passage of the congressional spending measure on a largely  
party-line 214-197 vote kept alive the momentum GOP leaders 
acquired only Tuesday, when the chamber passed its first 
appropriations bill for fiscal 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	That occurred only after Hastert called for Republican unity in  
a dramatic closed-door meeting and agreed to make new cuts in 
several bills, pleasing conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Following through on that strategy, GOP leaders offered an  
amendment cutting $54 million from the measure financing Congress 
that passed by voice vote. Top Republicans had initially planned to 
cut only about $26 million from the bill, but sidestepped a fresh 
conservative rebellion by adding $28 million in cuts from the 
account financing members' own offices. Conservatives initially 
sought a cut totaling $90 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can live with it,'' Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., said  
of the $54 million cut. Young chairs the House Appropriations 
Committee, which wrote the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats tried blocking the House from even debating the  
spending bill, hoping that enough Republicans would join them to 
succeed. They prolonged debate into the evening with a parade of 
procedural votes, losing every one. And in a near party-line roll 
call the House voted 216-194 to consider the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is a cut for cut's sake'' in which GOP leaders  
are ``continuing to pander to the right wing,'' said Rep. Steny 
Hoyer, D-Md. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP House margin is so narrow that Democrats need defections  
from only six Republicans to prevail. They were hoping to deal a 
major embarrassment to Hastert, R-Ill., only two days after GOP 
leaders thought they had rallied their troops behind them. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers' votes on the bill financing Congress can be tough to  
predict, since it finances their own staffs and the taxpayer-paid 
mail on which they rely to help re-elect themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The $28 million cut in members' office expenses would keep that  
account at $385 million, the same as this year. The original bill 
planned a 7.3 percent increase, well above the rate of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenders said the increase was necessary to cover inflation and  
to give their aides a raise. 
</P>
<P>
	Before passage, a provision was deleted that would have required  
House offices to begin recycling their own trash. Some Republicans 
said they oppose forcing lawmakers to recycle. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the Capitol, the Senate Appropriations Committee approved  
its own $1.7 billion version of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	That bill covers Senate expenses and joint congressional items  
like the Capitol architect. The House bill covers House expenses 
and joint items. When combined, the price tag will be about $2.5 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate panel also approved a $35.3 billion measure financing  
the departments of Commerce, State and Justice. White House budget 
chief Jacob Lew sent Senate leaders a letter threatening a veto 
because the bill doesn't provide $1.3 billion Clinton wanted to 
hire local police officers and because it cuts the amount of money 
the administration wanted for the census, embassy construction and 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate committee also approved an $8.3 billion bill  
financing military construction. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee approved all three bills by 27-0.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
