<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Speaks Out for Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan urged  
Harvard graduates to strive for integrity and avoid the temptation 
to cut corners in their professional lives. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech prepared for delivery at afternoon commencement  
ceremonies in Cambridge, Mass., Greenspan conceded today that his 
advice ran the risk of ``sounding a bit uncool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he asked the 1999 graduating class to listen to the  
``musings of an old, idealistic central banker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said he believed strongly that ``your success in life  
and the success of our country is going to depend on the integrity 
and other qualities of character'' demonstrated by coming 
generations. 
</P>
<P>
	``A generation from now, as you watch your children graduate,  
you will want to be able to say that whatever success you achieved 
was the result of honest and productive work and that you dealt 
with people the way you would want them to deal with you,'' 
Greenspan said in his prepared remarks, which were distributed in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not deny that many appear to have succeeded in a material  
way by cutting corners and manipulating associates, both in their 
professional and personal lives. But material success is possible 
in this world and far more satisfying when it comes without 
exploiting others,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The true measure of a career is to be able to be content, even  
proud, that you succeeded through your own endeavors without 
leaving a trail of casualties in your wake,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trust is at the root of any economic system based on mutually  
beneficial exchange,'' Greenspan said. He said that integrity and 
trust were not only sound moral principles but sound economic 
precepts as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without mutual trust, and market participants abiding by a  
rule of law, no economy can prosper,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While financial markets have grown increasingly worried that the  
Federal Reserve may soon start raising interest rates to fight 
inflation, Greenspan made no mention of monetary policy in his 
prepared remarks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
