<HEADLINE> Globalstar Satellites Put in Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Four satellites were successfully  
put into orbit today, the latest additions to the 
multibillion-dollar Globalstar communications network. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellites -- worth about $15 million each -- separated in  
pairs about an hour after the Boeing rocket carrying them was 
launched. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif.-based Globalstar plans to begin providing  
wireless telephone service beginning this fall. Among the regions 
to receive initial service: parts of the United States, Europe, 
South America and South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	The first four satellites in the $3.3 billion Globalstar network  
were launched by Boeing in February 1998. Seven months later, 12 
Globalstar satellites were destroyed shortly after liftoff when the 
Ukrainian Zenit rocket carrying them failed. Part of the wreckage 
fell onto Siberia. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's last launch, in early May, ended with the satellite  
stranded in the wrong orbit. An investigation continues into the 
failure of that Delta III, a larger and upgraded version of the 
rocket launched today. 
</P>
<P>
	Altogether, 48 satellites are planned for the Globalstar  
constellation. Boeing Delta II rockets, as well as Russian Soyuz 
rockets, will be used to launch the remaining satellites. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's launch was valued at about $115 million, including the  
cost of the satellites and the Delta II rocket. It was delayed two 
days by bad weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The Globalstar consortium of 12 companies was founded by Loral  
Space and Communications Ltd. and Qualcomm Inc. 




</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
