<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Delays Mideast Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Thursday  
postponed a trip to the Middle East while Israel struggles to form 
a new government. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department advised Mrs. Clinton against the trip once  
it became clear in recent days that Israeli Prime Minister-elect 
Ehud Barak was having problems forming a government, an official 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip was to include stops in Israel, Jordan and Yemen for  
the so-called ``Emerging Democracy Conference'' there, and meetings 
with the Palestinian Authority. Mrs. Clinton's office said the trip 
will be rescheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	She was to make the trip after accompanying President Clinton to  
a summit meeting of seven industrial powers plus Russia in Germany, 
which ends June 20. That part of her trip remains unchanged. She 
also plans stops in Italy and Morocco. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not unusual for high profile trips to be delayed because  
of political sensitivities. President Clinton postponed an early 
1998 trip to South Asia because it would have coincided with an 
election campaign in India. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department official said the diplomatic advice to Mrs.  
Clinton is not a sign the United States has lost confidence that 
Barak can form a government. 
</P>
<P>
	Her trip to the Middle East originally was scheduled for March  
but was postponed then, as well, so as not to disturb the pending 
Israeli elections or Jordan's mourning of King Hussein's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton caused a stir a year ago when she went beyond U.S.  
policy in advocating a Palestinian state. The official U.S. 
position is that the issue of whether to create such a state should 
be negotiated between Israel and the Palestinians. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Tests TV's Fairness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was standard first lady fare -- Hillary Rodham  
Clinton collecting instruments for charity during an appearance on 
the ``Today'' show. 
</P>
<P>
	But now that she's inched closer to a Senate candidacy, such  
feel-good exposure may have political benefits. TV executives face 
a balancing act between coverage of the first lady and their 
practices to ensure fairness for candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a lot of uncharted territory,'' said Jay Severin, a  
Republican political consultant. ``We've never had a first lady 
who's run for political office before. This is the first of many 
questions: Is this right? Is this fair? Is this appropriate?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Along with the charity work, Mrs. Clinton was briefly  
interviewed Thursday by Katie Couric of ``Today.'' The first lady's 
appearance was organized through Save the Music, a charity started 
by the cable network VH1 to distribute recycled musical 
instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing outside the show's storefront studio in Rockefeller  
Center, she made small talk with the tourists who come to watch the 
show each day. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is beautiful. Is this yours?'' she asked a woman who was  
donating her grandmother's violin. Mrs. Clinton said she had 
already donated one of her husband's saxophones. 
</P>
<P>
	Out of fairness, ``Today'' executive producer Jeff Zucker said  
that he had unsuccessfully sought to have New York City Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani appear this week on the show. Giuliani, a 
Republican, is considered a possible opponent if Mrs. Clinton runs 
for the Senate in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that she's a potential candidate, you do have to think of  
things like this,'' he said, ``and we did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zucker said if Mrs. Clinton appears on ``Today'' again, it will  
be in a political interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives at ABC briefly talked about the impact on a  
prospective campaign when ``Good Morning America'' was invited to 
televise a town meeting on teen violence from the White House two 
weeks ago with President and Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The importance of the issue in the wake of the Colorado school  
massacre outweighed the political considerations, ABC News 
President David Westin said. Future decisions will be made on a 
case-by-case basis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly, one of the factors we will take into account is if  
it is more a matter of image in a political race or if it's 
newsworthy,'' he said. ``If it's newsworthy, we have to cover it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal equal time provisions, which ensure broadcasters give  
fair exposure to candidates, didn't apply to Mrs. Clinton's 
``Today'' appearance on Thursday for three reasons, said Andrew 
Schwartzman, president of the Washington-based Media Access 
Project. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules don't kick in until a person is a declared candidate.  
Even if Mrs. Clinton had declared, only other Democrats would be 
entitled to equal time until the party determines its nominee, 
Schwartzman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, NBC has a Federal Communications Commission  
exemption for the ``Today'' show that affects most political 
interviews, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is clearly benefiting from a journalistic  
honeymoon, said Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media 
and Public Affairs in Washington. In recent months, evening news 
shows have run 28 stories about her potential Senate candidacy and 
six stories about Vice President Gore's presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would think the morning news shows would act more like  
journalism instead of entertainment puff shows,'' Lichter said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McHale, Thompson: Hall of Fame? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Kevin McHale, who was a key member of  
the Boston Celtics in the early 1980s, and retired Georgetown coach 
John Thompson were among 13 nominated today as candidates for 
basketball's Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others who played for a time with the Celtics -- Dennis  
Johnson, Jo Jo White and Wayne Embry -- were also nominated. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale played 12 seasons with the Celtics and was part of a  
frontcourt with Robert Parish and Larry Bird. The team won NBA 
championships in 1981, 1984 and 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	At 6-foot-10, McHale used agility, long arms, and his array of  
moves to shoot over even taller defenders. He averaged 18 points 
per game for his career. But McHale was also picked three times to 
the NBA's Defensive Team. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, who retired from Georgetown this year, coached the  
team to its 1984 national championship and 14 straight NCAA 
tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	Other nominees this year are: Bob McAdoo, a two-time NBA  
champion with Los Angeles; Maurice Cheeks of the 1983 NBA 
championship team in Philadelphia; Dennis Johnson, who took a total 
of three championship rings with Boston and Seattle; Gus Johnson of 
the Baltimore Bullets, who died of a brain tumor in 1987; Sidney 
Moncrief of the Milwaukee Bucks; 1967 NBA ring-holder Chet Walker 
of Philadelphia; and White, who played with two championship Celtic 
teams and captured an Olympic gold medal with the U.S. team in 
1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The nominees also include Mount St. Mary's coach Jim Phelan,  
whose 800-442 record gave him more victories than any other active 
college coach; Tex Winter, an assistant Chicago Bulls coach who has 
spent 52 seasons at Div. 1 college and NBA teams -- more than any 
active coach; Morgan Wootten, the coach at DeMatha High School in 
Washington, D.C., whose record of 1,185-178 is the best ever for a 
high school coach; and Embry, who took an NBA championship with the 
Celtics in 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of the election will be announced June 21.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
