<DOCNO> APW19990610.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 17:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Selig: Royals Ownership Votes Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Baseball owners are not likely to act on Miles  
Prentice's bid to buy the Kansas City Royals at their September 
meeting, commissioner Bud Selig said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice, who has put together a group of more than 40 investors  
to buy the team for $75 million, met for almost three hours with 
the ownership committee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice reached his agreement with the team last Nov. 13. He  
and Royals president Mike Herman had been hopeful of getting 
approval of the owners in September, which Selig said was ``a 
possibility but not likely.'' The owners' next scheduled meeting 
after that is in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``The purchase of a baseball team is a unique process,'' Selig  
said. ``We've had other large groups. Every one of these has its 
own indigenous characteristics, which makes it difficult to assess 
and compare one to another. They made a very good presentation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig said the size of Prentice's group was ``not a particular  
concern,'' but was evasive when asked if the group's finances 
worried the committee. Baseball officials have expressed concern 
about whether the group has enough money to successfully operate 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to comment on the specifics,'' Selig said. ``We  
have a lot of information to digest, some of which was new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Selig had met previously with Prentice, Herman and Royals  
chairman David Glass, this was the first time information on the 
sale was given to the full ownership committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very confident we will have baseball in Kansas City and  
Miles Prentice will be the owner,'' Herman said. ``That's how I 
feel. Ask commissioner Selig how he feels. I'm not uncomfortable 
with this process because we've been there before. These are 
honorable men and it gets done at a pace they dictate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice, 56, a Vermont native who made his fortune as a lawyer  
in New York, characterized the meetings as ``a very positive 
exchange, a good dialogue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm optimistic. I've always remained optimistic because I  
believe in the integrity of the process,'' Prentice said. ``The way 
things have gone to date, I've never had any bad feelings at all. 
Both sides asked questions they wanted to ask and received the 
answers they wanted to get on the table. I think they were happy 
with them. I can't say any more than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig said the sale ``was too early in the process'' to  
determine when the sale will be in the form he will bring to an 
approval vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll be an ongoing exchange of information,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
