<HEADLINE> Accused Nazi Renounces Citizenship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A New York man accused of hiding a past as a  
guard at Nazi slave labor camps left the United States and 
renounced his citizenship, the Justice Department announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is abandoning a lawsuit filed a year ago against  
Dmytro Sawchuk, 74, of Glen Spey, because he went to the U.S. 
consulate in Frankfurt, Germany, in March and surrendered his U.S. 
passport and naturalization certificate. 
</P>
<P>
	In the federal court case in New York, Sawchuk was accused of  
concealing from U.S. authorities his having served at an SS-run 
training camp in Poland in 1943 and as an armed guard at two slave 
labor camps for Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint also said he guarded Jewish prisoners who were  
forced to exhume and burn the corpses of hundreds of thousands of 
Jews who were murdered at a death camp in Belzec, Poland, in 1942. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
