<HEADLINE> Wheat Up; Corn, Soybeans Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures advanced Thursday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, while corn and soybean futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat advanced after heavy rains fell in winter wheat growing  
areas, further delaying harvesting of mature crops and leaving them 
more vulnerable to disease and pests. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans retreated amid forecasts for timely rains to  
relieve young crops that have baked under above-normal temperatures 
in the Midwest for the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 4 3/4 cents to $2.59 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.20 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 cent to 
$1.24 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 2 1/2 cents to $4.69 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
amid concern about a large amount of slaughter-ready hogs at a time 
when supermarkets already have secured ample supplies for the 
summer. Beef futures also finished mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .17 cent to 66.15 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .05 cent to 77.32 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
fell .80 cent to 53.37cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 2.43 
cents to 47.62 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
