<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8:20 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serb Forces Begin Leaving Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes,  
Yugoslav army convoys began withdrawing from Kosovo today as part 
of a peace deal signed by Serbian and Western generals to end the 
Balkans conflict. About 150 trucks, other army vehicles and cars 
carrying soldiers crossed the northern border of Kosovo at Medare, 
Western reporters at the scene said. The Pentagon confirmed the 
withdrawal this morning, but said the pullout started more slowly 
than was expected. ``We know that one MUP (special police) unit has 
left. We'd like to see a lot more flow'' of troops across the 
border out of Kosovo, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Move Toward Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly 4,000 heavily armed U.S. troops moved  
toward Kosovo today, ready to help keep the peace in the shattered 
Balkan province once a newly signed peace deal with Yugoslavia took 
effect, the Pentagon said. Nearly 2,000 Marines aboard ships in the 
Aegean Sea began moving ashore in Greece at about dawn local time 
before heading overland to Macedonia to spearhead the entry of U.S. 
forces into Kosovo. At the same time, 200 Army troops are to begin 
flying to Macedonia from U.S. bases in Germany. The initial 
contingent of U.S. peacekeepers, which will enter Kosovo after the 
first British forces go in, will have tanks and other heavy armor. 

</P>
<P>
	Slow Indonesia Count Arouses Suspicion  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police tightened security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count aroused anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging is again plaguing the 
country. Election officials denied any improprieties, saying they 
have been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in 
Monday'parliamentary election, billed as the country's most 
democratic vote in 44 years. By today, unofficial results released 
to journalists show that 8.2 percent of the votes had been 
tabulated, a fraction of what had been promised. 

</P>
<P>
	Brain Damage-Cancer Defense Linked  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Testicular cancer can lead to seizures, memory  
loss and dementia long before the cancer is detected, researchers 
reported today in the third study to link brain damage to an immune 
system attack on cancer. The brain damage apparently is caused not 
by the cancer itself, but by an overly aggressive attack by body's 
own immune system on a protein produced by tumors, the researchers 
said. In today's New England Journal of Medicine, researchers said 
men with testicular cancer and damage to one of the brain's 
emotional centers had a particular type of antibody in their blood. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Premier Warns Lawmakers  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin warned lawmakers  
today that he might threaten their jobs if they failed to approve a 
package of economic austerity bills. Stepashin said he might call a 
confidence vote in his new Cabinet. If lawmakers vote 
no-confidence, then President Boris Yeltsin could disband the lower 
house, the State Duma, and call new elections -- a prospect 
lawmakers want to avoid. Communist and hard-line lawmakers, fearing 
a backlash from the public, have been resisting quick action on a 
series of bills that would introduce new taxes. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Stresses Loyalty To Church  
</P>
<P>
	SIEDLCE, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II stressed loyalty to the  
church today and warned young people against falling victim to 
``travesties of religion, or to manipulations of the truth.'' At a 
Mass attended by thousands of Roman Catholics and Eastern rite 
Catholics from Belarus, Ukraine and Russia, the pontiff called for 
people to follow the example of 13 martyrs slain in Pratulin in 
1874 for resisting conversion to Orthodox Christianity. ```How 
sweet it is to die for the faith.' These were their last words,'' 
John Paul said. 

</P>
<P>
	Nikkei Surges 480 Points  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks today jumped on optimism that the  
nation's economic recovery was picking up. The Nikkei surged 480.12 
points, closing the day's trading at 17,102.62. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockies 16, Mariners 11  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. hit his major league-leading 23rd  
home run, but the Colorado Rockies hit six homers and beat the 
Seattle Mariners 16-11 in a game delayed more than three hours by 
rain last night. Play was stopped for 3 hours, 18 minutes after 
Seattle scored three runs in the top of the seventh to cut 
Colorado's lead to 11-10. The teams combined for 10 home runs. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
