<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conviction Overturned in Cosby Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Autumn Jackson, imprisoned for allegedly trying  
to extort $40 million from Bill Cosby by threatening to tell the 
tabloids she was his illegitimate daughter, could soon be free on 
bail after a federal appeals court overturned her conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jackson, 24, was sentenced in 1997 to two years and two  
months in prison after she was convicted of extortion, conspiracy 
and crossing state lines to commit a crime. She has served just 
over half of the sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Wednesday ruled the  
trial judge improperly instructed the jury on the law of extortion. 
The court also overturned the convictions of two accomplices for 
the same reason, ordering the case returned to the lower court for 
retrial. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the appeals court said ``evidence at trial was plainly  
sufficient to support verdicts of guilty had the jury been properly 
instructed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court said the judge should have told jurors that in  
order to convict Ms. Jackson, they needed to find that she had 
wrongful intent. That would have allowed the jury to consider 
whether Ms. Jackson truly believed she was Cosby's daughter and 
therefore did not have any wrongful intent. 
</P>
<P>
	One of her lawyers, Robert Baum, said he would ask for Ms.  
Jackson to be freed on bail as soon as today. Prosecutors indicated 
they would not oppose the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White, said  
prosecutors hadn't decided whether to appeal the ruling. A lawyer 
for Cosby said the entertainer would support whatever decision they 
make. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Ms. Jackson demanded the money from Cosby on  
Jan. 16, 1997 -- the day Cosby's 27-year-old son, Ennis, was shot to 
death in a robbery while changing a flat tire on a Los Angeles 
highway. If Cosby failed to comply, she said, she would tell her 
story to the supermarket tabloids. The slaying of Cosby's son was 
unrelated to the alleged plot. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, Ms. Jackson and Jose Medina were arrested in New  
York in an FBI sting after signing a $24 million payoff agreement 
with Cosby's lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The case tarnished Cosby's wholesome TV image as husband and  
father when he was forced to disclose that he had an affair with 
Ms. Jackson's mother, Shawn Upshaw, in the 1970s. He had provided 
her with more than $100,000 in support over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	But he repeatedly denied he is Ms. Jackson's father, telling  
jurors that he told Ms. Jackson: ``I will be for you a father 
figure, but I am not your father.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of paternity was ruled irrelevant to the charges.  
Cosby took a paternity test after the trial to try to settle the 
dispute, but Ms. Jackson and her mother declined to take blood 
tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court also overturned the case against Medina, who  
was sentenced to five years and three months in prison, and Boris 
Sabas, who got three months behind bars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:41:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Trade Bill Clears Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. trade with sub-Saharan Africa would  
increase dramatically under a bill that moved closer Thursday to a 
full House vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Ways and Means Committee approved, by voice vote, a  
measure designed to foster economic growth in the 48 sub-Saharan 
countries by reducing tariffs and encouraging investments in 
infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, also by voice vote, approved a separate bill to  
assist Caribbean and Central American countries suffering from the 
devastation last fall by Hurricanes Georges and Mitch. The bill 
extends to those countries the same low tariffs that Mexico and 
Canada have under the North American Free Trade Agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Both measures advanced to the full House.  
</P>
<P>
	The Africa trade bill would grant duty-free and quota-free  
treatment to textile and apparel imports from African countries and 
provide enhanced market access to African products for 10 years. 
The countries would have to act to establish market-driven 
economies and not engage in human rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration strongly supports the bill, which  
many experts believe will lead to increased bilateral trade and 
investments with Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed a similar version last year, shortly before  
President Clinton made the first presidential visit to sub-Saharan 
Africa in 20 years. But it faltered in the Senate, as lawmakers 
from textile-industry states warned that it could hurt American 
textile workers, among other concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	The textile industry also has raised objections to both  
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the Africa bill continued Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis., expressed reservations about what he  
said was the bill's emphasis on supporting multinational corporate 
interests at the expense of broad-based economic and political 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the ranking Democratic member of the Senate subcommittee on  
Africa, I believe this is a critical issue and that we should be 
working to develop a bill that will be viable in both the House and 
Senate,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the legislation, which also is backed by the  
affected African nations, will help expand relations with a region 
that is teeming with a population of 700 million people but that 
accounts for just 2 percent of U.S. trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shifts our relationship with Africa from aid to trade,''  
said Rep. William Jefferson, D-La., a co-sponsor and Ways and Means 
Committee member. ``It's better for everyone to move forward to a 
profitable two-way, buy and sell business relationship that 
benefits everyone, than to maintain the status quo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to trade benefits, the Africa trade bill also  
protects against textile ``transshipment,'' in which a country will 
ship goods to the United States through another country that has 
access to tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The Africa trade bill is H.R. 4343; the Caribbean/Central  
America bill is H.R. 984. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:53:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.N. OKs Kosovo Peacekeeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council voted today to  
authorize an international peacekeeping force to move into Kosovo 
to ensure the safe return of 860,000 ethnic Albanian refugees 
driven from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution also calls for the United Nations to start  
rebuilding the province destroyed by war and NATO's 11-week bombing 
campaign, creating a civilian administration that would lay the 
groundwork for a future autonomous government. 
</P>
<P>
	It was approved 14-0 with China abstaining.  
</P>
<P>
	The council proceeded with the vote after NATO Secretary-General  
Javier Solana announced that Yugoslavia had sufficiently begun to 
withdraw its forces from Kosovo and that he had ordered the 11-week 
bombing campaign to stop. 
</P>
<P>
	The first troops of the force, consisting of NATO members and  
other countries, could arrive in Kosovo by Friday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	China and Russia had refused to vote until NATO stopped bombing.  
</P>
<P>
	China had attempted to drastically reduce NATO's power to act  
militarily in Yugoslavia if necessary. That amendment was rejected 
by other council members, but another amendment referring to the 
authority of the council was incorporated. 
</P>
<P>
	That satisfied Beijing's main concern, Deputy Ambassador Shen  
Guofang said in announcing after brief consultations this morning 
that he wouldn't block the resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution formally caps a sequence of events that began  
Wednesday with the signing of a military agreement between NATO and 
Yugoslavia that called for Yugoslavia to withdraw its forces from 
Kosovo within 11 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution authorizes NATO and other countries to send in  
troops to Kosovo and use ``all necessary means'' to protect 
returning ethnic Albanians for an indefinite period. It asks the 
United Nations to establish an interim administration for the Serb 
province that would give its residents ``substantial autonomy'' 
from Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to the council before the vote, Yugoslavia's U.N. envoy  
Vladislav Jovanovic said his country had succeeded in its two main 
goals -- ``successfully'' defending itself against NATO 
``aggression'' and keeping Kosovo part of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the indefinite mandate of the international force was  
unacceptable and a ``gross violation'' of Yugoslavia's sovereignty. 
He also accused the council of trying to dismember Yugoslavia by 
passing a resolution allowing for what he said would be the 
secession of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Beijing's main concern was that the resolution would be enacted  
under Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter, which makes it militarily 
enforceable. 
</P>
<P>
	China had wanted military action under Chapter 7 limited to  
protecting international personnel sent to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In a gesture to Beijing, council members did bow to China's  
other main concern late Wednesday, allowing the resolution to 
stress the principles of the U.N. Charter, particularly the 
responsibility of the Security Council for the maintenance of 
international peace and security. 
</P>
<P>
	China and Russia had based their opposition to NATO's airstrikes  
on the grounds that the alliance had taken matters of international 
peace into its own hands when it launched airstrikes March 24 
without approval from the council, where both members have veto 
power. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:53:45 </DATE_TIME>
