<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Negotiating Haskins' Buyout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The University of Minnesota is negotiating a  
contract buyout with basketball coach Clem Haskins amid allegations 
of academic fraud involving the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks with Haskins' lawyer, Ronald Zamansky, began last week but  
the matter became public during a regents meeting on Thursday. 
Regent Robert Bergland said regents didn't object to negotiations 
to buy out Haskins' contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the clear, overwhelming consensus was that we're going  
to wait until the president gets what he needs for decisions, and 
then we'll find out in more detail what's happening and counsel 
with him on what to do,'' Bergland said after Thursday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	In an open meeting to discuss gender-equity goals, McKinley  
Boston, vice president of athletic and student affairs, didn't 
comment on buyout negotiations and declined to answer questions 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	University president Mark Yudof authorized university general  
counsel Mark Rotenberg to begin negotiations with Haskins, even 
though an investigation into the scandal won't be completed until 
September. Rotenberg said Thursday no agreement had been reached 
and there was no timeline for the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston signed Haskins' 10-year contract in 1994 when he was the  
men's athletic director. It includes an unusual clause that allows 
Haskins to receive $423,000 in deferred compensation even if his 
contract is terminated with just cause. If just cause cannot be 
shown, Haskins would be entitled to almost $1.2 million, plus 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotenberg, who gave the status report on the negotiations to  
regents, declined to discuss their reactions. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter what happens, the investigation will be completed  
even if something happens and coach Haskins leaves,'' Bergland said 
after Thursday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Yudof would not say what prompted him to authorize the talks  
now, nor would he comment on any timeline for further action. Yudof 
and Rotenberg said the university hadn't begun looking for a 
replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	Various factors may be pressuring the university to move  
quickly. Yudof will be out of the country July 10-23 for a working 
trip to Europe and the Middle East. Haskins' contract includes a 
clause that would increase his buyout by $74,299 if he is released 
after July 1. And basketball recruiting could be hampered if the 
coach's status remains uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	Haskins, who has referred all calls to his lawyer, has denied  
any knowledge of academic cheating in his program or improper 
payments to players. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach is accused of tolerating and facilitating academic  
fraud among men's basketball players, misusing booster club money 
and intervening on behalf of athletes accused of sexual misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Former university employee Jan Gangelhoff said she did course  
work for at least 21 players from 1993-98, which was confirmed by 
four players, prompting the university to suspend four other 
current players from the NCAA tournament opener against Gonzaga in 
March. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:53:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Ruling Party Bounces Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's ruling Golkar Party,  
written off before this week's historic election as a spent force 
because of its authoritarian past, bounced back in vote counting 
Thursday. Party officials predicted it still might be able to lead 
a coalition in a new Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a development would dash the hopes of pro-reform parties,  
democracy activists and student protesters that the first free 
election in Indonesia in 44 years would wipe away the remnants of 
President Suharto's rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The autocratic Suharto, who like many Indonesians uses only one  
name, held power for 32 years thanks in part to support from 
Golkar, which enjoyed a huge parliamentary majority. 
</P>
<P>
	While those days appeared to be over, Golkar officials predicted  
the party would emerge with enough seats to block the rival 
frontrunner, Megawati Sukarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic Party 
for Struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	If so, Golkar might be able to reinstall Suharto's unpopular  
hand-picked successor, President B.J. Habibie, when a head of state 
is chosen by a special assembly in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are all afraid of Golkar and what they represent being  
resurrected from the grave. We have to keep it out of power,'' said 
newspaper commentator Wimar Witoelar. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadel Muhammad, a senior Golkar official, predicted Golkar would  
get 30 percent of the vote. Analysts have said some minor 
Muslim-based parties could swing behind Golkar along with a bloc of 
non-elected military-appointed legislators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can form a coalition with any party that has a  
similar platform and accepts Habibie as president,'' Fadel said. 
</P>
<P>
	So far only 14.3 percent of the 113 million votes cast on Monday  
have been tabulated. The extremely slow count has raised fears of 
tampering, similar to the manipulation that allowed Golkar to win 
landslide victories in tightly controlled ballots under Suharto. 
</P>
<P>
	Suharto, who is fending off allegations of large-scale  
corruption, resigned a year ago after bloody riots and student 
protests. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest unofficial results had Megawati's party leading with  
35.2 percent of the vote, followed by Golkar with 20.9 percent. 
Third was Megawati's main ally, the National Awakening Party headed 
by Muslim leader Abdurrahman Wahid, with 12.1 percent. Overall, 48 
parties fielded candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear how many seats those numbers would  
translate to in Indonesia's complex system of proportional 
representation. But the top vote-getter is not necessarily 
guaranteed the most seats in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign and local polling monitors have said the election itself  
was generally free and fair, despite minor irregularities. However, 
they have criticized the slow count, saying it could undermine 
public trust in the new democratic system. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudini, head of the General Elections Commission, denied claims  
of widespread foul play and blamed the delays on slow and 
meticulous work by workers processing ballots in tens of thousands 
of villages. 
</P>
<P>
	He said problems were inevitable because the election was set up  
in only three months, compared with three years in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people in Indonesia are impatient because this is the  
first time that we implemented a general election like this -- more 
democratic, more open and more fair,'' said Rudini, who uses only 
one name, like many Indonesians. 
</P>
<P>
	He said some provinces where there had been complaints about  
irregularities had been authorized to hold another vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The election for 462 seats in Parliament was the first step  
toward selecting a president. The new legislators will join 38 
representatives of the powerful military and 200 government 
appointees to choose a head of state in five months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:53:45 </DATE_TIME>
