<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fleisher Tries Following His Own Act  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Bruce Fleisher is just learning how to  
follow his own tough act. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher became the first player ever to win his first two  
career starts on the Senior PGA tour in February. He finished 
second the next two weeks, then added a third victory in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a ride,'' Fleisher said before Thursday's practice  
round for the BellSouth Classic. ``A lot of emotion, a lot of 
running around, a lot of demands. Things have settled down quite a 
bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher shot no higher than 70 in his first 12 rounds on the  
Senior tour, but has cooled off some since. His best finish in five 
events since winning the Home Depot Invitational was a tie for 13th 
a month ago at the Nationwide Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher attributes his fast start on the senior tour to playing  
regularly on the PGA tour until he turned 50. He has career 
winnings of $1.7 million on the PGA tour, and already has won more 
than half that much ($894,592) this year. That's second on the 
senior's money list to Allen Doyle, the only other three-time 
winner this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher said his whirlwind start proved to be a distraction  
he's just now worked his way out of. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't really been able to focus that well the last five or  
six weeks, and now I think I'm starting to,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He shot an 8-under 64 in a pro-am on Wednesday the first time he  
played the 6,783-yard Springhouse Golf Club course. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hitting the ball fine, but I haven't made a putt in six  
weeks,'' he said. ``You've got 54 holes, no cut. You'd better be 
putting out here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even on his bad weeks Fleisher hasn't been terrible. He's  
finished in the top 10 in half of his 12 starts, never worse than 
27th. He leads the tour in four categories: scoring (69.85), 
putting (1.747), sand saves (66 percent) and all-around. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really just happy to be out here,'' he said, the ``we''  
being him and caddy Dennis Turning. ``Winning is certainly a bonus, 
but we're still feeling our way around in the first year. Winning 
gives you the confidence you can do it, but it's hard to keep that 
intensity up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher is the leading money-winner in the field for the  
BellSouth, which begins Friday. Doyle, who won the Cadillac NFL 
Golf Classic last week, withdrew due to back spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	Isao Aoki, the 1998 champion and winner of two of the last three  
BellSouth Classics, is back to defend his title. All the former 
champions are here: Gil Morgan ('97), Jim Dent ('95) and Lee 
Trevino ('94). 
</P>
<P>
	The total purse is $1.4 million, with $210,000 going to the  
winner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0268 </DOCNO>
