<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 16:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Challenges Gov't. Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A computer expert asked by the government to  
create a program that would remove Microsoft's Internet browser 
from its Windows operating system watched his program fail Thursday 
during a courtroom demonstration. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Felten, a computer science professor at Princeton  
University, took the stand as the government's final rebuttal 
witness in the Microsoft antitrust trial. He had testified 
previously; last December he described a program he wrote that took 
Internet Explorer out of Windows 98. A modified version of that 
program was introduced as evidence Thursday shortly after Felten 
made his second appearance in the witness box. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft attorney Steve Holley immediately challenged the  
program's effectiveness, arguing that the program did not remove 
the browser from Windows, but simply hid it. To prove his point, 
Holley presented Felten with a laptop computer and asked him to 
install his new ``removal'' program. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten resisted, saying he couldn't vouch for the effectiveness  
of the program since the computer he was given was loaded with 
numerous software programs, including multiple Internet browsers. 
The computers on which he had tested his removal program were 
loaded only with Windows 98. 
</P>
<P>
	He ultimately installed the program and, afterward, followed a  
series of instructions by Holley, at the end of which another 
Internet Explorer browser appeared on the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is that, Mr. Felten?'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how it got there,'' Felten responded. He  
maintained, however, that ``the removal program is still a valid 
proof of concept.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The point of this is to show that Microsoft can do this.  
...There are many ways in which Microsoft can go about delivering 
Windows 98 without IE,'' Felten said. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten's testimony -- that there is no technical reason for  
Microsoft to bundle its Web browser into the popular Windows 
operating system -- touches on a central claim in the government's 
antitrust case. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that Windows and its browser are so closely  
integrated that it is impossible to remove the Web software without 
crippling Windows. The government, however, alleges that Microsoft 
illegally ``tied'' Windows and its browser to undermine Netscape 
Communications Corp., whose Web software is Microsoft's biggest 
competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department called upon Felten to testify again to  
help debunk previous testimony from a Microsoft executive who found 
Felten's original program full of bugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will rule on the case without  
a jury, suggested another reason why some consumers may not want a 
browser integrated into their operating system: computer security. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the courtroom demonstration, he asked Felten whether  
there was a difference in risks between having the choice of a 
browser or having none at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten said there was. Some companies, he said, may not want  
computers with Web browsers because it could allow employees to 
roam freely on the Internet. That could be risky for more 
inexperienced users. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems self-evident to me that the presence of a browser  
increases the risk of penetration of a virus,'' Jackson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten agreed, saying there was less chance of introducing a  
virus into a system if it didn't have a browser than if it did. 
</P>
<P>
	His main purpose in the trial was to rebut testimony from  
Microsoft executive James Allchin, who complained that Felten's 
tinkering disabled a popular feature in Windows 98 that allows 
consumers to install off the Internet incremental updates and 
improvements to Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Felten testified that the new version of his program leaves such  
files intact. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
