<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Nears Vote on Y2K Litigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate was moving toward passage of  
legislation to protect businesses from being broadsided by lawsuits 
arising from computers tainted by the millennium bug. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senate bill, a compromise between Republicans and  
Democrats that has been months in the making, faces a tough future, 
criticized on the one hand by House members who say it is too weak 
and on the other by the Clinton administration, which says it is 
too strong and will be vetoed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., with  
the help of Democratic Sens. Ron Wyden of Oregon and Christopher 
Dodd of Connecticut, would give companies 90 days to fix Y2K 
glitches before lawsuits can be filed and would encourage 
mediation. 
</P>
<P>
	It would limit class action lawsuits, ensure that most companies  
are liable only for the proportion of the damage they cause and set 
punitive damage caps for companies with 50 or fewer employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Failure to pass this responsible legislation would be like  
sticking a monkey wrench in the high-tech engine that is driving 
our economic prosperity,'' Wyden said. Business leaders who have 
actively lobbied for the bill have said it is their top legislative 
priority for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	With passage, possible today or Friday, the bill would have to  
be reconciled with a House-passed version that is stronger in 
protecting defendants from lawsuits and supporters would have to 
deal with the White House veto threat. The administration says the 
Senate bill, while better than the House alternative, still goes 
too far in curbing a consumer's legal rights to seek damages for 
economic losses. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday the Senate defeated, 57-41, a substitute version  
offered by Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., that was acceptable to the 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerry's measure, while similar in most respects to McCain's,  
would have exempted individual consumers from the limits set by the 
legislation, eliminated all punitive damage caps and applied 
proportionate damage -- holding companies responsible only for their 
share of damage caused -- only to defendants that had alerted users 
to Y2K problems. 
</P>
<P>
	An amendment by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., to exempt consumers  
from the bill was also defeated, 65-32. 
</P>
<P>
	The lone Democrat to speak out against the need for lawsuit  
controls was Sen. Ernest Hollings of South Carolina. Hollings said 
trial lawyers and punitive damage awards are essential to consumer 
interests in America and linked enthusiasm for a litigation bill to 
the political contributions of the high-tech industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silicon Valley has got the money and people are falling over  
pell-mell,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 96.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
