<HEADLINE> Bauer Qualifies for Matching Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful and conservative  
activist Gary Bauer announced Thursday that he has raised enough 
money to qualify for federal matching dollars in January 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	To become eligible for matching dollars, a presidential  
candidate must raise a minimum of $5,000 in each of at least 20 
states. Bauer's campaign met that threshold in 23 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer's campaign must now begin submitting monthly reports to  
the Federal Election Commission -- which oversees the matching funds 
-- in order to receive money at the beginning of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Bauer campaign is continuing to gain valuable resources  
nationwide,'' said campaign manager Frank Cannon. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Less than a week after his appointment, a  
California co-chairman of George W. Bush's presidential bid 
resigned after conflict-of interest questions were raised. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruben Barrales, chief executive officer of Joint Venture:  
Silicon Valley, quit after board members of the nonpartisan group 
suggested his political activities were inappropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	The venture is a regional collaboration of public organizations  
and private businesses working to improve the economy and quality 
of life in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is inappropriate for the head of the organization, in my  
view, to take an activist role, to say nothing of a leadership 
role, in a political campaign,'' said venture member Jay T. Harris, 
publisher of the San Jose Mercury News. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to avoid any appearance of partisanship,'' Barrales  
said Wednesday. ``It was a decision I reached on my own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group of six co-chairmen for the Texas governor's California  
effort was carefully selected to represent the state's racial and 
economic diversity. They were named June 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrales is Hispanic, like the fastest-growing segment of the  
California electorate, and also represented the crucial high-tech 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- GOP hopeful Gary Bauer became the latest  
GOP candidate to bash Texas Gov. George W. Bush on his abortion 
stance Thursday, arguing the front-runner is ducking the issue and 
won't commit to name only anti-abortion justices to the Supreme 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of making that commitment, Governor Bush talks about  
all sorts of side issues and avoids the heart of the matter,'' said 
Bauer, in an interview. ``It's consistent with his lack of 
leadership, quite frankly, generally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said Bush's vagueness on many issues during the early  
stages of the campaign will not sit well with conservative 
activists who decide Iowa caucus campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to see, I think, that his campaign peaked a couple  
of weeks ago,'' said Bauer. ``As more details come out on these 
sorts of issues, conservatives generally are going to find it very 
hard to swallow the vagueness of his agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole appointed a new finance  
chairwoman Thursday for her presidential exploratory committee, 
which has been stymied in its fund-raising efforts by a crowded 
field of Republican hopefuls. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonnie McElveen-Hunter, who is president and owner of a North  
Carolina publishing and communications company, brings a solid 
business and fund-raising background to the Dole team. 
</P>
<P>
	McElveen-Hunter has raised money for several charitable  
organizations, including Habitat for Humanity and the United Way. 
Her company, Pace Communications, is one of the largest 
female-owned companies in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found the ideal chairwoman -- an innovative entrepreneur who  
will help us bring new donors and voters into our campaign,'' Mrs. 
Dole said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole announced last week that she had raised enough funds  
to be eligible for federal matching dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has raided a fellow  
Republican governor's staff to bulk up his presidential exploratory 
committee communications office.	   Andrew Malcolm, most recently executive assistant and chief of 
communications for Montana Gov. Marc Racicot, will become senior 
communications strategist for the Bush campaign, dealing mainly 
with print reporters and helping coordinate the campaign's state 
press secretaries. 
</P>
<P>
	For 26 years before joining Racicot's staff in 1993, Malcolm was  
a reporter, columnist and bureau chief for The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Malcolm says he is excited to join Bush's campaign.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm delighted to be thought of as a part of his team,''  
Malcolm said Thursday. ``It has been a wonderful experience for me 
to work for Governor Racicot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN (AP) -- The ``Biography'' television show devoted to Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush was viewed in some 1.86 million households. 
That tops a show about another presidential candidate, but falls 
far short of breaking the record for the show, program officials 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The program, which aired Wednesday night on the A&AMP;E cable  
network, topped an earlier ``Biography'' about Sen. John McCain, 
R-Ariz., which averaged 1.61 million households. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the network, both presidential hopefuls trail far  
behind the leader in ``Biography'' ratings: Andre the Giant. A 
program about the late wrestler's life was watched by a record 3.4 
million households in January. 
</P>
<P>
	``Biography'' is planning profiles of all the major presidential  
contenders this year, said A&AMP;E senior vice president Michael 
Cascio. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Douglas Kiker in Washington, Michael Glover in Des  
Moines, Iowa, and Mike Holmes in Austin, Texas, contributed to this 
report. 
  	   	
</P>
