<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Aircraft Silent in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	KUMANOVO, Macedonia (AP) -- Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug news  
agency is reporting that the last airstrikes occurred early 
yesterday evening, when the city of Urosevac in southern Kosovo was 
hit. ``The enemy aircraft fell silent after that,'' Tanjug said. 
Yugoslav and Western generals signed a pact yesterday clearing the 
way for a peace plan for the shattered Serb province after 78 days 
of intense NATO airstrikes. The alliance began bombing Yugoslavia 
after President Slobodan Milosevic refused to sign a peace 
agreement for Kosovo 

</P>
<P>
	Belgraders Celebrate Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Thousands of smiling, elated  
Belgraders took to the streets last night to celebrate the signing 
of an agreement that could end 11 weeks of NATO's bombing campaign 
in Yugoslavia. Carrying Yugoslav flags and flares, honking car 
horns, even opening champagne to celebrate, residents of the 
Yugoslav capital stormed the main square in cars and on foot. 
``Thank God it is over!'' shouted 22-year-old Mirjana Jankovic, 
laughing with her friends and reveling on a warm summer evening. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Emphasizes Christian Unity  
</P>
<P>
	SIEDLCE, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II will meet today with  
Orthodox Christians during a trip to eastern Poland. Orthodox 
Christian Churches and the Roman Catholic Church have been 
separated since the Great Schism in 1054 in a dispute over papal 
authority and interpretation of their creed. The dispute is rooted 
in a decision by Emperor Constantine in 330 to move the capital of 
the Roman Empire to Byzantium, later Constantinople. John Paul, the 
head of the Roman Catholic Church, is emphasizing Christian unity 
and religious pluralism during his 13-day pilgrimage to his 
homeland. 

</P>
<P>
	Slow Count Arouses Suspicion in Indonesia  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police tightened security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count aroused anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging was again plaguing the 
country. Election officials denied any improprieties, saying they 
have been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in Monday's 
parliamentary election, billed as the country's most democratic 
vote in 44 years. By today, unofficial results released to 
journalists showed that 8.2 percent of the votes had been 
tabulated, a fraction of what had been promised. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA To Allow Carry-On Coffee  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration decided  
yesterday that airline passengers can keep cups of coffee they've 
carried onto airplanes -- even through takeoff. The decision comes 
after a flight attendant for Alaska Airlines complained that the 
FAA inspector overseeing the West Coast carrier was forcing it to 
collect carry-on coffee cups out of concern that passengers could 
be splashed. But inspectors overseeing Alaska's competitors did not 
have the same rule, prompting complaints of unfairness. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Advance  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks today jumped on optimism that the  
nation's economic recovery was picking up. The Nikkei Stock Average 
surged 480.12 points, closing the day's trading at 17,102.62 
points. Yesterday the average closed up 59.58 points. The Nikkei 
was its highest closing level today since May 6, when the index 
finished at 17,300.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks Defeat Cubs 8-7  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Randy Johnson struck out 14 in his fourth  
consecutive victory and the Arizona Diamondbacks barely weathered a 
six-run eighth-inning rally by Chicago to beat the Cubs 8-7 last 
night and avoid a sweep. Byung-Hyun Kim, Arizona's 20-year-old 
South Korean pitcher, was thrown out of the game after the eighth 
inning because a bandage, possibly containing a foreign substance, 
had fallen out of the collar of his jersey on a pitch. Sammy Sosa, 
who struck out three times, homered off Johnson's first pitch in 
the eighth, a shot that traveled an estimated 443 feet to left. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Beat Blue Jays 4-3 in 14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rey Ordonez shook off an 0-for-5 night by  
singling in the winning run in the 14th inning of the New York 
Mets' 4-3 victory over the Toronto Blue Jays last night. The Mets, 
one out away from defeat, rallied for three runs off David Wells in 
the ninth. With runners on second and third, Robin Ventura lined a 
two-run single to center to make it 3-2. New York won its fourth 
straight game since general manager Steve Phillips fired half the 
coaching staff on Saturday night following an eight-game losing 
streak. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
