<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Look To Improve Rural Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission will ask  
telecommunications companies whether regulations need to be relaxed 
in order to improve Internet access in rural areas, its chairman 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency also intends to hold field hearings to hear the  
concerns of rural residents, Chairmen Bill Kennard said after 
meeting for an hour with a group of farm-state Senate Democrats, 
led by Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers want the commission to subsidize high-speed  
Internet access in rural communities. Kennard said the commission 
would consider the idea but left a brief news conference without 
taking questions on the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet ``is as important to rural America as the highway  
system was in the 1940s and 1950s and the railroads were at the 
turn of the century,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress said in a 1996 law that rural areas should have  
telecommunications services ``reasonably comparable'' to those in 
cities. But lawmakers left it up to the FCC to decide how to 
accomplish it. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already is funneling nearly $1.7 billion in  
subsidies to schools and libraries this year, including those in 
rural areas and inner cities, for a variety of telecommunications 
needs, including Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC recently voted to boost that funding to $2.25 billion,  
despite concerns it would raise phone bills. The money is collected 
from phone companies, which usually pass the fees on to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The senators say farmers, rural businesses and small-town  
health-care facilities need access to high-speed Internet services 
for transmitting graphics and large amounts of data. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the revolution in telecommunications continues to advance,  
we cannot let our country be divided into technological haves and 
have-nots,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said, ``There are hundreds of thousands  
of jobs at stake. There's a way of life at stake in rural areas.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
