<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 23:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Gives Clinton Win-Win Moment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, addressing the nation as  
commander in chief, got to deliver the best possible news to 
Americans: The war is over, and not a single American died in 
combat. 
</P>
<P>
	Even many Clinton detractors are giving him credit for a  
remarkable political achievement -- capping a risky, 11-week 
military campaign against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	If ever there was a win-win moment for the president, who only  
months earlier stood on impeachment trial in the Senate, this 
clearly was it. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Kosovo we did the right thing. We did it the right way. And  
we will finish the job,'' Clinton said in a speech Thursday night 
to the nation. And with the exception of a few still-disgruntled 
Republicans, few politicians seemed interested in challenging that 
assertion. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly is a plus for Clinton overall,'' said Lee  
Hamilton, who heads the Woodrow Wilson International Center for 
scholars, a Washington think tank. 
</P>
<P>
	``He fought a war that got the results he wanted without a  
single casualty. That is phenomenal,'' said Hamilton, former senior 
Democrat on the House International Relations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	And even if sometimes grudgingly, many leading Republicans  
joined in the applause. 
</P>
<P>
	``All Americans should be relieved,'' said Sen. John McCain of  
Arizona, a 2000 Republican presidential candidate who had been 
sharply critical of Clinton for not planning for a ground war. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can argue about whether we should have become involved in  
this conflict and about how we prosecuted the war, but we should 
all agree that our victory is very good news for the United States, 
NATO and for the world,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	And House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters, ``We  
are thrilled, very happy, relieved that there is an agreement in 
Kosovo. ... I think we can all be very happy and prayerful that 
that's happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't mean Republican attacks on Clinton have been  
stilled. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his harshest detractors in the House were unwilling to  
give the president any credit. ``It can be argued that Mr. 
Milosevic has accomplished most of his goals,'' said Rep. Duncan 
Hunter, R-Calif. ``This is certainly no victory,'' said Rep. Mark 
Souder, R-Ind. He said Kosovo was less stable now than it was 
before 11 weeks of bombing. ``If this is a victory, what would a 
defeat look like?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as Clinton was receiving widespread praise elsewhere, the  
House was debating -- incredibly, said Democrats -- a Republican 
provision to bar funds for peacekeepers in Kosovo after Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The House in the end rejected the provision -- during debate on a  
defense spending bill -- on a 270-155 vote. But only after Clinton 
promised in writing that he would seek congressional approval for 
funding the 7,000 American peacekeepers and to pay for them 
``without harming military readiness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, 142 Republicans voted in favor of keeping the funding  
cutoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be a death wish on the part of Republicans,'' said  
Thomas Mann of the Brookings Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mann also suggested Clinton may not be able to reap as much  
of a boost from the victory as President Bush did, if briefly, from 
his 1991 Gulf War victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans aren't deeply engaged in this issue. But you can be  
sure, at least at this stage, they're grateful for an end to the 
bombing,'' Mann said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton said the real ``genius of this agreement'' may be that  
it also offers Russians an opportunity to claim a much-needed boost 
in prestige at a time of deteriorating relations between Washington 
and Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to say they ended the war. They were the key  
actors in the diplomacy. Their ideas were rejected, but their role 
was enhanced,'' Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Republicans in Congress seemed incredulous that Clinton had  
managed to pull it off yet again -- producing a political victory 
after following a course fraught with risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why are we so eager to say a victory has been achieved?''  
asked Rep. Stephen Buyer, R-Ind., one of the House impeachment 
managers in the Senate's trial of Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Greenstein, a political science professor at Princeton  
University, said Clinton is now ``standing tall, having suddenly 
played commander-in-chief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That said, Greenstein added that it's hard to know what the  
impact of the achievement will be, coming so late in Clinton's 
presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know how it's going to fit into the obituary,''  
Greenstein said. ``Will it replace Monica?'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international  
affairs for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
