<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gwynn's Return Pushed Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Tony Gwynn's quest for 3,000 hits remains on  
hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn felt a knot in his left calf before Thursday's game  
against the Oakland Athletics and his planned return to the San 
Diego Padres' lineup was scrapped. 
</P>
<P>
	The banged-up Padres held off activating Gwynn from the 15-day  
disabled list in order to see how he felt during batting practice. 
Rookie Mike Darr, who would have been optioned to Triple-A Las 
Vegas had Gwynn been activated, was told to take batting practice 
and be ready. 
</P>
<P>
	Darr ended up starting in right field and batting second, the  
fourth straight game in which manager Bruce Bochy has started three 
rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn ``said he felt good yesterday, but that doesn't mean he'll  
feel good today,'' general manager Kevin Towers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 39-year-old Gwynn, who is 25 hits short of 3,000, didn't  
have much to say after San Diego's 2-1 win over Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to talk about nothin' today. Sorry,'' said Gwynn,  
who has been out since straining his left calf coming out of the 
batter's box against Cincinnati on May 21. ``I'll try again 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn thought he was ready to return Wednesday night, but Bochy  
held him out and said he planned to start the eight-time batting 
champion Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just felt a little something in there and didn't want to  
take a chance,'' Bochy said Thursday. ``We're going to give him a 
day or two. As much as he wants to play, he did own up to some 
discomfort. He did the right thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres open a three-game series at Houston on Friday. Bochy  
said Gwynn could be activated Saturday, or, with an off day Monday, 
the team might wait until it returns to San Diego Tuesday night to 
face Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Gwynn returned Thursday, he would have been on pace to get  
his 3,000th hit July 1 against the Los Angeles Dodgers in the final 
game of a seven-game homestand. The Padres are at Colorado July 
2-4, then come home to face San Francisco July 5 in the opener of a 
six-game homestand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres were held to four hits by Jimmy Haynes and two  
relievers in losing 3-0 Wednesday night. They are 7-11 since Gwynn 
went on the disabled list May 22. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Gwynn went out, the Padres have been shut out three times  
and held to five or fewer hits six times. While Gwynn is hitting 
.333, five players who have started in right field during his 
absence are batting just .190 (12-for-63) with four homers and 
eight RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	The defending NL champion Padres are hitting a league-low .247.  
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Wally Joyner, shortstop Chris Gomez and left  
fielder Reggie Sanders are also on the disabled list. Catcher 
Carlos Hernandez suffered a season-ending Achilles' injury in 
spring training. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
