<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Testimony Admitted in Lewis Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The defense in the malpractice case stemming from  
the death of Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis won a victory 
Thursday when a judge allowed the testimony of a man expected to 
say he used cocaine with the player. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith denied a motion by  
lawyers for Lewis' widow that would have prevented Wayne Brown's 
allegations from entering the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In sworn testimony, Brown said he used cocaine with the NBA  
All-Star on several occasions. Brown apparently is overseas and 
unavailable to testify in person, so his testimony would be read 
aloud in court, if defense lawyers decide to use it. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gilbert Mudge, the main defendant in the suit filed by Donna  
Harris-Lewis, has testified that Lewis confessed two weeks before 
his death in July 1993 that he had used cocaine -- a claim 
vehemently denied by his widow. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, a renowned cardiologist, and consultants Drs. Mark  
Creager and Peter Friedman, were sued by Harris-Lewis, who claims 
they misdiagnosed and mistreated her husband's fatal heart 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	An earlier diagnosis by a team of doctors said Lewis had a  
life-threatening arrhythmia after he collapsed during a playoff 
game. Mudge said during a May 1993 news conference that Lewis' 
heart was normal and that he suffered from a neurological condition 
that causes fainting spells. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, Lewis died of an arrhythmia, or abnormal heart  
rhythm, while practicing jump shots. He was 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge has said the late cocaine admission by Lewis made an  
accurate diagnosis impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Thursday, Dr. Robert J. Myerburg, chief of cardiology at  
the University of Miami School of Medicine, testified as an expert 
on behalf of Friedman, who performed a test on Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Myerburg emphasized that Friedman was a consultant in Lewis'  
care, not his lead doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was consulted to give opinions,'' Myerburg said. ``He did  
not have overall responsibility for treatment plans.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
