<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 13:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Restoration of Medicare Funds Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unless lawmakers restore some money they cut  
from Medicare to help balance the federal budget, the sickest 
senior citizens may suffer a lack of care, government and private 
experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be an access problem developing for the most complex  
patients,'' said William Scanlon, director of health financing at 
the General Accounting Office, Congress's auditing agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Scanlon and other government and private experts testified  
Thursday at a hearing of the Senate Finance Committee, which is 
confronting complaints about Medicare cuts that Congress set in 
motion in 1997 as part of an agreement to balance the federal 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, lawmakers agreed to trim $115 billion from  
Medicare's spending over five years -- mainly from payments to 
health care providers. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, medical industry groups along with some patient advocates  
say the cuts were too deep and they are lobbying hard to get some 
money back. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts who testified Thursday said there's little evidence the  
1997 cuts are causing widespread harm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not suggesting a wholesale redo of the balanced budget  
act,'' said Gail Wilensky, chair of the Medicare Payment Advisory 
Committee, a panel of private experts who advise Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she said new per-patient payment limits on some health  
care providers -- including nursing homes, home health agencies and 
physical therapists -- may not provide enough for the most expensive 
patients. As a result, patients with very serious or chronic 
medical conditions may have trouble finding a nursing home bed or 
home health care. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilensky urged lawmakers to look for ways to target some extra  
dollars to health care providers ``to protect the very sickest 
patients.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The warning comes even as Congress is looking for additional  
Medicare savings this year to help prepare the health insurance 
program for the elderly and disabled for an onslaught of aging baby 
boomers in about a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers expressed frustration with the competing demands.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've got the political theory that in even years we cut  
Medicare and in odd years we put the money back,'' said Sen. John 
Breaux, D-La. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
