<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices tumbled Thursday, pushing yields on  
30-year Treasury issues to their highest levels in more than 13 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 15/32  
point, or $4.68 3/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.06 percent from 6.02 percent 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the highest closing level for the long bonds since they  
finished at 6.07 percent on April 29, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said an unexpectedly strong report on economic growth  
in Japan in the first three months of the year suggested that the 
global economic situation is improving and could generate 
inflationary pressures worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve policy-makers have already indicated they are  
leaning toward a tighter monetary policy and many analysts expect 
they could raise interest rates later this month to curb inflation 
in the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates would diminish the value of bonds already in  
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sentiment in the bond market remains distinctively negative,''  
said Williams V. Sullivan Jr., a senior money market economist at 
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``There is no appetite to take risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the report from Japan that the economy there grew 1.9  
percent in the first quarter, the first gain since the summer of 
1997, set the tone for bond trading in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``It suggests the global economy is healing, and that means  
there is a greater chance of overheating and inflation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said the U.S. market faces a heavy calendar of  
corporate bond issues as well as a number of economic indicators in 
the next week that could show that the pace of consumer spending is 
growing. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one wants to step in front of these upcoming challenges''  
by buying bonds for the time being, Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were off by between 2/32 point and 7/32 point and intermediate 
maturities were off as much as 10/32 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.65 percent as the  
discount gained 0.06 percentage point to 4.53 percent. Six-month 
yields were 5.01 percent, as the discount added 0.04 percentage 
point to 4.82 percent. One-year yields were 5.09 percent as the 
discount held steady at 4.84 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 1/4 percent from 4.75 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 25/32 to 119 21/32. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.51 percent from 5.46 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
