<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines OK Customer Service Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's major airlines today agreed to a  
plan for better treatment of their passengers, a voluntary move 
aimed at holding off more serious mandatory directives from 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	One part of the 12-point plan, a draft of which was obtained  
Wednesday by The Associated Press, would commit airlines to meeting 
customers' essential needs during long, on-aircraft delays. That 
would include making ``every reasonable effort to provide food, 
water, restroom facilities and access to medical treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That commitment stems from the New Year's travel delays in  
Detroit, when passengers stuck on snowbound plans were held for 
hours in view of the airport terminal, in some cases without access 
to food, water or functioning toilets. Complaints about such 
treatment prompted several bills in the House and Senate this year. 
</P>
<P>
	One such bill would require airlines to pay passengers  
compensation when they are stranded for more than two hours. 
Another would give passengers 48 hours to cancel nonrefundable 
tickets. Northwest Airlines, the focus for many of the New Year's 
complaints, also was criticized last week by the Transportation 
Department for its handling of the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The heads of the nation's major airlines were planning to  
announce the plan during a midday news conference in downtown 
Washington. They had been expected to announce it during a news 
conference with lawmakers on Capitol Hill, but that was postponed 
Wednesday when last-minute glitches arose. 
</P>
<P>
	David Fuscus, spokesman for the Air Transport Association, the  
trade group representing the airlines, said: ``Clearly there has 
been an outcry on this issue. Certainly Congress has been at the 
forefront of it. And we've been talking with members about it and 
ways to do a better job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides better treatment of stranded passengers, the airline  
plan would publicly commit the airlines to several things that have 
been proposed by Congress and the Clinton administration, or which 
already are the law or are the current policies of some carriers. 
According to the draft, they include: 
</P>
<P>
	--Providing the lowest fare available on telephone reservation  
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	--Notifying customers of known delays, cancellations and  
diversions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Return of checked baggage within 24 hours.  
</P>
<P>
	--Increasing the baggage liability limit from the current $1,250  
per bag. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowing reservations to be held or canceled.  
</P>
<P>
	--Providing prompt ticket refunds.  
</P>
<P>
	--Disclosing airline procedures for accommodating disabled  
passengers or minors traveling alone. 
</P>
<P>
	--Establishing and disclosing policies for all passengers who are  
kept off a flight despite a confirmed reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	--Disclosing in advance aircraft seating plans, rules on frequent  
flier redemptions and ticket cancellation policies. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ensuring flight partners provide comparable customer service.  
</P>
<P>
	--Assuring that all written complaints are answered within 60  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	The service commitment says the plans will be completed by Dec.  
15 and fully implemented by June 15, 2000. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
