<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Slave Labor Fund Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- After months of negotiations, 16 Germany companies  
that profited from Nazi-era slave labor announced details of a 
promised compensation fund Thursday, including a provision to pay 
victims living in eastern Europe less than those in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler AG, BMW AG and other major industrial concerns  
agreed to establish the fund under growing pressure from 
class-action suits in the United States on behalf of former slave 
laborers. 
</P>
<P>
	In announcing the fund, the 16 companies made clear that their  
intention is to quash the suits. 
</P>
<P>
	However, reacting to the plan in a news conference in Munich,  
one of the leading lawyers in the suits, Edward Fagan of New York 
City, indicated that he was not satisfied with the plan presented 
by industry and said he will press on with legal action. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies worked out details of the fund during months of  
negotiations led by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's chief of staff 
Bodo Hombach. Hombach met two days ago with industry leaders to 
help draft the plan presented Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Further details -- including the value of the fund and the timing  
of the payments -- will be decided in coming weeks during meetings 
with U.S. and German officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said they will make payments to forced laborers  
who worked for six months or more, and that claims will be honored 
in part based on need. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of the lump-sum payments will be based on the average  
pensions in the claimant's home country -- accounting for the lower 
payments in poorer eastern European nations than in the United 
States, Canada and other western nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said they were establishing a foundation,  
``Remembrance, Responsibility and the Future,'' to administer the 
fund. 
</P>
<P>
	A second foundation will be established to pay for people who  
worked in agriculture and for German municipalities, and for former 
prisoners of war. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
