<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- How hot is it?  
</P>
<P>
	No, it's not the opening line to a joke, it's a common question  
at the Stanley Cup finals in Dallas. It's not about the temperature 
on the streets, which is warm enough, it's about the temperature 
within Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Players have been talking about it, particularly Buffalo goalie  
Dominik Hasek. He said he was so exhausted from the heat at the 
conclusion of Game 1 Tuesday night that he could not skate across 
the ice to celebrate the 3-2 overtime victory with his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	The temperature during the day in Dallas was in the high '90s,  
and one league official said it could have been as high as the '70s 
inside the arena by the end of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL commissioner Gary Bettman said the league had chipped in  
with the Stars to purchase a new refrigeration unit. The players 
didn't notice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were concerned with dehydration with a lot of the players  
and obviously the goaltender wearing all the equipment he (is 
wearing) is probably the worst-case scenario,'' Sabres coach Lindy 
Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MATTER OF PERSPECTIVE:* Thursday night's Game 2 of the Stanley  
Cup finals marked the 99th game for the Buffalo Sabres since the 
start of the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	A long season? Not for Sabres captain Mike Peca.  
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people in the world work 11 1/2 months a year,'' Peca  
said. ``This is what we do. This is not a big deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLOSE CALLS:* Winning one-goal games in the playoffs is nothing  
new for the Buffalo Sabres. Their 3-2 overtime victory on Tuesday 
night improved their record to 7-0 in one-goal contests in the 
postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Stars are 6-5 in such games.  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *VEZINAS APLENTY:* This year's finals feature a rarity: two  
goaltenders who are multiple winners of the Vezina Trophy as the 
NHL's top goalie. Buffalo's Dominik Hasek has four and Dallas' Ed 
Belfour, two (not counting this season). 
</P>
<P>
	Multiple Vezina winners in the finals have occurred only one  
other time in NHL history -- in 1946 with Montreal's Bill Durnan and 
Boston's Frank Brimsek. They each had two. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SABRES' STAT:* The Buffalo Sabres continue to get outshot in  
the playoffs -- and continue to win. 
</P>
<P>
	In 16 games prior to Thursday night's Game 2, the Sabres had  
been outshot 10 times -- including 37-24 by Dallas on Tuesday night. 
The Sabres' record in those games: 9-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the Sabres had a playoff-best 13-3 record prior to  
Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *POWERLESS:* It might sound funny, but the Dallas Stars don't  
really like being on the power play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think maybe it gets us a little bit out of our rhythm,'' Joe  
Nieuwendyk says. ``We like to play five on five.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars were handed 10 power plays in Game 1 and managed to  
convert only one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously our power play is going to have to score a few more  
goals if we get that many opportunities,'' Nieuwendyk said before 
Thursday night's game. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WAITING GAME:* The fans started lining up early for tickets to  
Thursday night's game. One said he had been standing in line since 
11:30 a.m. in the humid Dallas weather, and the group had expanded 
considerably by 1 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	None of them knew when the box office would open, or if there  
were any tickets available. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope so,'' said one young woman who was sprawled on the  
concrete. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GOING GLOBAL:* The Stanley Cup finals gets around. It is being  
telecast live to most areas of the world, including Africa, the 
Caribbean, Central and South America, Asia and the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *A PROSPECT:* The top amateur goaltender available in this  
year's Entry Draft? He's Brian Finley, a rookie with the Barrie 
Colts of the Ontario Hockey League. 
</P>
<P>
	Finley appeared with other top prospects at a luncheon in the  
midst of the Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very focused, uses his stopper very well and does a good  
job pushing the puck into the corner,'' says Frank Bonello, who 
directs Central Scouting for the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Finley said he started out as a forward until switching to  
goaltender at age 9. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it helps my goaltending now,'' Finley said. ``To be a  
good goaltender, you have to be a good skater.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 14:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Delay Passenger Rights Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public relations collided with political  
reality Thursday, and airlines scrapped an announcement about their 
plans to improve customer service. Senate leaders had complained 
that they had not signed off on the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The sudden reversal left the head of United Airlines, Gerald  
Greenwald, with the chore of standing before a roomful of reporters 
and announcing that a news conference called to unveil the proposal 
was being postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the coming days we will be working to refine and improve  
our plan in conjunction with Sen. John McCain and other leading 
members of the House and Senate,'' said Greenwald, who also serves 
as chairman of the airline's trade group, the Air Transport 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Without taking questions, he disappeared behind the closed doors  
of the association's board room, where the nation's other top 
airline executives were waiting. 
</P>
<P>
	While the announcement triggered embarrassment among airline  
executives and chuckling on Capitol Hill, the parties agreed on a 
central point: The nation's major airlines and senators who have 
been complaining about the way they treat passengers are close to 
agreeing on a voluntary plan that would stave off congressional 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the package would be increased compensation for lost  
luggage, a promise to give passengers basic amenities when there 
are long on-board flight delays and a pledge to respond quickly to 
passenger complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The elements are drawn from several bills filed by the House,  
the Senate and the Clinton administration after passenger 
complaints peaked over the New Year's holiday, when thousands of 
travelers were stranded at Midwest airports following a snowstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest Airlines came under particularly harsh criticism for  
holding passengers for hours on one jet in Detroit despite a lack 
of food and water and an overflowing toilet. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations with the airlines have been led by McCain, R-Ariz.,  
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee and co-sponsor of one of 
the passenger rights bills. Also participating have been McCain's 
co-sponsor, Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., along with Sens. Slade Gorton, 
R-Wash., Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and 
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties had planned to hold a news conference on Capitol  
Hill to make a joint announcement, but that was scrapped Wednesday 
after airline haggling over details. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Air Transport Association announced that a  
consensus had been reached and it scheduled a midday news 
conference. The timing was driven by the fact that the executives 
were in town for their quarterly meeting. When the appointed hour 
arrived, however, Greenwald announced the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for several senators said support for the airline plan  
evaporated as senators read a headline in The Wall Street Journal 
saying the airlines were near an agreement with the White House. 
The headline bothered the senators because the Clinton 
administration had not been involved in the negotiations, the 
spokesmen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several senators also said they wanted tougher language on  
several points, including policies on handling lost baggage, 
accommodating passengers who get ``bumped'' despite confirmed 
reservations and public notifications when there are flight delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Marshall, a spokesman for Rockefeller, said an agreement was  
still possible despite the postponement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a good start and we're continuing to work with  
the airlines to get something done here that will be in the best 
interests of passengers,'' he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990610.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Resistance Members To Be Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five former members of CIA-backed Iraqi  
resistance groups jailed for 2 1/2 years will be released while they 
seek asylum in another country, the Immigration and Naturalization 
Service said. 
</P>
<P>
	The men belonged to two groups supported by the CIA as part of a  
U.S. effort to overthrow or weaken Saddam Hussein after the 1991 
Gulf War. When Saddam's troops swept through northern Iraq, 
thousands of opposition fighters and their families were evacuated 
by the U.S. military. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the men were detained by the United States. An  
immigration judge denied them asylum in March 1998 and ordered them 
deported, saying they were security risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement signed Thursday, five of the men will accept  
the deportation order and withdraw any appeals, said Russ Bergeron, 
spokesman for the INS in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	A sixth Iraqi rejected the agreement and will remain in custody.  
</P>
<P>
	The agreement was expected to be filed at immigration court  
early Friday, said Niels Frenzen, the attorney for the six men. 
</P>
<P>
	If the agreement is approved, the men will be able to join their  
families in Nebraska but will be under house arrest until granted 
asylum elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
