<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins' Owner Late for Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Running late, Daniel Snyder missed the first  
hour of his first practice as presumptive owner of the Washington 
Redskins. That didn't stop him from making some strong 
first-impression judgments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously some players are heavy and not where they need to  
be,'' Snyder said. ``We're going to fix that. And I could sense 
there are probably a few that don't want to play. Otherwise they're 
doing great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder's visit, during Thursday morning's voluntary minicamp,  
was his first appearance at Redskin Park since his $800 million 
offer to buy the team was approved May 25 by NFL owners. He is 
expected to close the sale later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Snyder has been quiet about his plans for the team. His  
only firm position has been that he plans to retain the Redskins 
name despite objections from some Native American groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Like every other owner, Snyder says he wants to win, although  
his timetable seems to have shifted. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, he said the Redskins were a rebuilding team. Now, he  
sees them as playoff-bound right away -- even though they are young 
and haven't been in the postseason since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is the year we make the playoffs,'' Snyder said.  
``And this is the year we show Washington that we respect the fans 
and show we're committed. It's always important to win in every 
thing I do. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to step up the heat and the pressure.''  
</P>
<P>
	During the NFL approval process, Snyder promised to retain coach  
Norv Turner and general manager Charley Casserly for what amounts 
to a one-year trial. However, he must also name a team president to 
run the operation on a day-to-day basis. Snyder is too busy with 
his local communications empire to take the role himself -- he 
couldn't even get through watching practice Thursday without his 
cellular phone ringing with other business. 
</P>
<P>
	After practice, Snyder addressed the players briefly, discussing  
with them his passion to win and telling them not to be fooled by 
his age. At 34, Snyder is the youngest majority owner in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder then spoke for 30 minutes with cornerback Darrell Green,  
who is five years older than his new boss. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very positive, in terms of an owner, that the guy knows  
business and knows how to be successful,'' Green said. ``He doesn't 
see us as horses. He is seeing with a passion that goes back to his 
childhood.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
