<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Works on Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans and Democrats on a key House  
committee agreed Thursday to begin working on a compromise to 
safeguard Social Security, a sign that efforts to overhaul the 
retirement program are not dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the Ways and Means Committee, said  
the panel would hold a series of meetings behind closed doors ``to 
discuss areas of common ground'' and possibly prepare a draft bill 
for further action. 
</P>
<P>
	In an impassioned speech to the committee, the Texas Republican  
said both political parties must put aside partisan considerations 
to ensure that Social Security remains solvent as the huge baby 
boom generation retires. The program is healthy now, but faces 
insolvency by 2034. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can prove that a democracy can address a difficult problem  
far ahead of the drop-dead date,'' Archer said. ``We can prove, 
perhaps for the first time, that we don't have to wait until we're 
at the edge of the cliff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's top Democrat, Rep. Charles Rangel of New York,  
agreed that private committee sessions would be the only way to 
``find out not how far apart we are, but how close are we?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It would enhance the respect and support of both Democrats and  
Republicans ... if we could come together in a bipartisan way,'' 
Rangel said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said President  
Clinton commended Archer and Rangel for ``working in a constructive 
way'' on Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a vast contrast to some of the other Republican leaders  
who have pronounced Social Security reform ... dead for the year 
for political reasons,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides still face long odds in reaching agreement on fixing  
Social Security, traditionally one of the most sensitive political 
issues. Clinton has proposed a plan that not all Democrats embrace, 
and GOP leaders haven't endorsed an alternative developed by Archer 
and Rep. E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Multiple political considerations complicate any attempt at  
compromise, including control of the House in 2000 and Vice 
President Al Gore's campaign for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats believe that cooperating with Republicans to fix  
Social Security only enhances the GOP in voters' eyes, while 
Republicans worry they could be hammered by Clinton and the 
Democrats if they push their own overhaul plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has encouraged the  
Ways and Means Committee to move forward. And Archer met last week 
with the House Democratic leader, Rep. Richard Gephardt of 
Missouri, and assured him that Democrats would be not be left out 
as legislation is developed. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as they're not talking about dismantling the program,  
we're willing to look at ways to reach a workable solution,'' said 
Gephardt spokeswoman Laura Nichols. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
