<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 15:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canoeist's Profanity Trial Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STANDISH, Mich. (AP) -- A man went on trial Thursday on charges  
he shouted a blue streak in front of women and children when he was 
dumped from his canoe on the Rifle River. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy Joseph Boomer, 25, faces a possible 90 days in jail and  
a $100 fine if convicted of violating an 1897 law that bans 
profanity in the presence of women and children. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about criminalizing ordinary, day-to-day speech  
-- language that just about everybody in the country has used 
personally from time to time,'' said defense attorney William 
Street, handling the case on behalf of the American Civil Liberties 
Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Boomer does not deny he let off steam, but said he didn't see  
anyone but his friends and that his shouts were in jest. He denies 
using the four-letter obscenities that police allege. 
</P>
<P>
	Boomer, a factory worker from the Detroit suburb of Roseville,  
was with a group of friends last August on the river about 130 
miles north of Detroit when his canoe hit a rock. 
</P>
<P>
	He tumbled out and yelled a series of obscenities within earshot  
of a woman and children in another boat, said former sheriff's 
Deputy Kenneth Socia, who was patrolling the river and ticketed 
Boomer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone should be able to have a good time on the river, and  
it shouldn't be (disrupted) ... by other people intoxicated, 
swearing,'' Socia testified Thursday. ``I'm sitting there writing a 
ticket, and he's yelling at me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police began patrolling the river last summer after  
representatives of campgrounds, liveries and property owners 
complained that drunken, rowdy boaters were getting out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Ladd White, a local businessman said he hoped Boomer would be  
convicted so people realize that morals and respect are still 
important. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's been the downfall of societies in the past. Maybe this  
will send a message that morality does matter,'' White said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
