<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serb Troops Leaving Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav troops began to rumble out  
of Kosovo in trucks, armored cars and buses Thursday, prompting 
NATO to suspend its punishing 78-day air war and the United Nations 
to authorize a heavily armed security force to restore peace and 
begin reconstruction. NATO troops massed in neighboring Macedonia 
to begin the peacekeeping mission, with the first soldiers ready to 
enter Kosovo as early as Friday. The force would also ensure the 
safe return of 860,000 refugees driven from their homes. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Claims Victory in Air War  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton claimed victory in the NATO  
air war against Yugoslavia today as American ground troops moved 
toward Kosovo to protect the return home of ethnic Albanian 
refugees. ``We have to finish the job and build the peace,'' he 
said. Euphoria swept through the White House at the successful 
conclusion of an 11-week conflict that had brought biting criticism 
and doubts about Clinton's handling of the showdown with Yugoslav 
leader Slobodan Milosevic. Clinton said the Serb retreat was a 
vindication for America's fighting forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, GOP Reach Deal on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House gave divided blessings today to a  
peacekeeping operation in Kosovo after Republicans extracted a 
written promise from President Clinton that it could be performed 
``without harming military readiness.'' On a 270-155 vote, the 
House removed from a $288.8 billion defense spending bill a 
GOP-drafted provision that would have barred U.S. funds from being 
used in Kosovo after Sept. 30. The vote came moments after Clinton 
promised to seek congressional authorization for an international 
peacekeeping force expected to include 7,000 Americans. 

</P>
<P>
	New Air Bags May Fail Crash Test  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's three largest automakers say  
their latest, less forceful air bags -- designed to reduce injuries 
to small adults and children -- cannot pass a proposed government 
crash test standard that the automakers say is too tough. Federal 
safety officials have proposed reinstating a crash test standard 
that requires an air bag to cushion an unbelted dummy when a 
vehicle is driven into a wall at 30 mph. But the automakers argue 
that air bags will have to be made more powerful again which will 
increase the chances that children and short adults will be injured 
in all types of crashes. 

</P>
<P>
	America's Health Said Improving  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Americans are eating more fruits and vegetables,  
seeing the dentist more often, and dying less frequently from 
breast cancer. But obesity -- among children especially -- has 
reached epidemic proportions, the surgeon general said today. 
Overall, the health of Americans has improved in the decade since 
the government released its Healthy People 2000 goals -- a blueprint 
of more than 300 health objectives, from reducing smoking to 
increasing seat belt use. 

</P>
<P>
	Gene Map May Be Completed by 2002  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A project to completely map the human  
genetic pattern could be complete by 2002, a year earlier than last 
predicted. Researchers around the world trying to catalog all of 
the 60,000 to 90,000 genes in human DNA are making rapid progress 
that could bump up the completion date. Identifying all the human 
genes will make it possible to treat or prevent cancer, inherited 
disorders and some diseases, experts say. 

</P>
<P>
	TBS To Launch Women's Channel  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Turner Broadcasting System is teaming up with  
two major magazine publishers to launch a cable television channel 
aimed at women, going up against the already successful Lifetime 
channel. The new channel will be launched together with an 
accompanying Web site early next year. The companies said the new 
channel would draw material from style, entertainment, travel, food 
and parenting articles in the various magazines published by Conde 
Nast and Time. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 69.02  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as good economic news for  
Japan increased Wall Street's fears that the unfettered growth of 
the U.S. economy will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates. At the close, the Dow industrials were down 69.02 at 
10,621.27. Declining issues on the NYSE outnumbered advances 
2,052-937. The technology-heavy Nasdaq was down 34.75 at 2,484.60. 

</P>
<P>
	Is Another Comeback in the Stars?  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars are used to making comebacks in  
playoff games; now they'll try to do it in a series. Trailing 1-0 
in the Stanley Cup finals, the Stars face another test in their 
postseason adventure story when they meet the Buffalo Sabres 
tonight in Game 2 at Reunion Arena. The Stars have made a habit of 
comebacks in the postseason, rallying to win five times when 
trailing at some point in the third period. That has tied an NHL 
record. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
  	   	
