<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Curbs Out-of-Court Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court limited the use during  
criminal trials of out-of-court statements by alleged accomplices 
who admit some wrongdoing but try to blame the defendant for the 
crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's divided ruling Thursday revived a Virginia death row  
inmate's challenge of his conviction for shooting a man to death 
during a carjacking. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Lee Lilly says his conviction was invalid because  
prosecutors were allowed to tell jurors his brother, Mark, admitted 
some involvement in the crime to police but blamed the killing on 
Lilly. Mark Lilly refused to testify during his brother's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In the court's main opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said the  
use of Mark Lilly's confession during Lilly's trial violated his 
constitutional right to confront the witnesses against him. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Lilly's confession could not be considered ``sufficiently  
reliable as to be admissible without allowing (Lilly) to 
cross-examine him,'' Stevens wrote, adding that Lilly's brother 
``had a natural motive to attempt to exculpate himself as much as 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision appeared to break little new ground. Stevens also  
noted the court previously has ruled accomplices' statements that 
shift blame to a defendant generally are not considered so 
trustworthy they can be used in court without cross-examination. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Willis of the American Civil Liberties Union of Virginia  
said, ``The Supreme Court is simply re-embracing one of the 
fundamental principles of criminal justice, and that is the right 
to face your accuser.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All nine justices voted to reverse the Virginia Supreme Court's  
decision that upheld Lilly's conviction. The justices also ordered 
a lower court to determine whether the error could be considered 
harmless and Lilly's conviction still could be upheld. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices split on their rationale.  
</P>
<P>
	Justices David H. Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G.  
Breyer agreed with Stevens that accomplices' confessions that 
incriminate a defendant generally cannot be used as evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Scalia agreed the constitutional violation in Lilly's case was  
``clear'' but did not join the main opinion's rationale. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day  
O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas said the 
Constitution did not create a blanket ban on the use of 
accomplices' confessions that incriminate a defendant. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles L. Hobson of the Criminal Justice Legal Foundation,  
which supported Virginia prosecutors in the case, called the ruling 
``a poor decision that reflects the current confusion about the 
confrontation clause'' in the Constitution's Sixth Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilly was convicted of the 1995 shooting death of Alexander  
DeFilippis at a rural convenience store near Heathwood, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Lilly shot DeFilippis during a carjacking. At  
Lilly's trial, co-defendant Gary Wayne Barker testified against him 
and said Lilly fired the fatal shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Lilly, who was charged in connection with the carjacking,  
refused to testify based on his Fifth Amendment privilege against 
self-incrimination. But prosecutors were allowed to tell jurors 
about Mark Lilly's confession to police. 
</P>
<P>
	The Virginia Supreme Court ruled the confession could be used.  
It should be considered reliable, the state court said, because 
Mark Lilly spoke against his own interest and because it was 
supported by Barker's testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's highest court said the Virginia court was wrong.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
