<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sets Aside Media Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal appeals court has reversed its ruling  
that ordered NBC television to turn over a videotape that was made 
but never used in a story about Louisiana state police. 
</P>
<P>
	The tape, made for an NBC ``Dateline'' segment, was demanded by  
lawyers for a Hispanic couple who are suing a Louisiana deputy 
sheriff, alleging civil rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals had ruled in September that NBC  
had to hand over the videotape, which shows an officer pulling over 
a car. NBC was investigating whether police were acting based on 
race, nationality or out-of-state plates. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for NBC argued the First Amendment provided qualified  
privilege on material reporters get from nonconfidential sources. 
The court found otherwise, and the ruling was seen as making it 
easier for lawyers to obtain unpublished notes and videotapes from 
journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	But the court vacated its ruling June 1, saying it may need to  
rehear the issue. It instructed lower court judges to stop using 
the September ruling as a precedent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking forward to further illumination of the issue  
from the Court of Appeals,'' said Susan Weiner, a lawyer for NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly from the journalist's perspective, the law in the  
circuit prior to this decision has appeared to recognize greater 
protection for journalist's work products, notes and tapes,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists have already reaped a benefit from the June 1 order.  
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the appeals court vacated a contempt finding  
involving The Wall Street Journal that was based on the September 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	In that case, a lower court judge refused to let Dow Jones &AMP;  
Co., publisher of the Journal, quash a subpoena for a reporter's 
notes. The subpoena was lodged by defendants in a securities action 
brought by stockholders of Centennial Technologies Inc. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
