<HEADLINE> Forbes Rails Against New $20 Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Multimillionaire Steve Forbes is adding a new  
plank to his campaign platform, pledging that if he is elected 
president, ``We will have money that looks real again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to about 100 members of the Greater Des Moines Chamber  
of Commerce meeting in Washington, Forbes railed against the new 
$20 bills, which he said ``look like Monopoly money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something that's going to change when a certain person  
leaves the White House,'' Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chamber of Commerce group, which represents 2,100 businesses  
in central Iowa, is a crucial constituency to Forbes' second bid 
for the Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks Thursday centered on his plan to rescue Social  
Security funds from politicians ``who want to put their paws on 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eliciting the only applause of his 20-minute speech, Forbes  
evoked the same bears-to-honey imagery he used in the first 
installment of a $10 million television advertising campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans, he said, should be able to invest up to three-fourths  
of their Social Security taxes in private accounts, out of the 
reach of politicians in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should show some compassion,'' he said to applause. ``Don't  
tempt these creatures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes and other candidates are pushing the Social Security  
theme in a battle for the growing pot of voters over 60. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls show that elderly voters are richer, better educated, more  
mobile, more likely to vote and increasingly more Republican than 
30 years ago. Though President Clinton won the over-60 vote in 1992 
and 1996, seniors voted Republican 54 percent to 43 percent in the 
1998 midterm elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
