<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia, NATO Sign Kosovo Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes,  
Yugoslav forces prepare to withdraw from Kosovo today as part of a 
peace deal signed by Yugoslav and Western generals to end the war 
over Kosovo. U.S. Marines in amphibious vehicles landed on the 
shores of northern Greece today, part of a vanguard force ready to 
enter Kosovo to bring peace to the province that 860,000 ethnic 
Albanians have fled since March. In the Yugoslav capital of 
Belgrade, residents honked car horns and set off firecrackers to 
celebrate the signing of a peace deal late Wednesday and what state 
media said was the first night without NATO air attacks in 2 1/2 
months. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Premier Warns Lawmakers  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin warned lawmakers  
today that he might threaten their jobs if they failed to approve a 
package of economic austerity bills. Stepashin said he might call a 
confidence vote in his new Cabinet. If lawmakers vote 
no-confidence, then President Boris Yeltsin could disband the lower 
house, the State Duma, and call new elections -- a prospect 
lawmakers want to avoid. Communist and hard-line lawmakers, fearing 
a backlash from the public, have been resisting quick action on a 
series of bills that would introduce new taxes. 

</P>
<P>
	Brain Damage-Cancer Defense Linked  
</P>
<P>
	Testicular cancer can lead to seizures, memory loss and dementia  
long before the cancer is detected, researchers reported today in 
the third study to link brain damage to an immune system attack on 
cancer. The brain damage apparently is caused not by the cancer 
itself, but by an overly aggressive attack by body's own immune 
system on a protein produced by tumors, the researchers said. In 
today's New England Journal of Medicine, researchers said men with 
testicular cancer and damage to one of the brain's emotional 
centers had a particular type of antibody in their blood. 

</P>
<P>
	New Drugs Blamed in 'Sleep Attacks'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two new drugs for Parkinson's disease may  
cause narcolepsy-like ``sleep attacks,'' according to doctors who 
say eight of their patients were in auto accidents after the drugs 
abruptly put them to sleep. The Food and Drug Administration is 
talking with the manufacturers about whether the drugs need 
additional warning labels. Dr. Steven Frucht of 
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York, who reported the 
eight cases in the journal Neurology, said Parkinson's patients 
should not overreact to the warning and stop taking the drugs, 
which can be very helpful for treating Parkinson's symptoms. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Emphasizes Christian Unity  
</P>
<P>
	SIEDLCE, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II will meet today with  
Orthodox Christians during a trip to eastern Poland. Orthodox 
Christian Churches and the Roman Catholic Church have been 
separated since the Great Schism in 1054 in a dispute over papal 
authority and interpretation of their creed. The dispute is rooted 
in a decision by Emperor Constantine in 330 to move the capital of 
the Roman Empire to Byzantium, later Constantinople. John Paul, the 
head of the Roman Catholic Church, is emphasizing Christian unity 
and religious pluralism during his 13-day pilgrimage to his 
homeland. 

</P>
<P>
	Slow Count Arouses Suspicion in Indonesia  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Police tightened security around  
Jakarta today as a slow election vote count aroused anxiety that 
Indonesia's long tradition of vote-rigging was again plaguing the 
country. Election officials denied any improprieties, saying they 
have been swamped by the 113 million votes cast in Monday's 
parliamentary election, billed as the country's most democratic 
vote in 44 years. By today, unofficial results released to 
journalists showed that 8.2 percent of the votes had been 
tabulated, a fraction of what had been promised. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Advance  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks today jumped on optimism that the  
nation's economic recovery was picking up. The Nikkei surged 480.12 
points, closing the day's trading at 17,102.62. 

</P>
<P>
	Rockies 16, Mariners 11  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. hit his major league-leading 23rd  
home run, but the Colorado Rockies hit six homers and beat the 
Seattle Mariners 16-11 in a game delayed more than three hours by 
rain last night. Play was stopped for 3 hours, 18 minutes after 
Seattle scored three runs in the top of the seventh to cut 
Colorado's lead to 11-10. The teams combined for 10 home runs. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 7, Rangers 2  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kevin Brown pitched eight strong innings to  
improve his home record to 5-0 and Eric Karros snapped a scoreless 
tie with a three-run homer last night, leading the Los Angeles 
Dodgers to a 7-2 victory over the Texas Rangers. Brown struck out 
six and allowed five hits, including a bases-loaded two-run single 
by Rusty Greer in the fifth inning after being staked to a 6-0 
lead. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
