<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coke Recalls 2.5M Bottles in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co.'s Belgian branch recalled  
2.5 million bottles of Coca-Cola after several children fell ill 
after drinking the the popular beverage at school. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, 31 pupils in northern Belgium were hospitalized  
after drinking from Coca-Cola bottles that came from a batch of 2.5 
million bottles produced last week in Antwerp. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysis by the company found that some of the bottles had a  
quality defect, which can lead to symptoms such as headaches, 
nausea and stomach cramps. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a quality issue where you have an off odor or taste,  
which you can get from consuming one or more Cokes,'' Coca-Cola 
spokeswoman Maureen O'Sullivan said Thursday. ``But there was no 
intoxication found.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a safety precaution, Coca-Cola has blocked all the bottles at  
point of sale and is presently trying to recall all the bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Sullivan said that the incident at a school on Bornem appears  
to be an isolated case but added ``we're taking this seriously, we 
want to avoid any risks for our consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soft drink company dispatched a team of researchers to the  
school on Tuesday after several students were hospitalized after 
drinking Coca-Cola with their lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Samples of the bottles were then sent to Coca-Cola laboratories  
in Brussels and Atlanta, as well as to an independent team in the 
Netherlands. O'Sullivan said the scientists, who will be running 
several tests, have found no traces of toxins. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors confirmed our tests, nothing could be found in the  
blood samples,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta-based Coca-Cola has been active in Belgium for the past  
70 years and has large bottling operations in Antwerp and Ghent. 
The U.S. company's European headquarters are also based in 
Brussels. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
