<DOCNO> APW19990610.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-10 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Pushes Europe, Japan on Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While saying that the risks of a global  
recession have diminished, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin stressed 
today that it still is ``critically important'' for Japan and 
Europe to do everything possible to boost economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said a Saturday meeting of finance ministers of the  
world's seven richest industrial countries would focus on 
coordinating strategies to promote growth as well as prepare the 
financial agenda for next week's annual economic summit meeting of 
leaders of the seven nations. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton and the leaders of Japan, Germany, France,  
Britain, Italy and Canada are expected to endorse actions already 
under way to promote greater disclosure of financial data by 
developing countries so foreign investors are not taken by 
surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	But the package of measures is expected to fall far short of  
some of the sweeping proposals for overhaul of the global financial 
architecture in the wake of a currency crisis that plunged 
one-third of the world into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Market turbulence last fall after Russia defaulted on billions  
of dollars of foreign loans sent stock prices crashing around the 
world and raised concerns of a global recession. However, the 
Federal Reserve stepped in and engineered a series of interest rate 
cuts that restored investor confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said the risk of a global recession stemming from the  
Asian currency crisis is now ``substantially diminished'' from what 
it had been last fall. But there is no room for complacency, he 
added, especially since the United States has the only major 
economy performing well. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin cautioned against reading too much into recent signs that  
Japan may finally be emerging from its worst recession in 50 years. 
He said both Japan and Europe, where growth has slowed, need to 
continue pursuing growth policies, in part to help relieve pressure 
on a soaring U.S. trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	It is ``critically important that Europe and Japan do their part  
because the international system cannot sustain indefinitely the 
large imbalances created by the disparities in growth and openness 
between the United States and its major trading partners,'' Rubin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin had expressed worries during a speech Wednesday that  
America's record trade deficits were spawning rising protectionist 
pressures that if unleashed could harm not only the U.S. economy 
but the fragile global recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to the Bretton Woods Committee, Rubin echoed many of  
the points made by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan during 
two recent addresses in which he also decried an increase of 
protectionist sentiment being spawned by record U.S. trade 
deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said last week that free trade had raised living  
standards around the world and efforts to erect new barriers could 
do ``great harm'' to the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin said he was particularly concerned about a drive in  
Congress to impose quotas on foreign steel shipments into the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the proposal, which passed the House by a 2-1 margin in  
March, threatened to set off a devastating chain-reaction of trade 
protectionism in other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. steel companies have argued that they need the stiff quotas  
to prevent thousands of American layoffs. But the administrations 
contends the bill clearly violates global trading rules 
administered by the World Trade Organization and would trigger 
copycat protectionist moves by other countries against American 
exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``That bill could well pass the Senate, and such action in the  
strongest major economy in the world creates a real risk of 
strengthening the already increased protectionist pressure being 
felt around the world,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, who support the steel quota  
measure, said Rubin needs to understand that ``free trade does not 
mean free to subsidize, free to dump or free to distort the market. 
Ohio Valley steel has suffered long enough from dumping. Senate 
action is long overdue.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
